    },
    {
        "id": 1075,
        "text": "<p>Opening Accounts Receivable 50k, Sales 80k, BD 4k. New Prov 10%. Closing Net Accounts Receivable?</p>",
        "meta": "Ideal Sch",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "50k",
            "1,13,400 TK",
            "80k",
            "1L"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>(50k+80k\u22124k)=126,000 TK. Net: 126k\u2212(126k\u00d710%)=1,13,400 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1076,
        "text": "<p>(Ref #137) Amount of Bad Debt Expense?</p>",
        "meta": "Ideal Sch",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "12.6k",
            "16.6k",
            "14.6k",
            "18.6k"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>(4,000 TK\u00a0BD+12,600 TK\u00a0New)\u22122,000 TK\u00a0Old=14,600 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1077,
        "text": "<p>Accounts Receivable 4L, New Bad Debt (BD) 40k. What is the 5% Provision?</p>",
        "meta": "DCC",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "60k",
            "58k",
            "40k",
            "18k"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>(4,00,000 TK\u221240,000 TK)\u00d75%=18,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1078,
        "text": "<p>Based on #141: (i) Asset \u2193 58k (ii) Profit \u2191 58k (iii) Profit \u2193 58k</p>",
        "meta": "DCC",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Total impact = 40,000 TK(BD)+18,000 TK(Prov)=58,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1079,
        "text": "<p>Which expense does NOT require cash outflow?</p>",
        "meta": "Bogra",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Bad Debt",
            "Salary",
            "Commission",
            "Insurance"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Bad Debt (\u0985\u09a8\u09be\u09a6\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09c0 \u09aa\u09be\u0993\u09a8\u09be) is a non-cash expense.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1080,
        "text": "<p>What is Bad Debt?</p>",
        "meta": "Bogra",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Irrecoverable part",
            "Future collection",
            "Possible loss",
            "Provision"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>The specific portion of Accounts Receivable that will never be recovered.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1081,
        "text": "<p>Bad Debt Provision is an\u2014</p>",
        "meta": "General",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Est. Income",
            "Certain Profit",
            "Advance Arrangement",
            "Certain Loss"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>It is an Advance Arrangement (\u0986\u0997\u09be\u09ae \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac\u09b8\u09cd\u09a5\u09be) for future risks.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1082,
        "text": "<p>Must increase Prov by 2k. Old Prov 4k. New Prov?</p>",
        "meta": "Cox's",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "2k",
            "3k",
            "6k",
            "7k"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>4,000 TK(Old)+2,000 TK(Increase)=6,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1083,
        "text": "<p>If Opening Prov was 6k (instead of 4k), what happens to BS?</p>",
        "meta": "Cox's",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "\u2193 Asset 8k",
            "\u2191 Liability 6k",
            "\u2191 Asset&Liability 2k",
            "\u2193 Asset&Liability 2k"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Higher provision reduces net assets and equity by the difference (2k).</p>"
    }
            ],
            shortCQData: [],
            fullCQData: []
        },
        "7": {
            subjectName: "Accounting 1st Paper",
            chapterName: "Chapter 7 : Work Sheet",
            mcqData: [
{
        "id": 1084,
        "text": "<p>The accounting period for preparing a worksheet can be\u2014\n\ni. One year\n\nii. One month\n\niii. Six months</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Asset worksheet can be prepared for any duration (monthly, quarterly, or yearly) depending on management needs.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1085,
        "text": "<p>Which one is a Capital Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Salary expense",
            "Ship rent",
            "Purchase of asset",
            "Purchase of goods"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Expenditures that provide long-term benefits, such as buying fixed assets, are capital expenditures.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1086,
        "text": "<p>Closing entries are given to\u2014\n\ni. Close nominal accounts\n\nii. Close permanent accounts\n\niii. Close drawing accounts</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Closing entries transfer balances of nominal (income/expense) and drawing accounts to zero; permanent accounts are not closed.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1087,
        "text": "<p>Examples of capital expenditure are\u2014\n\ni. Purchase of plant\n\nii. Plant installation cost\n\niii. Plant repair cost</p>",
        "meta": "Barishal  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Asset purchase and installation are capital costs. General repairs are considered revenue expenditures.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1088,
        "text": "<p>When are reversing entries provided?</p>",
        "meta": "Barishal  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Start of accounting period",
            "End of accounting period",
            "Mid-accounting period",
            "Start of next accounting year"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Reversing entries are made on the first day of the new period to simplify the recording of subsequent transactions.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1089,
        "text": "<p>Which one is a Capital Income?</p>",
        "meta": "Barishal  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Interest income",
            "Received rent",
            "Share premium",
            "Received discount"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Share premium is a non-recurring receipt from a long-term source, making it capital in nature.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1090,
        "text": "<p>Asset worksheet can be of\u2014\n\ni. 10 columns\n\nii. 12 columns\n\niii. 14 columns</p>",
        "meta": "Barishal  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>While 8, 10, and 12 columns are standard, 14-column worksheets are used when extra data is required.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1091,
        "text": "<p>What type of expense is Research and Development?</p>",
        "meta": "Barishal  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Capital",
            "Revenue",
            "Deferred revenue",
            "Operating"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Expenses that provide benefits over several years but are revenue in nature are called deferred revenue expenditures.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1092,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a Revenue Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Insurance of machine",
            "Installation cost of machine",
            "VAT on machine purchase",
            "Transport cost of machine"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Insurance is a recurring operating cost, whereas the others are part of the asset's cost (capital).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1093,
        "text": "<p>Money received from selling old furniture is\u2014</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Total income",
            "Revenue income",
            "Capital receipt",
            "Capital income"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>The entire amount received from selling a fixed asset is a capital receipt.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1094,
        "text": "<p>What is the total Service Revenue? (Based on stem)</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "37,000 TK",
            "64,000 TK",
            "67,000 TK",
            "88,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Service Revenue 50,000 TK + Accrued 5,000 TK + Earned portion of Unearned 9,000 TK (16,000 TK-7,000 TK) = 64,000 TK</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1095,
        "text": "<p>If 1/4 of Unearned Revenue is earned, what is the Net Service Revenue?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "88,000 TK",
            "67,000 TK",
            "66,000 TK",
            "59,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>50,000 TK (Revenue) + 5,000 TK (Accrued) + 4,000 TK (1/4 of 16,000 TK) = 59,000 TK</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1096,
        "text": "<p>Amortization of leasehold property is\u2014</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Capital Income",
            "Capital Expenditure",
            "Revenue Income",
            "Revenue Expenditure"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Annual wear and tear or expiration of a fixed asset's value is treated as a revenue expense.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1097,
        "text": "<p>Which one is a Capital Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Machine installation cost",
            "Furniture repair",
            "Purchase of goods",
            "Rent payment"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Installation increases asset value and capacity, qualifying as capital expenditure.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1098,
        "text": "<p>Which entry makes the balance of income-expense accounts zero?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Closing entry",
            "Opening entry",
            "Rectifying entry",
            "Reversing entry"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Closing entries transfer nominal account balances to the Income Summary to reset them for the next period.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1099,
        "text": "<p>Through which entry are revenue accounts closed?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Opening entry",
            "Adjusting entry",
            "Reversing entry",
            "Closing entry"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Nominal (revenue/expense) accounts are always closed using closing entries at year-end.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1100,
        "text": "<p>Which entry is given at the end of the period for accrued income, unearned income, etc.?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Closing entry",
            "Rectifying entry",
            "Adjusting entry",
            "Reversing entry"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Adjusting entries ensure the matching principle is followed by recording revenues and expenses in the correct period.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1101,
        "text": "<p>When unearned income is adjusted, what happens?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Income increases, Liability decreases",
            "Asset increases, Income decreases",
            "Asset increases, Income increases",
            "Asset increases, Liability decreases"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>As unearned revenue is earned, the liability is removed and recognized as actual income.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1102,
        "text": "<p>Closing entries are provided for\u2014\n\ni. Closing nominal accounts\n\nii. Closing drawing accounts\n\niii. Closing permanent accounts</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Only temporary accounts (nominal and drawings) are closed. Assets, liabilities, and equity (permanent) remain.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1103,
        "text": "<p>Which one is an optional step in the accounting cycle?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Worksheet",
            "Journal",
            "Ledger",
            "Financial Statements"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>While helpful for preparing final accounts, a worksheet is not a mandatory legal requirement of the cycle.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1104,
        "text": "<p>Where is \"Drawings\" shown in a worksheet?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Debit of Income Statement",
            "Credit of Income Statement",
            "Debit of Statement of Financial Position",
            "Credit of Statement of Financial Position"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Drawings reduce equity and are shown on the debit side of the Balance Sheet (Financial Position) columns.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1105,
        "text": "<p>Which account balance becomes zero after closing entries?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Insurance Premium",
            "Prepaid Rent",
            "Salaries Payable",
            "Accumulated Depreciation"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Insurance Premium is a nominal (expense) account, which is closed at year-end. Others are permanent/real accounts.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1106,
        "text": "<p>If goods are sold at cost (no profit), the effect is\u2014\n\ni. Expense decreases\n\nii. Income decreases\n\niii. Assets decrease</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Selling at cost reduces purchase (expense) and results in no profit/income. Asset (stock) simply changes to cash.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1107,
        "text": "<p>Examples of deferred expenses are\u2014\n\ni. Deferred Advertisement\n\nii. Research & Development\n\niii. Preliminary Expenses</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three are types of revenue expenditures whose benefits extend over multiple accounting periods.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1108,
        "text": "<p>When are reversing entries provided?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "1st day of accounting period",
            "Before adjusting entries",
            "Last day of accounting period",
            "Before preparing financial statements"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Reversing entries are traditionally recorded on the first day of the new accounting cycle.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1109,
        "text": "<p>Which entry is required to close revenue accounts?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Rectifying Journal",
            "Opening Journal",
            "Closing Journal",
            "Adjusting Journal"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Closing journals are specifically used to reset nominal accounts (income/expense) to zero.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1110,
        "text": "<p>Trial Balance shows Office Supplies 1,000 TK. Ending Supplies in adjustment is 600. The adjusting entry is\u2014</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh - 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Expense Debit 1000; Credit 1000",
            "Expense Debit 600; Credit 600",
            "Expense Debit 600; Credit 600",
            "Expense Debit 400; Credit 400"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>The used portion (1,000 TK - 600 = 400) is the expense. Journal: Supplies Expense Debit. 400, Office Supplies Credit. 400.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1111,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is considered an asset of the business?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Capital Receipt",
            "Revenue Receipt",
            "Capital Expenditure",
            "Revenue Expenditure"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Capital expenditures result in the acquisition of fixed assets, which provide long-term service.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1112,
        "text": "<p>Which one is a Capital Income?</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Sale of land",
            "Sale of goods",
            "Service revenue",
            "Commission income"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Selling land is a non-recurring event involving a fixed asset, resulting in a capital receipt/income.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1113,
        "text": "<p>What cannot be known from a worksheet?</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Net Profit",
            "Gross Profit",
            "Total Assets",
            "Total Liabilities"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>While a worksheet calculates Net Profit and identifies assets/liabilities, it doesn't typically isolate Gross Profit like a Trading Account.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1114,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is NOT in an 8-column worksheet?</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Trial Balance",
            "Adjustments",
            "Adjusted Trial Balance",
            "Income Statement"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>An 8-column worksheet skips the Adjusted Trial Balance column to save space.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1115,
        "text": "<p>If an adjusting entry for prepaid expense is omitted, what is the effect?</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Income \u2193, Asset \u2191",
            "Income \u2193, Asset \u2193",
            "Income \u2191, Asset \u2191",
            "Income \u2191, Asset \u2193"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Omitting the adjustment fails to recognize the expense (overstating income) and fails to reduce the asset (overstating assets).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1116,
        "text": "<p>Adjusting entries ensure\u2014\n\ni. Recognizing expense when incurred\n\nii. Recording revenue when earned\n\niii. Showing correct income statement</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Adjusting entries are the foundation of the accrual basis, ensuring all revenues and expenses are matched correctly.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1117,
        "text": "<p>Which account does NOT require a closing entry?</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Interest Income",
            "Sales Revenue",
            "Accumulated Depreciation",
            "Salary Expense"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Accumulated Depreciation is a contra-asset (permanent account), so it is not closed at year-end.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1118,
        "text": "<p>Which statement about the \"Accrual Basis of Accounting\" is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Presents wrong image",
            "Revenue recognized when earned",
            "Doesn't follow GAAP",
            "Recorded only when cash is received"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>The accrual basis recognizes revenue and expenses when they occur, regardless of when cash changes hands.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1119,
        "text": "<p>Which balance becomes zero after preparing closing entries?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Service Revenue",
            "Unearned Service Revenue",
            "Accumulated Depr.",
            "Prepaid Insurance"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Only nominal accounts like Service Revenue are zeroed out to the Income Summary.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1120,
        "text": "<p>When is a reversing entry made?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "1st day of period",
            "After adjustments",
            "Last day of period",
            "Before fin. statements"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>It is performed at the very beginning of a new period to reverse certain adjusting entries from the prior period.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1121,
        "text": "<p>What can be known through preparing a worksheet?\n\ni. Net profit or loss\n\nii. State of assets/Liabilities\n\niii. Account balances</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Asset worksheet summarizes the Trial Balance, Adjustments, Income Statement, and Balance Sheet all in one place.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1122,
        "text": "<p>Out of 900 commission received, if 100 is unearned, what is the revenue income?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "700 TK",
            "800 TK",
            "900 TK",
            "1000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Revenue Income = Total Received (900) - Unearned (100) = 800 TK</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1123,
        "text": "<p>When are reversing entries given?</p>",
        "meta": "Barishal  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Any time",
            "Start or end of any time",
            "End of a specific time",
            "Start of a specific time"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>They are specific to the start of a new accounting cycle/period.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1124,
        "text": "<p>Acquiring a fixed asset is called\u2014</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Capital Expenditure",
            "Revenue Expenditure",
            "Capital Receipt",
            "Revenue Income"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Costs incurred to acquire assets that provide long-term benefits are classified as capital expenditures.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1125,
        "text": "<p>The necessity of closing entries is to\u2014\n\ni. Close fixed asset accounts\n\nii. Close nominal accounts\n\niii. Close drawing accounts</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Closing entries reset temporary accounts (Income, Expense, Drawings) to zero; fixed assets (permanent) are never closed.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1126,
        "text": "<p>If the adjusting entry for accrued income is omitted\u2014\n\ni. Profit will be understated\n\nii. Income will be understated\n\niii. Equity will be understated</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Failing to record earned income results in lower reported profit, which in turn understates the owner's equity.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1127,
        "text": "<p>Which entry is required to close revenue and expense accounts?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Adjusting Journal",
            "Opening Journal",
            "Rectifying Journal",
            "Closing Journal"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Closing journals transfer nominal account balances to the Income Summary to prepare for the next period.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1128,
        "text": "<p>Which account requires a closing entry?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Drawings",
            "Capital",
            "Unearned Income",
            "Prepaid Insurance"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Drawings is a temporary account that must be closed against the Capital account at the end of the year.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1129,
        "text": "<p>What is a worksheet in a true sense?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Asset Journal",
            "Asset Ledger",
            "Asset Rough sheet (Draft)",
            "Asset Financial Statement"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Asset worksheet is an informal draft used by accountants to simplify the preparation of formal financial statements.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1130,
        "text": "<p>Which account balance becomes zero after providing closing entries?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Service Revenue",
            "Supplies",
            "Accumulated Depreciation",
            "Prepaid Insurance"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Service Revenue is a nominal account. Nominal accounts are the only ones zeroed out via closing entries.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1131,
        "text": "<p>Which one is different from the other three?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Apprentice Premium",
            "Apprentice Allowance",
            "Insurance Premium",
            "Utility Expense"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Apprentice Premium is an \"Income\" for the business, while the other three are \"Expenses.\"</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1132,
        "text": "<p>What is indicated by the adjustment of unearned income?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Asset \u2191 and Income \u2191",
            "Asset \u2193 and Income \u2193",
            "Liability \u2193 and Income \u2191",
            "Liability \u2191 and Income \u2193"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>When unearned income is earned, the liability (Unearned) decreases and the actual Revenue (Income) increases.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1133,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is an example of Revenue Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Import duty on machine",
            "Transport of machine",
            "Installation of machine",
            "Maintenance of machine"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Regular maintenance is a recurring expense (revenue), whereas purchase-related costs are capitalized.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1134,
        "text": "<p>What type of journal is used to update accounts at the end of the period?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "General Journal",
            "Adjusting Journal",
            "Closing Journal",
            "Reversing Journal"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Adjusting entries are used to bring account balances up to date under the accrual basis of accounting.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1135,
        "text": "<p>Adjusting advanced (unearned) income\u2014</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong - 2024",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Increases income & asset",
            "Decreases liability & increases income",
            "Decreases income & asset",
            "Increases expense & liability"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Adjusting unearned income recognizes that a liability has now been converted into earned revenue.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1136,
        "text": "<p>Which step of the accounting cycle is optional?</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Journal",
            "Trial Balance",
            "Ledger",
            "Worksheet"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>The worksheet is a tool for the accountant's convenience and is not a mandatory part of the formal cycle.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1137,
        "text": "<p>For which type of accounts are closing entries prepared?</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Personal accounts",
            "Nominal accounts",
            "Real (Asset) accounts",
            "Liability accounts"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Closing entries are only for nominal accounts (Income and Expenses) and the Drawings account.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1138,
        "text": "<p>Which heading is NOT required in an 8-column worksheet?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Adjustment",
            "Adjusted Trial Balance",
            "Income Statement",
            "Balance Sheet"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>An 8-column worksheet moves directly from adjustments to the financial statement columns, skipping the adjusted trial balance.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1139,
        "text": "<p>Closing entries are provided to\u2014\n\ni. Finish income accounts\n\nii. Finish expense accounts\n\niii. Finish drawing accounts</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Closing entries \"finish\" or zero out all temporary accounts for the current period.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1140,
        "text": "<p>Adjusting entries implement which accounting principles?\n\ni. Accounting Period Concept\n\nii. Accrual Basis\n\niii. Revenue Recognition</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Adjusting entries ensure that revenues and expenses are matched to the correct time period (Accrual/Matching).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1141,
        "text": "<p>Which is included in Capital Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Interest on loan",
            "Machine installation cost",
            "Travel expense",
            "Interest on capital"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Costs necessary to get a fixed asset ready for its intended use (like installation) are capitalized.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1142,
        "text": "<p>Which columns are included in a 10-column worksheet?\n\ni. Income Statement\n\nii. Retained Earnings Statement\n\niii. Statement of Financial Position</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Asset standard 10-column worksheet includes Trial Balance, Adjustments, Adjusted Trial Balance, Income Statement, and Balance Sheet.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1143,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a Capital Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Land development",
            "Salary payment",
            "Prepaid insurance",
            "Capital"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Improving land increases its value and utility over the long term, making it a capital expenditure.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1144,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a Revenue Income?</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Sale of land",
            "Sale of asset",
            "Interest received",
            "Share premium"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Interest received is a recurring operating income, making it revenue-based. Others are capital items.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1145,
        "text": "<p>Which of these is a part of a Worksheet?\n\ni. Trial Balance\n\nii. Ledger\n\niii. Journal</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Asset worksheet starts with a Trial Balance as its first column. Ledger and Journal are separate books.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1146,
        "text": "<p>What is the reversing entry for Accrued Salaries?</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Salaries Debit; Cash Credit",
            "Salaries Debit; Salaries Payable Credit",
            "Income Summary Debit; Salaries Credit",
            "Salaries Payable Debit; Salaries Credit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Asset reversing entry is the opposite of an adjusting entry. It clears the liability at the start of the next period.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1147,
        "text": "<p>Trial Balance shows Salary 20,000 TK and Accrued Salary 5,000 TK. How much is shown in the Adjusted Trial Balance column?</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "25,000 TK",
            "20,000 TK",
            "30,000 TK",
            "15,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Adjusted amount = Trial Balance (20,000 TK) + Adjustment (5,000 TK) = 25,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1148,
        "text": "<p>What is the adjusting entry for Accrued Salaries?</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Salaries Debit; Salaries Payable Credit",
            "Salaries Debit; Cash Credit",
            "Salaries Payable Debit; Salaries Credit",
            "Salaries Debit; Income Summary Credit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>To record an expense that has been incurred but not yet paid, we debit the expense and credit the liability.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1149,
        "text": "<p>Which account is closed with a closing entry at the end of the period?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Asset account",
            "Liability account",
            "Equity account",
            "Revenue account"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Revenue and Expense accounts (nominal accounts) are closed annually to reset their balances.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1150,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is NOT determined in a worksheet?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Gross Profit",
            "Net Profit",
            "Total Assets",
            "Total Liabilities"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Worksheets focus on Net Profit calculation; Gross Profit is typically identified in the formal Trading Account.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1151,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a Deferred Revenue Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Advertisement",
            "Accrued Salary",
            "Depreciation",
            "Prepaid Insurance"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Large advertisement costs that benefit the business for several years are treated as deferred revenue.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1152,
        "text": "<p>Anna Traders buys a building for 2,05,000 TK, pays 1,000 TK for stamps, and 4,000 TK for other contract costs. Total Capital Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "2,10,000 TK",
            "2,09,000 TK",
            "2,06,000 TK",
            "2,05,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Capital Expense = Purchase Price (2,05,000 TK) + Stamp (1,000 TK) + Contract costs (4,000 TK) = 2,10,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1153,
        "text": "<p>Which one is the scientific method of accounting?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Cash Basis",
            "Accrual Basis",
            "Single Entry",
            "Triple Entry"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Accrual Basis is globally accepted as scientific because it matches revenue and expenses to their actual periods.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1154,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is NOT mandatory?</p>",
        "meta": "Barishal  Board - 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
