    },
    {
        "id": 1165,
        "text": "<p>If the adjusting entry for accrued expense is omitted\u2014\n\ni) Profit is overstated\n\nii) Expense is understated\n\niii) Profit is understated</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Failing to record an expense results in lower total expenses (understated) and higher reported profit (overstated).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1166,
        "text": "<p>Why are closing entries required?\n\ni) To close expenses\n\nii) To close income\n\niii) To close capital expenditures</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Closing entries target temporary (nominal) accounts like income and expense. Capital expenditures involve permanent assets.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1167,
        "text": "<p>How many columns are required in the most widely used worksheet?</p>",
