    {
        "id": 1223,
        "text": "<p>Supplies 1,350 TK in Trial Balance. Ending inventory is 800. What is the adjusting entry?</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore  Board - 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Sup Debit 550; Expense Credit 550",
            "Expense Debit 550; Sup Credit 550",
            "Expense Debit 800; Sup Credit 800",
            "Sup Debit 1350; Expense Credit 1350"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Amount used = 1,350 TK - 800 = 550. Journal: Supplies Expense Debit, Supplies Credit.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1224,
        "text": "<p>If an accountant forgets to adjust \"Accrued Interest on Loan\"\u2014\n\ni. Profit overstated\n\nii. Equity overstated\n\niii. Liability understated</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong - 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Forgetting an expense keeps profit high and hides a debt (liability), affecting equity as well.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1225,
        "text": "<p>Which entry is given to record Advances and Accruals?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Reversing Entry",
            "Closing Entry",
            "Adjusting Entry",
            "Opening Entry"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Adjusting entries are used to bring the accrual-basis accounts up to date at year-end.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1226,
        "text": "<p>For which of the following items is a closing entry applicable?</p>",
        "meta": "Barishal  Board - 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Salary Account",
            "Machinery Account",
            "Accounts Receivable",
            "Loan Account"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Salary is an expense (nominal account), which must be closed at the end of the period. The others are permanent accounts.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1227,
        "text": "<p>Which accounts must be closed at the end of the accounting period?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur  Board - 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "All asset accounts",
            "All nominal accounts",
            "All personal accounts",
            "All liability accounts"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Nominal accounts (Income, Expense, and Drawings) are closed to reset their balances for the next year.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1228,
        "text": "<p>Unused supplies are adjusted by\u2014\n\ni. Deducting from supplies used\n\nii. Adding to supplies\n\niii. Showing as a current asset</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur  Board - 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Adjusting for unused supplies ensures that only the used portion is recorded as an expense, while the remainder stays as an asset.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1229,
        "text": "<p>How many steps (main stages) does a worksheet generally have?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "2",
            "3",
            "4",
            "5"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>The five standard steps are: Trial Balance, Adjustments, Adjusted Trial Balance, Income Statement, and Balance Sheet.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1230,
        "text": "<p>Which columns are NOT included in a 10-column worksheet?\n\ni. Income Statement\n\nii. Equity Statement\n\niii. Retained Earnings Statement</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii",
            "i & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Asset 10-column worksheet includes Trial Balance, Adjustments, Adjusted Trial Balance, Income Stmt, and Balance Sheet.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1231,
        "text": "<p>Total commission received 5,000 TK; 2,000 TK is for the next year. What is the current year's revenue?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "2,000 TK",
            "3,000 TK",
            "5,000 TK",
            "7,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Revenue Income = Total (5,000 TK) - Advance (2,000 TK) = 3,000 TK</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1232,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a Revenue Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Deferred Ad",
            "Preliminary Expense",
            "Share discount",
            "Interest expense"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Interest is a recurring cost of borrowing, making it a standard revenue expenditure.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1233,
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a Capital Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Amortization of Goodwill",
            "Amortization of Lease",
            "Purchase of Furniture",
            "Purchase of goods"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Buying fixed assets like furniture for long-term use is a capital expenditure.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1234,
        "text": "<p>Mr. Anik buys machines for the purpose of \"Resale.\" What type of expense is this?</p>",
        "meta": "Cumilla  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Revenue Expenditure",
            "Capitalized Expense",
            "Capital Expenditure",
            "Deferred Revenue"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>If assets are bought for resale (inventory), they are treated as goods purchase (Revenue Expenditure).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1235,
        "text": "<p>Machine 1,00,000 TK; Installation 20,000 TK; Carriage 10,000 TK; Year-end Repair 5,000 TK. Total Capital Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "1,00,000 TK",
            "1,20,000 TK",
            "1,30,000 TK",
            "1,35,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Capitalized Cost = 1,00,000 TK + 20,000 TK + 10,000 TK = 1,30,000 TK. Year-end repair is revenue expenditure.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1236,
        "text": "<p>If the above machine (1.3L) is sold for 1,00,000 TK after total depreciation of 32,500 TK, what is the profit/loss?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Loss 9,000 TK",
            "Loss 2,500 TK",
            "Profit 2,500 TK",
            "Profit 9,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Book Value = 1,30,000 TK - 32,500 TK = 97,500 TK. Sale 1,00,000 TK - 97,500 TK = 2,500 TK Profit.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1237,
        "text": "<p>Car repair (general) 20,000 TK; Repair to start car (initially) 2,000 TK; Monthly operating 10,000 TK. Total annual Revenue Expense?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "10,000 TK",
            "20,000 TK",
            "1,20,000 TK",
            "1,40,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Revenue Expense = (10,000 TK x 12) + 20,000 TK (General Repair) = 1,40,000 TK</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1238,
        "text": "<p>Based on the car stem above, what is the Capital Expenditure?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "10,000 TK",
            "20,000 TK",
            "5,00,000 TK",
            "5,02,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Capital Expense = Purchase (5,00,000 TK) + Initial repair to make it usable (2,000 TK) = 5,02,000 TK</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1239,
        "text": "<p>Trial Balance shows Office Supplies 1,300 TK. Ending supplies 600 TK. The adjusting entry is\u2014</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Sup Expense Debit 1,300 TK; Sup Credit 1,300 TK",
            "Sup Debit 750 TK; Sup Expense Credit 750 TK",
            "Sup Expense Debit 700 TK; Sup Credit 700 TK",
            "Sup Expense Debit 600 TK; Sup Credit 600 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Used amount = 1,300 TK - 600 = 700 TK. Journal: Supplies Expense Debit, Office Supplies Credit.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1240,
        "text": "<p>By providing closing entries\u2014\n\ni. Nominal accounts are closed\n\nii. Drawings are transferred to capital\n\niii. Accounts are opened for the current year</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Closing entries close the past year's revenue/expenses; they do not open new accounts (that's the opening entry's role).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1241,
        "text": "<p>If an adjusting entry for accrued expense is not provided\u2014\n\ni. Profit will be overstated\n\nii. Expense will be understated\n\niii. Profit will be understated</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Omitting an expense makes the profit look higher (overstated) and the total expenses look lower (understated).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1242,
        "text": "<p>Stationery purchase 10,000 TK, unused at year-end 4,000 TK. Correct adjustment entry?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Stat Debit 10 TKkTK; Cash Credit 10 TKkTK",
            "Stat Debit 6 TKkTK; Cash Credit 6 TKkTK",
            "Unused Stat Debit 6 TKkTK; Stat Credit 6 TKkTK",
            "Unused Stat Debit 4 TKkTK; Stat Credit 4 TKkTK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>To adjust for assets remaining, we debit the asset (Unused/Prepaid) and credit the expense (Stat) for the remaining amount.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1243,
        "text": "<p>Opening stat 6,000 TK; Purchase 10,000 TK; Unused 4,000 TK. Amount shown in Income Statement?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhethet  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "4,000 TK",
            "6,000 TK",
            "12,000 TK",
            "16,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Stationery Expense = (Opening 6,000 TK + Purchase 10,000 TK) - Closing 4,000 TK = 12,000 TK</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1244,
        "text": "<p>If goods are distributed for free as advertisement, the adjusting entry is\u2014</p>",
        "meta": "Barishal  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Ad Debit; Cash Credit",
            "Purchase Debit; Ad Credit",
            "Ad Debit; Def Ad Credit",
            "Ad Debit; Purchase Credit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Free distribution reduces inventory (Purchases) and increases the Advertisement expense.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1245,
        "text": "<p>Which is NOT a mandatory (required) entry?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii",
            "iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Reversing entries (Option iii) are optional and provided at the discretion of the accountant for convenience.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1246,
        "text": "<p>Reversing entries are applicable for\u2014\n\ni. Receivable Service Revenue\n\nii. Wages Payable\n\niii. Depreciation Expense</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka  Board - 2015",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Reversing entries are used for accruals and deferrals, but never for non-cash estimates like Depreciation.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1247,
        "text": "<p>Asset worksheet is an accounting\u2014</p>",
        "meta": "Azizul Haque College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Mandatory document",
            "External use document",
            "Internal & optional document",
            "Unnecessary document"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>It is used internally by the accounting staff and is not legally required (optional).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1248,
        "text": "<p>Salary (120%) is 1,20,000 TK. What is the amount of Salaries Payable?</p>",
        "meta": "AKM City College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "10,000 TK",
            "20,000 TK",
            "30,000 TK",
            "40,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Base (100%) = 1,20,000 TK / 1.2 = 1,00,000 TK. Payable (20%) = 1,20,000 TK - 1,00,000 TK = 20,000 TK</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1249,
        "text": "<p>Salary paid for 10 months is 40,000 TK. Amount of Salaries Payable?</p>",
        "meta": "Milestone College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "4,000 TK",
            "6,000 TK",
            "8,000 TK",
            "10,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Monthly = 40,000 TK / 10 = 4,000 TK. Payable for 2 months = 4,000 TK x 2 = 8,000 TK</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1250,
        "text": "<p>Unearned Income is shown in\u2014\n\ni. Trial Balance\n\nii. Debit of Income Statement\n\niii. Credit of Balance Sheet</p>",
        "meta": "Azizul Haque College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "i",
            "ii",
            "iii",
            "i & ii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Unearned income is a liability and appears on the credit side of the Balance Sheet columns.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1251,
        "text": "<p>Trial Balance shows Insurance 18,000 TK. 3 months are prepaid. Amount of Prepaid Insurance?</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore Govt College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "3,600 TK",
            "4,500 TK",
            "9,000 TK",
            "6,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Prepaid = (18,000 TK / 12 months) x 3 months = 4,500 TK</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1252,
        "text": "<p>What is \"Unexpired Cost\" considered?</p>",
        "meta": "Amrit Lal Dey College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Asset",
            "Expense",
            "Liability",
            "Equity"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Unexpired costs (like prepaid insurance or unused supplies) are assets because they offer future benefit.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1253,
        "text": "<p>What type of expenditure is Unexpired Advertisement?</p>",
        "meta": "AKM City College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Current",
            "Revenue",
            "Capital",
            "Deferred Revenue"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Advertisement costs that carry benefits to future periods are called Deferred Revenue Expenditures.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1254,
        "text": "<p>\"Revenue Expenditure\" refers to\u2014\n\ni. Current period revenue cost\n\nii. Reserved cost for next periods\n\niii. Current period write-offs</p>",
        "meta": "Jashore Govt College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>It includes current operational costs and the portion of deferred costs expensed (written off) this year.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1255,
        "text": "<p>What is the cost of advertising a brand new product in the market?</p>",
        "meta": "Jalalabad Cant.",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Capital Inv",
            "Revenue Expense",
            "Deferred Revenue",
            "Capital Expense"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Large initial costs for a new product are typically deferred and written off over several years.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1256,
        "text": "<p>When prepaid expenses are adjusted (expiring)\u2014</p>",
        "meta": "Notre Dame",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Expense \u2193 & Asset \u2191",
            "Asset \u2191 & Expense \u2191",
            "Asset \u2191 & Liability \u2191",
            "Expense \u2191 & Asset \u2193"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>As the prepayment expires, the expense is recorded (Increases) and the asset (Prepaid) is used up (Decreases).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1257,
        "text": "<p>Closed at the end of the accounting period\u2014\n\ni. Expenses\n\nii. Revenues\n\niii. Drawings</p>",
        "meta": "AKM City College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii, & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All temporary accounts (Revenue, Expense, Drawings) are reset to zero via closing entries.</p>"
    }
