    {
        "id": 1764,
        "text": "<p>Disadvantages of Single Entry System:\n\ni. Partial and incomplete\n\nii. Difficulty in verifying accuracy\n\niii. Difficulty in determining financial results</p>",
        "meta": "Notre Dame College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Since it lacks a trial balance and full disclosure, all these are valid disadvantages.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1765,
        "text": "<p>What is the formula for calculating Profit or Loss in Single Entry?</p>",
        "meta": "General",
        "type": "general",
        "options": [
            "Opening. Capital - Closing. Capital",
            "(Opening. Capital + Drawings) - Closing. Capital",
            "(Closing. Capital + Drawings) - (Opening. Capital + Interest. on Capital)",
            "(Opening. Capital + Drawings) - (Closing. Capital + Opening. Expense)"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Profit = (Closing Capital + Drawings) - (Opening Capital + Additional Capital/Interest).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1766,
        "text": "<p>How is Opening Capital calculated?</p>",
        "meta": "General",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Opening. Assets - Opening. Liabilities",
            "Opening. Assets - Current Liabilities",
            "Closing. Assets - Opening. Assets",
            "Opening. Assets - Opening. Assets"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Opening Capital is the difference between total opening assets and total opening liabilities.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1767,
        "text": "<p>Mr. Rafi: Opening. Capital 2,00,000 TK; Closing. Capital 3,00,000 TK; Drawings 20,000 TK; Add. Capital 50,000 TK. What is the Net Profit?</p>",
        "meta": "Ideal School & College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "70,000 TK",
            "1,00,000 TK",
            "1,80,000 TK",
            "2,20,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Net Profit = (3,00,000 TK + 20,000 TK) - (2,00,000 TK + 50,000 TK) = 70,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1768,
        "text": "<p>(Ref to stem 59) If Mr. Rafi had withdrawn an additional 20,000 TK, how would Net Profit change?</p>",
        "meta": "Ideal School & College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Increase by 40,000 TK",
            "Increase by 20,000 TK",
            "Decrease by 20,000 TK",
            "Decrease by 40,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Increasing drawings by 20,000 TK increases the profit result by the same amount.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1769,
        "text": "<p>Mr. Shahin withdraws TK 2,000 TK on the 15th of every month. If the interest rate is 5% p.a., what is the total interest on drawings?</p>",
        "meta": "Ideal School & College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "300",
            "325",
            "335",
            "600"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Interest = (Monthly Drawing \u00d7 Rate) \u00d7 6 = (2,000 TK \u00d7 5%) \u00d7 6 = 600. (Middle of month rule uses 6 months).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1770,
        "text": "<p>TK 1,000 TK is withdrawn on the 1st of every month. Interest rate is 10%. What is the interest on drawings?</p>",
        "meta": "Viqarunnisa Noon College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "650",
            "620",
            "600",
            "550"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Interest = (1,000 TK \u00d7 10%) \u00d7 6.5 = 650. (Start of month rule uses 6.5 months).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1771,
        "text": "<p>On what basis is profit or loss determined in the Single Entry System?</p>",
        "meta": "Viqarunnisa Noon College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Income-Expenditure",
            "Liabilities",
            "Assets",
            "Capital"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Profit is determined by comparing Opening Capital and Closing Capital.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1772,
        "text": "<p>Mr. Sakur's closing capital is TK 30,000 TK, which is 20% less than his opening capital. What is the 5% interest on capital?</p>",
        "meta": "Viqarunnisa Noon College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "1,250 TK",
            "1,500 TK",
            "1,875 TK",
            "2,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Opening Capital = 30,000 TK / 0.80 = 37,500 TK. Interest = 37,500 TK \u00d7 5% = 1,875 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1773,
        "text": "<p>On Jan 1, a 10% loan of TK 50,000 TK was taken. On March 31, TK 10,000 TK was repaid (excluding interest). What is the accrued interest at year-end?</p>",
        "meta": "Notre Dame College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "2,000 TK",
            "3,500 TK",
            "4,250 TK",
            "4,750 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Interest = (50,000 TK \u00d7 10% \u00d7 3/12) + (40,000 TK \u00d7 10% \u00d7 9/12) = 1,250 TK + 3,000 TK = 4,250 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1774,
        "text": "<p>What is the formula for calculating profit/loss in Single Entry?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka City College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Opening Capital + Drawings - Closing Capital",
            "Closing Capital + Drawings - Opening Capital",
            "Closing Capital + Opening Capital - Drawings",
            "Closing Capital - Opening Capital - Drawings"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Net Profit = (Closing Capital + Drawings) - (Opening Capital + Additional Capital).</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1775,
        "text": "<p>What is the formula for calculating profit or loss in the Single Entry System?</p>",
        "meta": "Abdul Kadir Mollah College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Opening Capital + Drawings - Closing Capital",
            "Closing Capital + Drawings - Opening Capital",
            "Closing Capital + Opening Capital - Drawings",
            "Closing Capital - Opening Capital - Drawings"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Net Profit = (Closing Capital + Drawings) - (Opening Capital + Additional Capital). Since \"Additional Capital\" isn't in the options, b is the most accurate formula.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1776,
        "text": "<p>Mr. Sakib withdraws TK 1,000 TK at every month-end and TK 1,000 TK worth of goods annually. Total annual cash drawings?</p>",
        "meta": "Abdul Kadir Mollah College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "10,000 TK",
            "11,000 TK",
            "12,000 TK",
            "13,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Cash Drawings = 1,000 TK \u00d7 12 = 12,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1777,
        "text": "<p>(Ref to stem 68) If a TK 1,000 TK Almirah is bought for the business from withdrawn funds, total drawings for the year?</p>",
        "meta": "Abdul Kadir Mollah College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "12,000 TK",
            "13,000 TK",
            "14,000 TK",
            "15,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Total = (12,000 TK cash + 1,000 TK goods) - 1,000 TK business expense = 12,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1778,
        "text": "<p>How is profit/loss calculated in Single Entry?</p>",
        "meta": "Govt. Azizul Haque College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Deducting Expense from income",
            "Deducting income from Expense",
            "Adding income and Expense",
            "Comparing Closing Capital and Opening Capital"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>It relies on the capital comparison method.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1779,
        "text": "<p>Add. Capital = 2,000 TK; Drawings = 2,000 TK; Net Profit = 1,000 TK; Closing Capital = 7,000 TK. What is the Opening Capital?</p>",
        "meta": "Jalalabad Cantonment",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "4,000 TK",
            "6,000 TK",
            "7,000 TK",
            "8,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Opening Capital = (Closing Capital + Drawings) - (Add Capital + Profit) = (7,000 TK + 2,000 TK) - (2,000 TK + 1,000 TK) = 6,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1780,
        "text": "<p>Mr. Ashraf (Jan 1) Opening Capital: 3,00,000 TK. Year-end: Cash 1,00,000 TK; Van 50,000 TK; Debtors 70,000 TK; Creditors 1,50,000 TK; Stock 5,00,000 TK; Investment 50,000 TK. Closing Capital?</p>",
        "meta": "Amrita Lal Dey College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "3,20,000 TK",
            "5,40,000 TK",
            "6,20,000 TK",
            "6,80,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Closing Capital = (1,00,000 TK+50,000 TK+70,000 TK+5,00,000 TK+50,000 TK) - 1,50,000 TK = 6,20,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1781,
        "text": "<p>(Ref to stem 72) What is the Net Profit?</p>",
        "meta": "Amrita Lal Dey College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "2,00,000 TK",
            "2,40,000 TK",
            "3,20,000 TK",
            "3,80,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Net Profit = Closing Capital - Opening Capital = 6,20,000 TK - 3,00,000 TK = 3,20,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1782,
        "text": "<p>According to Single Entry, if a personal asset is sold to provide funds to the business, what is the impact?\n\ni. Lower income tax\n\nii. Higher income tax\n\niii. Change in Statement of Affairs</p>",
        "meta": "General",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>It acts as additional capital. This increases owner's equity (Statement of Affairs) but doesn't increase operational profit, potentially keeping tax lower.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1783,
        "text": "<p>Mr. Salam withdrew 500 cash every 4 months and 2,000 TK worth of goods annually. He paid 10,000 TK office salary and provided a 20,000 TK personal computer to the business. Additional Capital?</p>",
        "meta": "Notre Dame College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "10,000 TK",
            "20,000 TK",
            "26,000 TK",
            "30,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Additional Capital = Salary payment (10,000 TK) + Computer (20,000 TK) = 30,000 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1784,
        "text": "<p>(Ref to stem 84) What is the total amount of drawings?</p>",
        "meta": "Notre Dame College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "2,500 TK",
            "3,500 TK",
            "6,000 TK",
            "8,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Total Drawings = (500 \u00d7 3 times a year) + 2,000 TK goods = 1,500 TK + 2,000 TK = 3,500 TK.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1785,
        "text": "<p>What is a Statement of Affairs (\u09ac\u09c8\u09b7\u09af\u09bc\u09bf\u0995 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ac\u09b0\u09a3\u09c0)?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore Govt. Mohila College",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "An Account",
            "Statement of Assets & Liabilities",
            "Balance Sheet",
            "Income & Expense Stmt"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>It is a statement showing assets and liabilities at a specific date to find capital.</p>"
    },
    {
        "id": 1786,
        "text": "<p>Opening. Accounts Payable: 20,000 TK; Closing. Accounts Payable: 22,000 TK. Credit Purchase: 70,000 TK. What is the amount of cash paid to creditors?</p>",
        "meta": "General",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "26,000 TK",
            "68,000 TK",
            "72,000 TK",
            "1,12,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Cash Paid = Opening. Balance + Credit Purchase - Closing. Balance = 20,000 TK + 70,000 TK - 22,000 TK = 68,000 TK.</p>"
    }
            ],
            shortCQData: [],
            fullCQData: []
        },
        "8": {
            subjectName: "Accounting 1st Paper",
            chapterName: "Chapter 8 : Accounting for Tangible and Intangible Assets",
            mcqData: [
{
        id: 1,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Lamisha Ltd. charges depreciation at a rate of 10% on machinery. The book value of a machine is 25,000 Taka and its accumulated depreciation is 15,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What is the purchase price of the machine?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["10,000 Taka", "25,000 Taka", "27,500 Taka", "40,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Purchase Price = Book Value + Accumulated Depreciation = 25,000 + 15,000 = <strong>40,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 2,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Lamisha Ltd. charges depreciation at a rate of 10% on machinery. The book value of a machine is 25,000 Taka and its accumulated depreciation is 15,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. If the current selling price of the machine is 30,000 Taka, what will be the profit or loss?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Profit of 5,000 Taka", "Loss of 10,000 Taka", "Profit of 15,000 Taka", "Loss of 15,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>Profit = Selling Price - Book Value = 30,000 - 25,000 = <strong>5,000 Taka (Profit)</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 3,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mr. Pushpo imported a machine for 20,00,000 Taka. He paid 2,00,000 Taka for customs duty and dock charges, and spent 50,000 Taka for installation. After an estimated useful life of 5 years, the salvage value of the machine is estimated at 1,50,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. At what value will the machine be recorded in the books of accounts?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["18,50,000 Taka", "20,00,000 Taka", "21,50,000 Taka", "22,50,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Recorded Value (Cost) = Purchase Price + Import Duty + Installation = 20,00,000 + 2,00,000 + 50,000 = <strong>22,50,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 4,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mr. Pushpo imported a machine for 20,00,000 Taka. He paid 2,00,000 Taka for customs duty and dock charges, and spent 50,000 Taka for installation. After an estimated useful life of 5 years, the salvage value of the machine is estimated at 1,50,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What type of expenditure are the dock charges and customs duty described in the stem?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Capital Expenditure", "Revenue Expenditure", "Capitalized Expenditure", "Deferred Revenue Expenditure"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>Costs like dock charges and customs duty are <strong>Capital Expenditures</strong> because they are necessary to bring the fixed asset to its working condition.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 5,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Miss Tahsin purchased a motor car for 50,000 Taka. Currently, its accumulated depreciation balance is 20,000 Taka. She sold the car for 36,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What is the profit or loss on the sale?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Profit of 6,000 Taka", "Loss of 14,000 Taka", "Loss of 20,000 Taka", "Profit of 36,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>Profit/Loss = Selling Price - (Purchase Price - Accumulated Depreciation) = 36,000 - (50,000 - 20,000) = 36,000 - 30,000 = <strong>6,000 Taka (Profit)</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 6,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Miss Tahsin purchased a motor car for 50,000 Taka. Currently, its accumulated depreciation balance is 20,000 Taka. She sold the car for 36,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. In the journal entry for the sale of the car, which will be credited?</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Motor car account<br>ii. Accumulated depreciation account<br>iii. Gain on sale of motor car account</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>The credit entries are <strong>Motor Car</strong> (to remove the cost) and <strong>Gain on Sale</strong>. Accumulated Depreciation is debited to remove its existing balance.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 7,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Korimon Ltd. charges depreciation at a rate of 10% on machinery. The book value of a machine is 30,000 Taka and its accumulated depreciation is 20,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What is the purchase price of the machine?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Commerce College",
        type: "college",
        options: ["10,000 Taka", "20,000 Taka", "30,000 Taka", "50,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Purchase Price = Book Value + Accumulated Depreciation = 30,000 + 20,000 = <strong>50,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 8,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Korimon Ltd. charges depreciation at a rate of 10% on machinery. The book value of a machine is 30,000 Taka and its accumulated depreciation is 20,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. If the current selling price of the machine is 35,000 Taka, what will be the profit or loss?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Commerce College",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Profit of 5,000 Taka", "Loss of 5,000 Taka", "Profit of 15,000 Taka", "Loss of 15,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>Profit = Selling Price - Book Value = 35,000 - 30,000 = <strong>5,000 Taka (Profit)</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 9,
        text: "<p>What type of account is Accumulated Depreciation?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Liability", "Asset", "Contra Expense", "Contra Asset"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Accumulated Depreciation is a <strong>Contra Asset</strong> account. It reduces the gross value of the asset on the balance sheet.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 10,
        text: "<p>What type of transaction is depreciation?</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Non-cash<br>ii. Invisible<br>iii. On credit</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Barisal Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>Depreciation is <strong>Non-cash</strong> because no cash is paid out, and <strong>Invisible</strong> because no physical exchange of value is seen.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 11,
        text: "<p>Mr. Bashar purchased furniture for 20,000 Taka for use in business. If the annual depreciation is 1,000 Taka, what is the rate of depreciation?</p>",
        meta: "Barisal Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["4%", "5%", "8%", "10%"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Depreciation Rate = (Annual Depreciation / Purchase Price) × 100 = (1,000 / 20,000) × 100 = <strong>5%</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 12,
        text: "<p>Which of the following is a non-cash transaction?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Credit purchase", "Depreciation", "Sale through bill", "Purchase by check"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p><strong>Depreciation</strong> is a non-cash transaction as it is an allocation of cost over time, requiring no immediate cash payment.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 13,
        text: "<p>From which word did the word 'Depreciation' originate?</p>",
        meta: "Rajshahi Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Depretum", "Deptium", "Depretium", "Depcitium"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>The word originates from the Latin <strong>'Depretium'</strong> (De = down, Pretium = price/value).</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 14,
        text: "<p>Reasons for charging depreciation-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Consistency principle<br>ii. Tax savings<br>iii. Replacement of asset</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Rajshahi Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "ii & iii", "i & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Charging depreciation ensures <strong>consistency</strong>, provides <strong>tax savings</strong> by reducing taxable income, and creates a fund for <strong>asset replacement</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 15,
        text: "<p>Which of the following is a non-cash transaction?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Amortization of fixed assets", "Recovery of bad debts", "Prepaid service income", "Prepaid expenses"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p><strong>Amortization</strong> (for intangible assets) and depreciation (for tangible assets) are both non-cash internal allocations.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 16,
        text: "<p>When charging depreciation under the fixed installment (straight-line) method, what is considered?</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Purchase price of the asset<br>ii. Book value of the asset<br>iii. Estimated useful life</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Sylhet Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "ii & iii", "i & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Straight-line uses <strong>Cost</strong>, <strong>Salvage Value</strong>, and <strong>Useful Life</strong>. Book value is primarily used in reducing balance methods.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 17,
        text: "<p>Depreciation is charged on-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Fixed assets<br>ii. Current assets<br>iii. Tangible assets</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Depreciation is exclusively charged on <strong>Fixed Assets</strong> that are <strong>Tangible</strong> in nature.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 18,
        text: "<p>As a result of charging depreciation-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Asset and owner's equity decrease<br>ii. Expense increases and profit decreases<br>iii. Asset decreases and owner's equity increases</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Viqarunnisa Noon School & College",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>Depreciation expense decreases <strong>Owner's Equity</strong>, while the credit to Accumulated Depreciation decreases the <strong>Net Asset</strong> value.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 19,
        text: "<p>Which of the following values of a fixed asset is distributed over its useful life?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Govt. Women's College",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Purchase price", "Acquisition cost", "Depreciable value", "Book value"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>The <strong>Depreciable Value</strong> (Cost - Salvage) is the total amount that is systematically allocated over the asset's life.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 20,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Latif Traders purchased a machine on January 1, 2015, for 1,90,000 Taka. The installation cost of the machine was 10,000 Taka. Depreciation is charged at a rate of 10% annually using the reducing balance method.</p><p>Q. What is the amount of depreciation for the year 2015?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["1,000 Taka", "18,000 Taka", "19,000 Taka", "20,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Depreciation (2015) = (1,90,000 + 10,000) × 10% = 2,00,000 × 10% = <strong>20,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 21,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Latif Traders purchased a machine on January 1, 2015, for 1,90,000 Taka. The installation cost of the machine was 10,000 Taka. Depreciation is charged at a rate of 10% annually using the reducing balance method.</p><p>Q. What will be the book value of the machine after three years?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["1,40,000 Taka", "1,45,800 Taka", "1,80,000 Taka", "2,00,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Year 1: 2,00,000 - 20,000 = 1,80,000</p><p>Year 2: 1,80,000 - 18,000 = 1,62,000</p><p>Year 3: 1,62,000 - 16,200 = <strong>1,45,800 Taka</strong></p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 22,
        text: "<p>What factors must be considered when calculating depreciation under the straight-line method?</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Purchase price of the asset<br>ii. Salvage value of the asset<br>iii. Estimated useful life</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Rajshahi Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "ii & iii", "i & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Calculating straight-line depreciation requires the <strong>Original Cost</strong>, the <strong>Salvage Value</strong>, and the <strong>Useful Life</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 23,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Rony Limited purchased a machine on January 1, 2014, for 3,00,000 Taka. The salvage value is 20,000 Taka and the estimated life is 10 years. Depreciation is calculated using the reducing balance method.</p><p>Q. What is the depreciable value of the machine for the year 2014?</p>",
        meta: "Rajshahi Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["2,70,000 Taka", "2,80,000 Taka", "3,00,000 Taka", "3,20,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>In the reducing balance method, salvage value is not deducted from the cost to determine the base for depreciation. Thus, the depreciable value is the full cost of <strong>3,00,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 24,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Rony Limited purchased a machine on January 1, 2014, for 3,00,000 Taka. The salvage value is 20,000 Taka and the estimated life is 10 years. Depreciation is calculated using the reducing balance method (Double Declining assumed).</p><p>Q. Determine the amount of depreciation for the year 2015.</p>",
        meta: "Rajshahi Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["24,000 Taka", "48,000 Taka", "56,000 Taka", "60,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Rate = 20% (assuming double-declining 2/10)</p><p>2014 Dep = 3,00,000 × 20% = 60,000</p><p>2015 Dep = (3,00,000 - 60,000) × 20% = <strong>48,000 Taka</strong></p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 25,
        text: "<p>In which method of determining depreciation is the salvage value not subtracted?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Sum-of-the-years'-digits method", "Production units method", "Straight-line method", "Reducing balance method"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>In the <strong>Reducing Balance</strong> method, the depreciation rate is applied to the full book value (Cost - Accum Dep) without deducting salvage first.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 26,
        text: "<p>Which method is most commonly used for charging depreciation?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Straight-line method", "Revaluation method", "Annuity method", "Replacement cost method"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>The <strong>Straight-line method</strong> is the most widely used due to its simplicity and equal distribution of cost.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 27,
        text: "<p>If an asset has no salvage value, which method of depreciation will not result in the asset value becoming zero at the end of its useful life?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Reducing balance method", "Straight-line method", "Sum-of-the-years'-digits method", "Production method"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>Because it calculates a percentage of a declining balance, the <strong>Reducing Balance</strong> method mathematically never reaches exactly zero.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 28,
        text: "<p>Which is the modern journal entry for recording depreciation?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Depreciation A/C Dr; Asset A/C Cr", "Accumulated Depreciation A/C Dr; Depreciation A/C Cr", "Asset A/C Dr; Depreciation Expense A/C Cr", "Depreciation Expense A/C Dr; Accumulated Depreciation A/C Cr"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Modern accounting uses the <strong>Indirect Method</strong>, where the expense is debited and the provision (Accumulated Depreciation) is credited.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 29,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mr. Sohel purchased a machine on January 1, 2014, for 80,000 Taka. The installation cost of the machine was 20,000 Taka. The depreciation rate is 10%.</p><p>Q. If Mr. Sohel records the machine purchase and installation cost in cash-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Machine account Dr<br>ii. Installation expense account Dr<br>iii. Cash account Cr</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i", "ii", "i & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Capitalization rule: All costs to make an asset usable (like installation) are debited to the <strong>Asset Account</strong> (Machine), not an expense.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 30,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mr. Sohel purchased a machine on January 1, 2014, for 80,000 Taka. The installation cost of the machine was 20,000 Taka. The depreciation rate is 10%.</p><p>Q. What is the amount of depreciation for the machine in 2015?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["2,00,000 Taka", "6,000 Taka", "8,000 Taka", "10,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Depreciation (2015) = (80,000 + 20,000) × 10% = 1,00,000 × 10% = <strong>10,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 31,
        text: "<p>In the fixed installment method, which of the following are considered when calculating depreciation?</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Purchase price of the asset<br>ii. Book value of the asset<br>iii. Estimated useful life</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Chittagong Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>The Straight-line method focuses on the <strong>Original Cost</strong> and <strong>Life</strong>; Book value is the base for the reducing balance method.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 32,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>The value of machinery in Shoikat Traders' Trial Balance is 1,00,000 Taka. The installation cost of the machine was 2,000 Taka and the repair cost was 1,000 Taka. He charges depreciation at a rate of 10%.</p><p>Q. What will be the annual depreciation on December 31?</p>",
        meta: "Sylhet Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["10,000 Taka", "10,100 Taka", "10,200 Taka", "10,300 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Depreciation = (Machinery + Installation Cost) × 10% = (1,00,000 + 2,000) × 10% = 1,02,000 × 10% = <strong>10,200 Taka</strong>. (Repair cost is revenue expenditure and not capitalized).</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 33,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>The value of machinery in Shoikat Traders' Trial Balance is 1,00,000 Taka. The installation cost of the machine was 2,000 Taka and the repair cost was 1,000 Taka. He charges depreciation at a rate of 10%.</p><p>Q. If Mr. Shoikat decides to charge depreciation at a rate of 20% instead of 10%-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Net profit will decrease<br>ii. There will be a change in asset valuation<br>iii. Inconsistency will appear in the Balance Sheet</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Sylhet Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "ii & iii", "i & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 3
    },
    {
        id: 34,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>The purchase price of a machine is 1,90,000 Taka, installation cost is 10,000 Taka, salvage value is 20,000 Taka, and useful life is 10 years. Depreciation is charged at a rate of 20% using the reducing balance method.</p><p>Q. What is the book value of the machine at the end of the third year?</p>",
        meta: "Barisal Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["97,040 Taka", "97,280 Taka", "1,02,400 Taka", "1,28,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Cost = 2,00,000</p><p>Year 1 Dep: 40,000 | BV: 1,60,000</p><p>Year 2 Dep: 32,000 | BV: 1,28,000</p><p>Year 3 Dep: 25,600 | BV: <strong>1,02,400 Taka</strong></p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 35,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>The purchase price of a machine is 1,90,000 Taka, installation cost is 10,000 Taka, salvage value is 20,000 Taka, and useful life is 10 years. Depreciation is charged at a rate of 20% using the reducing balance method.</p><p>Q. If straight-line depreciation is used instead of the reducing balance method, what will be the effect on the financial statements in the initial years?</p>",
        meta: "Barisal Board · 2016",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Profit will increase", "Profit will decrease", "Tax liability will decrease", "Asset value will decrease"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>Straight-line depreciation (18k) would be lower than the first-year reducing balance depreciation (40k), leading to higher reported <strong>Net Profit</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 36,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>On April 1, 2012, Rita Enterprise purchased a machine for 47,000 Taka and installed it for 7,000 Taka. The life of the machine is estimated at 5 years with a salvage value of 4,000 Taka. The firm closes its accounts on December 31 every year.</p><p>Q. What is the depreciation for 2012 under the straight-line method?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["5,000 Taka", "7,500 Taka", "10,000 Taka", "10,800 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Dep = (47k + 7k - 4k) / 5 = 10,000. For 9 months (Apr-Dec): 10,000 × 9/12 = <strong>7,500 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 37,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>On April 1, 2012, Rita Enterprise purchased a machine for 47,000 Taka and installed it for 7,000 Taka. The life of the machine is estimated at 5 years with a salvage value of 4,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. If the firm uses the double-declining balance method, what will be the depreciation rate?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["10%", "20%", "30%", "40%"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Rate = (100% / Life) × 2 = (100% / 5) × 2 = <strong>40%</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 38,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Sachin Machinery purchase details: Jan 1, 2012: 1,00,000 Taka; June 30, 2012: 70,000 Taka. The machine purchased in June was sold on July 1, 2013, for 60,000 Taka. 10% Straight-line depreciation is charged.</p><p>Q. What is the total depreciation on December 31, 2012?</p>",
        meta: "Rajshahi Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["8,500 Taka", "10,000 Taka", "13,500 Taka", "17,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Total Dep = (1,00,000 × 10%) + (70,000 × 10% × 6/12) = 10,000 + 3,500 = <strong>13,500 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 39,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Sachin Machinery purchase details: June 30, 2012: 70,000 Taka. This machine was sold on July 1, 2013, for 60,000 Taka. 10% Straight-line depreciation is charged.</p><p>Q. What is the profit or loss on the sale of the machine on July 1, 2013?</p>",
        meta: "Rajshahi Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Profit of 500 Taka", "Loss of 3,000 Taka", "Loss of 6,500 Taka", "Loss of 10,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>BV at Sale = 70,000 - 3,500 (2012) - 3,500 (2013 half) = 63,000. Loss = 63,000 - 60,000 = <strong>3,000 Taka (Loss)</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 40,
        text: "<p>Which method of depreciation uses the formula to determine the rate based on salvage value and cost ($1 - \\sqrt[n]{S/C}$)?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Straight-line", "Reducing balance", "Sum-of-the-years'-digits", "Annuity"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>This is the standard mathematical formula used to calculate the percentage rate for the <strong>Reducing Balance</strong> method.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 41,
        text: "<p>In the straight-line method, which factors are considered for depreciation?</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Purchase price of the asset<br>ii. Estimated salvage value<br>iii. Estimated useful life</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Chittagong Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>All three factors (Cost, Salvage, and Life) are mandatory components of the <strong>Straight-line</strong> depreciation formula.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 42,
        text: "<p>A machine was purchased for 20,000 Taka on January 1, 2010. 10% reducing balance depreciation is charged. What will be the accumulated depreciation balance after 6 years?</p>",
        meta: "Sylhet Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["8,000 Taka", "9,371 Taka", "10,629 Taka", "16,364 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>BV after 6 years = 20,000 × (0.9)^6 ≈ 10,629. Accum Dep = 20,000 - 10,629 = <strong>9,371 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 43,
        text: "<p>If an asset's useful life is 8 years, what will be the depreciation rate under the straight-line method?</p>",
        meta: "Barisal Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["10%", "12%", "12.5%", "16%"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Rate = 100 / 8 = <strong>12.5%</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 44,
        text: "<p>Which is the correct formula for the depreciation rate under the straight-line method?</p>",
        meta: "Barisal Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Option A", "Option B", "Option C", "Option D"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>The formula is <strong>Rate = (100 / Life)</strong> for the basic straight-line percentage.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 45,
        text: "<p>If the useful life of a machine is 8 years instead of 10 years-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. The depreciation rate will increase<br>ii. Net profit will decrease<br>iii. Tax liability will increase</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2015",
        type: "college",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>A shorter life increases the annual depreciation expense, which **reduces net profit** and consequently **reduces tax liability**.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 46,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>On December 31, 2017, Jason Ltd. purchased a machine for 50,000 Taka. The installation cost was 7,000 Taka and carriage cost was 3,000 Taka. Salvage value is 5,000 Taka and useful life is 5 years.</p><p>Q. What is the annual depreciation for the machine under the straight-line method?</p>",
        meta: "Ideal School & College, Dhaka",
        type: "college",
        options: ["12,000 Taka", "11,000 Taka", "10,400 Taka", "9,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Depreciation = (50,000 + 7,000 + 3,000 - 5,000) / 5 = 50,000 / 5 = <strong>11,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 47,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>On December 31, 2017, Jason Ltd. purchased a machine for 50,000 Taka. The installation cost was 7,000 Taka and carriage cost was 3,000 Taka. Useful life is 5 years.</p><p>Q. If the company uses the double-declining balance method, what will be the depreciation rate?</p>",
        meta: "Ideal School & College, Dhaka",
        type: "college",
        options: ["16.36%", "18.91%", "20%", "40%"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Rate = (100% / 5) × 2 = <strong>40%</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 48,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>The useful life of a machine is 10 years and the salvage value is 5,000 Taka. The purchase price of the machine is 55,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What will be the annual depreciation rate under the reducing balance method?</p>",
        meta: "Notre Dame College, Dhaka",
        type: "college",
        options: ["10%", "20%", "5%", "25%"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Reducing Balance Rate = (100% / Life) × 2 = (100% / 10) × 2 = <strong>20%</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 49,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>The useful life of a machine is 10 years and the salvage value is 5,000 Taka. The purchase price of the machine is 55,000 Taka. The depreciation rate is 20%.</p><p>Q. What will be the depreciation for the second year under the reducing balance method?</p>",
        meta: "Notre Dame College, Dhaka",
        type: "college",
        options: ["5,000 Taka", "10,000 Taka", "8,800 Taka", "8,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Year 1 Dep = 55,000 × 20% = 11,000. Year 2 Dep = (55,000 - 11,000) × 20% = <strong>8,800 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 50,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mr. Rahim purchased a machine on January 1, 2017, for 2,00,000 Taka. The installation cost was 10,000 Taka and the carriage cost was 15,000 Taka. Useful life is 10 years and salvage value is 20,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What is the total cost of the machine?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka City College",
        type: "college",
        options: ["2,45,000 Taka", "2,25,000 Taka", "2,05,000 Taka", "2,00,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Total Cost = Purchase Price + Installation + Carriage = 2,00,000 + 10,000 + 15,000 = <strong>2,25,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 51,
        text: "<p>On January 1, 2012, furniture was purchased for 40,000 Taka. If depreciation is charged at 10% using the reducing balance method, how much will be in the accumulated depreciation provision after 4 years?</p>",
        meta: "Milestone College, Dhaka",
        type: "college",
        options: ["4,000 Taka", "16,000 Taka", "15,756 Taka", "13,756 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Yr 1: 4,000 | Yr 2: 3,600 | Yr 3: 3,240 | Yr 4: 2,916</p><p>Total Accumulated = 4,000 + 3,600 + 3,240 + 2,916 = <strong>13,756 Taka</strong></p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 52,
        text: "<p>The purchase price of an asset is 1,00,000 Taka and its salvage value is 20,000 Taka. If depreciation is charged at 20% under the reducing balance method, what is the first-year depreciation?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Govt. Women's College",
        type: "college",
        options: ["20,000 Taka", "16,000 Taka", "12,000 Taka", "10,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>In the reducing balance method, salvage value is not subtracted from the cost for the calculation. Dep = 1,00,000 × 20% = <strong>20,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 53,
        text: "<p>If an asset was purchased for 25,000 Taka and depreciation for 2012 was 2,500 Taka (10%), what will be the depreciation for 2013 under the reducing balance method?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Commerce College",
        type: "college",
        options: ["2,200 Taka", "2,250 Taka", "2,300 Taka", "2,500 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Dep (2013) = (25,000 - 2,500) × 10% = 22,500 × 10% = <strong>2,250 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 54,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Sabila Builders purchased a machine on July 1, 2017, for 9,75,000 Taka. The carriage cost was 25,000 Taka. Useful life is 20 years and salvage value is 40,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. If the carriage cost is debited to the Purchase (মেশিন ক্রয়) account instead of the Machine account, what type of error is it?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Education Board Model College",
        type: "college",
        options: ["Error of Omission", "Compensating Error", "Error of Commission", "Error of Principle"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Debiting a capital expenditure (Machine) to a revenue account (Purchase) is a <strong>Principle Error</strong> as it violates accounting rules.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 55,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Sabila Builders purchased a machine on July 1, 2017, for 9,75,000 Taka. The carriage cost was 25,000 Taka. Useful life is 20 years. Depreciation rate is 10%.</p><p>Q. What is the depreciation for 2017 under the reducing balance method?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Education Board Model College",
        type: "college",
        options: ["1,00,000 Taka", "50,000 Taka", "48,000 Taka", "96,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Dep = (9,75,000 + 25,000) × 10% = 1,00,000. For 6 months (July-Dec): 1,00,000 × 6/12 = <strong>50,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 56,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>On January 1, 2017, Shrobona Ltd. had a furniture balance of 1,20,000 Taka and an accumulated depreciation balance of 50,000 Taka. The salvage value after 5 years is estimated at 20,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What is the annual depreciation under the straight-line method?</p>",
        meta: "Govt. Commerce College, Chittagong",
        type: "college",
        options: ["10,000 Taka", "14,000 Taka", "20,000 Taka", "24,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Straight-line Dep = (Cost - Salvage) / Life = (1,20,000 - 20,000) / 5 = 1,00,000 / 5 = <strong>20,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 57,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>On January 1, 2017, Shrobona Ltd. had a furniture balance of 1,20,000 Taka and an accumulated depreciation balance of 50,000 Taka. Useful life is 5 years.</p><p>Q. If the depreciation rate is 10%, what is the depreciation for 2017 under the reducing balance method?</p>",
        meta: "Govt. Commerce College, Chittagong",
        type: "college",
        options: ["5,000 Taka", "7,000 Taka", "10,000 Taka", "12,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Dep (2017) = (Balance - Accumulated Dep) × Rate = (1,20,000 - 50,000) × 10% = 70,000 × 10% = <strong>7,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
{
        id: 1,
        text: "<p>On which of the following assets is depreciation charged?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Land", "Building", "Trademark", "Patent"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p><strong>Land</strong> is never depreciated as its life is considered infinite. <strong>Trademarks</strong> and <strong>Patents</strong> are amortized. <strong>Buildings</strong> are tangible fixed assets that lose value over time, hence they are depreciated.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 2,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mr. Arafat Ali purchased a machine on January 1, 2024, for 6,00,000 Taka. The installation cost was 40,000 Taka and carriage cost was 10,000 Taka. Useful life is 10 years. Reducing balance method is used.</p><p>Q. What is the acquisition cost of the machine?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["6,00,000 Taka", "6,10,000 Taka", "6,40,000 Taka", "6,50,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Acquisition Cost = Purchase Price + Installation + Carriage = 6,00,000 + 40,000 + 10,000 = <strong>6,50,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 3,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mr. Arafat Ali purchased a machine on January 1, 2024, for 6,00,000 Taka. The installation cost was 40,000 Taka and carriage cost was 10,000 Taka. Useful life is 10 years. Reducing balance method is used.</p><p>Q. What is the book value of the machine at the end of the first year?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["4,80,000 Taka", "5,20,000 Taka", "5,92,000 Taka", "6,00,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Cost = 6,50,000. Rate = (100 / 10) × 2 = 20%.</p><p>Depreciation = 6,50,000 × 20% = 1,30,000.</p><p>Book Value = 6,50,000 - 1,30,000 = <strong>5,20,000 Taka</strong>.</p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 4,
        text: "<p>Factors to be considered in determining depreciation are-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Purchase price<br>ii. Effective useful life<br>iii. Salvage value</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Dinajpur Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>All three factors are essential for any depreciation calculation to accurately allocate the asset's cost over time.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 5,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>A machine was purchased on January 1, 2022, for 1,00,000 Taka. Estimated useful life is 10 years and salvage value is 10,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What is the depreciation for the year 2024 under the straight-line method?</p>",
        meta: "Barisal Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["1,000 Taka", "9,000 Taka", "10,000 Taka", "11,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Dep = (1,00,000 - 10,000) / 10 = 90,000 / 10 = <strong>9,000 Taka</strong>. In the straight-line method, the amount remains constant every year.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 6,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>A machine was purchased on January 1, 2022, for 1,00,000 Taka. Estimated useful life is 10 years and salvage value is 10,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What is the depreciation for the year 2025 under the reducing balance method?</p>",
        meta: "Barisal Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["20,000 Taka", "16,000 Taka", "12,800 Taka", "10,240 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Rate = 20%. </p><p>2022: 1,00,000 × 20% = 20,000 (BV: 80k)</p><p>2023: 80,000 × 20% = 16,000 (BV: 64k)</p><p>2024: 64,000 × 20% = 12,800 (BV: 51.2k)</p><p>2025: 51,200 × 20% = <strong>10,240 Taka</strong></p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 7,
        text: "<p>What type of value of an asset is referred to as depreciation?</p>",
        meta: "Barisal Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Used value", "Unused value", "Salvage value", "Sale value"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>Depreciation is the systematic allocation of the <strong>Used-up portion</strong> of the asset's cost over its life.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 8,
        text: "<p>Which of the following is the most suitable method for calculating depreciation on fixed assets like buildings, furniture, and machinery?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Reducing balance method", "Straight-line method", "Sum-of-years'-digits method", "Machine hour rate method"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p>The <strong>Reducing Balance method</strong> is ideal for machinery as it charges higher depreciation in earlier years when the asset is most productive.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 9,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Sun Traders spent 6,00,000 Taka and 50,000 Taka for machine purchase and installation respectively on January 1, 2024. Life is 10 years and salvage value is 40,000 Taka. Straight-line method is used.</p><p>Q. What is the annual depreciation of the machine?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["56,000 Taka", "60,000 Taka", "61,000 Taka", "65,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Dep = (6,50,000 - 40,000) / 10 = 6,10,000 / 10 = <strong>61,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 10,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Sun Traders spent 6,50,000 Taka for a machine. Life is 10 years and salvage value is 40,000 Taka. Straight-line annual depreciation is 61,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. If reducing balance is used, by how much more will the asset value decrease in the Balance Sheet in the 1st year compared to straight-line?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["41,000 Taka", "51,000 Taka", "61,000 Taka", "69,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Red. Bal Rate = 20%. Dep = 6,50,000 × 20% = 1,30,000.</p><p>Difference = 1,30,000 - 61,000 = <strong>69,000 Taka</strong>.</p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 11,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mr. Mamun purchased a machine for 1,80,000 Taka on Jan 1, 2023, with 20,000 Taka installation cost. Life is 10 years and salvage value is 30,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What is the depreciation for 2024 under the reducing balance method?</p>",
        meta: "Sylhet Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["40,000 Taka", "34,000 Taka", "32,000 Taka", "27,200 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Cost = 2,00,000. Rate = 20%.</p><p>2023 Dep = 40,000. BV = 1,60,000.</p><p>2024 Dep = 1,60,000 × 20% = <strong>32,000 Taka</strong>.</p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 12,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mr. Mamun spent 20,000 Taka for machine installation. What if this is incorrectly recorded as a revenue expenditure?</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Machine value understated by 20,000<br>ii. Net profit understated by 20,000<br>iii. Total assets and liabilities understated by 20,000</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Sylhet Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["i & ii", "ii & iii", "i & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Recording capital expenditure as revenue understated assets (Machine) and understated profit (which in turn understates Equity/Liabilities side).</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 13,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Machine cost 3,00,000 Taka, installation 40,000, carriage 10,000. Life is 10 years. Reducing balance method is used.</p><p>Q. What will be the book value of the machine at the end of the first year?</p>",
        meta: "Chittagong Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["2,40,000 Taka", "2,72,000 Taka", "2,80,000 Taka", "3,00,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Cost = 3,50,000. Rate = 20%. Dep = 70,000. Book Value = 3,50,000 - 70,000 = <strong>2,80,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 14,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Machine cost 3,50,000. If straight-line is used instead of reducing balance in the first year-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Depreciation amount will decrease<br>ii. No impact on profit<br>iii. Net profit will increase</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Chittagong Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Straight-line dep (35,000) is lower than reducing balance (70,000) in the first year, hence profit will increase.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 15,
        text: "<p>Factors considered in determining depreciation are-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Purchase price<br>ii. Effective useful life<br>iii. Salvage value</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Chittagong Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 3
    },
    {
        id: 16,
        text: "<p>In which method is the salvage value of the asset considered in the final year of its useful life?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Straight-line method", "Reducing balance method", "Production method", "Sum-of-years'-digits method"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>In the <strong>Reducing Balance method</strong>, salvage value is not subtracted from the cost base initially but serves as a floor below which the asset cannot be depreciated.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 17,
        text: "<p>Essential factors for charging depreciation on assets are-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Total cost of the asset<br>ii. Estimated useful life<br>iii. Salvage value</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 3
    },
    {
        id: 18,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Selim Traders purchased a machine on July 1, 2023, for 90,000 Taka and spent 10,000 for installation. Life is 10 years and salvage value is 20,000 Taka. Accounts close on Dec 31.</p><p>Q. What is the depreciation for 2024 under the straight-line method?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["4,000 Taka", "5,000 Taka", "8,000 Taka", "10,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Dep = (1,00,000 - 20,000) / 10 = <strong>8,000 Taka</strong>. Since 2024 is a full year, the amount is 8,000.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 19,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Selim Traders purchased a machine on July 1, 2023, for 1,00,000 Taka. Rate is 20%.</p><p>Q. What is the depreciation for 2023 under the reducing balance method?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["4,000 Taka", "5,000 Taka", "8,000 Taka", "10,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Dep = 1,00,000 × 20% = 20,000. For 6 months (July-Dec): 20,000 × 6/12 = <strong>10,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 20,
        text: "<p>In which method does the amount of depreciation remain equal in all financial years?</p>",
        meta: "Mymensingh Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Reducing balance", "Straight-line", "Sum-of-years'-digits", "Production method"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>The <strong>Straight-line method</strong> distributes the cost of the asset equally over its useful life.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 21,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mita Enterprise purchased a machine on April 1, 2024, for 94,000 Taka and installed it for 14,000 Taka. Life is 5 years and salvage value is 8,000 Taka. Accounts close on Dec 31.</p><p>Q. What is the depreciation for 2024 under the straight-line method?</p>",
        meta: "Mymensingh Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["10,000 Taka", "15,000 Taka", "20,000 Taka", "21,600 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Annual Dep = (1,08,000 - 8,000) / 5 = 20,000.</p><p>For 9 months (Apr-Dec): 20,000 × 9/12 = <strong>15,000 Taka</strong>.</p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 22,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Useful life is 5 years.</p><p>Q. If the firm uses the reducing balance method, what is the depreciation rate?</p>",
        meta: "Mymensingh Board · 2025",
        type: "board",
        options: ["10%", "20%", "40%", "30%"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Rate = (100% / 5) × 2 = <strong>40%</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 23,
        text: "<p>The useful life of a machine in Jubayer Traders is 10 years. Annual depreciation is 20,000 Taka and salvage value is 25,000 Taka. What is the purchase price of the machine?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["4,50,000 Taka", "2,25,000 Taka", "2,00,000 Taka", "1,75,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Dep = (Cost - Salvage) / Life -> 20,000 = (Cost - 25,000) / 10 -> 2,00,000 = Cost - 25,000 -> Cost = <strong>2,25,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 24,
        text: "<p>Which of the following is a contra-asset?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Accumulated Depreciation", "Share Discount", "Patent", "Goodwill"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p><strong>Accumulated Depreciation</strong> is a contra-asset account as it reduces the value of the fixed asset on the balance sheet.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 25,
        text: "<p>Which of the following is an external cause of depreciation?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Obsolescence", "Passage of time", "Depletion", "Usage wear and tear"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p><strong>Obsolescence</strong> (becoming outdated due to new technology) is an external factor. Time, depletion, and usage are internal or inherent to the asset.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 26,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>Mr. Akib purchased a machine for 1,00,000 Taka at the beginning of 2021. Useful life is 5 years and the straight-line method is used. At the end of 2023, the machine was sold for 50,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What is the amount of profit or loss on the sale?</p>",
        meta: "Dhaka Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Loss 50,000", "Profit 50,000", "Profit 10,000", "Loss 10,000"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Annual Dep = 1,00,000 / 5 = 20,000.</p><p>Accum Dep (3 years) = 60,000. Book Value = 40,000.</p><p>Profit = 50,000 - 40,000 = <strong>10,000 Taka (Profit)</strong>.</p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 27,
        text: "<p>On which of the following fixed assets is depreciation NOT charged?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Land", "Building", "Furniture", "Machinery"],
        correctAnswer: 0,
        explanation: "<p><strong>Land</strong> is an asset with an infinite life and is not subject to physical wear and tear in an accounting sense, so it is not depreciated.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 28,
        text: "<p>The purchase price of a machine is 4,00,000 Taka. If the useful life is 10 years and annual straight-line depreciation is 35,000 Taka, what is the salvage value?</p>",
        meta: "Comilla Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["35,000 Taka", "40,000 Taka", "36,500 Taka", "50,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 3,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Dep = (Cost - Salvage) / Life -> 35,000 = (4,00,000 - Salvage) / 10 -> 3,50,000 = 4,00,000 - Salvage -> Salvage = <strong>50,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 29,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>On January 1, 2020, Tonmoy Co. purchased equipment for 42,000 Taka. Carriage and installation costs were 3,000 Taka. Life is 6 years and salvage value is 6,000 Taka. On January 1, 2023, the equipment was sold for 20,000 Taka. Straight-line method is used.</p><p>Q. What is the amount of profit or loss on the sale?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Loss 1,000 Taka", "Loss 2,500 Taka", "Loss 5,500 Taka", "Loss 7,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<div class='text-xs space-y-1'><p>Cost = 45,000. Annual Dep = (45,000 - 6,000) / 6 = 6,500.</p><p>Accum Dep (3 yrs) = 19,500. Book Value = 25,500.</p><p>Loss = 25,500 - 20,000 = <strong>5,500 Taka (Loss)</strong>.</p></div>"
    },
    {
        id: 30,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2'>On January 1, 2020, Tonmoy Co. purchased equipment for 42,000 Taka. Carriage and installation costs were 3,000 Taka. Life is 6 years and salvage value is 6,000 Taka. Straight-line method is used.</p><p>Q. What is the amount of annual depreciation?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["6,000 Taka", "6,500 Taka", "7,000 Taka", "7,500 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 1,
        explanation: "<p>Annual Dep = (42,00,0 + 3,000 - 6,000) / 6 = 39,000 / 6 = <strong>6,500 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 31,
        text: "<p>Factors that influence the determination of depreciation are-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. Purchase price of the asset<br>ii. Estimated useful life<br>iii. Estimated salvage value</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Jessore Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 3
    },
    {
        id: 32,
        text: "<p>Which of the following is NOT an internal cause of depreciation?</p>",
        meta: "Mymensingh Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["Passage of time", "Wear and tear", "Obsolescence", "Depletion"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p><strong>Obsolescence</strong> (becoming outdated due to technology) is an external factor. Time, wear and tear, and depletion are internal factors inherent to the asset's use.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 33,
        text: "<p>Depreciation is-</p><p class='ml-4 my-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'>i. An invisible transaction<br>ii. A non-cash transaction<br>iii. A cost allocation process for fixed assets</p><p>Which of the following is correct?</p>",
        meta: "Mymensingh Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["i & ii", "i & iii", "ii & iii", "i, ii & iii"],
        correctAnswer: 3
    },
    {
        id: 34,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2 text-[13px]'>Soma Traders purchased a machine on January 1, 2021, for 5,75,000 Taka (including 15% VAT). Installation cost was 25,000 Taka. Life is 10 years and salvage value is 50,000 Taka.</p><p>Q. What is the annual depreciation under the straight-line method?</p>",
        meta: "Mymensingh Board · 2024",
        type: "board",
        options: ["50,000 Taka", "52,500 Taka", "55,000 Taka", "60,000 Taka"],
        correctAnswer: 2,
        explanation: "<p>Total Cost = 5,75,000 + 25,000 = 6,00,000. Annual Dep = (6,00,000 - 50,000) / 10 = <strong>55,000 Taka</strong>.</p>"
    },
    {
        id: 35,
        text: "<p>Read the following stem and answer the question:</p><p class='italic my-2 border-l-4 border-sky-400 pl-3 bg-sky-50 dark:bg-sky-900/10 py-2 text-[13px]'>Soma Traders machine cost was 6,00,000. Life is 10 years and salvage value is 50,000 Taka. Reducing balance method is used.</p><p>Q. What is the depreciation for the second year under the reducing balance method?</p>",
