        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Once bought in the primary market, shares are traded (resold) in the Secondary Market.</p>",
        "id": 3900
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Jamuna Ltd. advertised a prospectus to sell 5,00,000 shares to the public. This market is?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Money Market",
            "Primary Share Market",
            "Secondary Market",
            "Informal Market"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Selling shares directly to the public for the first time via prospectus is the Primary Market.</p>",
        "id": 3901
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which year was the Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE) established?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "1950",
            "1954",
            "1960",
            "1970"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>The Dhaka Stock Exchange was originally incorporated in 1954 as the East Pakistan Stock Exchange.</p>",
        "id": 3902
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Murad bought shares of Padma Bank and sold them after a year. In which market did he trade?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Money Market",
            "Secondary Market",
            "Primary Market",
            "Debt Market"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Since he sold existing shares to another party after holding them, this transaction occurred in the Secondary Market.</p>",
        "id": 3903
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Why do shareholders buy and sell shares in the secondary market?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajuk · -",
        "type": "model",
        "options": [
            "To collect loans",
            "Need for collateral",
            "Need for liquidity",
            "Need to distribute property"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>The secondary market provides liquidity, allowing investors to convert their investments into cash quickly.</p>",
        "id": 3904
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the offer to sell shares to the general public called?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Share Underwriting",
            "Public Offering",
            "Rights Issue",
            "Private Placement"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>A Public Offering (like an IPO) is the formal invitation for the general public to subscribe to shares.</p>",
        "id": 3905
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which financing is secured by specific collateral?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Bond",
            "Debenture",
            "Preferred Share",
            "Common Share"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Unlike debentures (unsecured), Bonds are usually backed by specific physical assets or collateral.</p>",
        "id": 3906
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which one is a short-term financial instrument?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Mutual Fund",
            "Treasury Bill",
            "Bond",
            "Debenture"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Treasury Bills are money market instruments with a maturity of less than one year.</p>",
        "id": 3907
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following companies acts as a Merchant Banker?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "DSE",
            "Janata Bank Ltd.",
            "CRAB",
            "ICB"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>ICB (Investment Corporation of Bangladesh) is a leading merchant banker and institutional investor in Bangladesh.</p>",
        "id": 3908
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is an Equity Security?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Bond",
            "Debenture",
            "Treasury Bill",
            "Share"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Shares represent ownership (equity), while bonds, debentures, and T-bills represent debt.</p>",
        "id": 3909
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is traded in the capital market?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Fixed Assets",
            "Foreign Currency",
            "Bill of Exchange",
            "Debenture"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Debentures are long-term debt securities traded in the capital market. Bills of exchange are money market tools.</p>",
        "id": 3910
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which market do investors buy and sell shares among themselves?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Primary Market",
            "Money Market",
            "Secondary Market",
            "Commercial Market"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>The Secondary Market is the venue for trading between existing investors.</p>",
        "id": 3911
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The capital market of Bangladesh is primarily dependent on which of the following?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Bond",
            "OTC",
            "Share",
            "Sovereign Bond"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>The Bangladesh capital market is heavily dominated by Equity (Shares) rather than debt or bonds.</p>",
        "id": 3912
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which market are debentures sold?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Money Market",
            "Retail Market",
            "Wholesale Market",
            "Bond Market"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Debentures are a type of long-term debt instrument traded in the Bond/Capital Market.</p>",
        "id": 3913
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a money market tool?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Debenture",
            "Share",
            "Commercial Paper",
            "Bond"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Commercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument used by corporations.</p>",
        "id": 3914
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>How many types of capital markets are there?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "2",
            "3",
            "4",
            "5"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>The capital market is divided into two: Primary Market and Secondary Market.</p>",
        "id": 3915
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Where are the shares of listed companies traded?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Bangladesh Bank",
            "Stock Exchange",
            "Loan Control Authority",
            "Insurance Authority"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Listed shares are traded on a licensed Stock Exchange (DSE or CSE).</p>",
        "id": 3916
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Who sells Treasury Bills in the market?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Government",
            "Commercial Bank",
            "Bangladesh Bank",
            "Investment Corporation"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>While it is a government debt, Bangladesh Bank acts as the agent to sell T-Bills to the public/banks.</p>",
        "id": 3917
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which one is used in import-export trade?</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Banker's Acceptance",
            "Line of Credit",
            "Commercial Paper",
            "Revolving Credit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>A Banker's Acceptance is a common short-term credit investment used to finance international trade.</p>",
        "id": 3918
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The purpose of the secondary market is— i. Maintain liquidity, ii. Issue new securities, iii. Access info on securities</p>",
        "meta": "Ideal · -",
        "type": "model",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>The secondary market is for trading existing securities, not issuing new ones (which is the primary market).</p>",
        "id": 3919
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Shares sold by a company through the stock exchange include— i. Primary, ii. Secondary, iii. Preferred</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>(Repeat of Q61) Both new issues and existing trades occur via the exchange infrastructure.</p>",
        "id": 3920
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Functions of Bangladesh Bank include— i. Note & currency issue, ii. Advising govt, iii. Forex reserve management</p>",
        "meta": "Model · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>As the Central Bank, Bangladesh Bank manages the currency, reserves, and acts as the government's banker.</p>",
        "id": 3921
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which year did the stock market resume its operations after the independence of Bangladesh?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "1972",
            "1974",
            "1976",
            "1983"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>After being closed during the liberation war, DSE resumed operations in 1976.</p>",
        "id": 3922
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which market is regulated by the Securities and Exchange Commission?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Capital",
            "Money",
            "Gold",
            "Silver"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>BSEC is the primary regulator for the capital (stock) market.</p>",
        "id": 3923
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a function of Bangladesh Bank?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Accepting deposits from customers",
            "Credit control of commercial banks",
            "Creating credit deposits",
            "Providing loans to customers"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>As the central bank, Bangladesh Bank controls the volume of credit in the economy to maintain stability.</p>",
        "id": 3924
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which is the regulatory body for Microcredit in Bangladesh?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "MRA",
            "SEC",
            "DSE",
            "CSE"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>MRA (Microcredit Regulatory Authority) regulates NGOs and micro-finance institutions.</p>",
        "id": 3925
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The regulatory body of the Money Market is—</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "ICB",
            "BSEC",
            "Central Bank",
            "Sonali Bank"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>The Central Bank (Bangladesh Bank) regulates the short-term money market.</p>",
        "id": 3926
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which year was BSEC established?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "1990",
            "1995",
            "2001",
            "1993"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>BSEC was established on June 8, 1993.</p>",
        "id": 3927
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following can be called Money Laundering?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Sending money from abroad via bills",
            "Sending via Western Union",
            "Sending via banking channels",
            "Sending via Hundi"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Sending money through informal/illegal channels like Hundi is a primary form of money laundering.</p>",
        "id": 3928
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Mr. Ahsan, a garment businessman, secretly transferred 5 Lakh to Malaysia without using Bangladesh Bank channels.\n\nQ: What type of offense has he committed?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Civil offense",
            "Money market offense",
            "Criminal offense",
            "Money Laundering offense"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Illegal cross-border transfer of funds bypassing regulatory channels is a money laundering offense.</p>",
        "id": 3929
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: (Same as above)\n\nQ: How much fine must Mr. Ahsan pay?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "5 Lakh",
            "7.50 Lakh",
            "10 Lakh",
            "12.50 Lakh"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Under the law, the fine for money laundering is at least double the amount involved. ($5 \\times 2 = 10$).</p>",
        "id": 3930
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the meaning of Money Laundering?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Receiving money",
            "Paying money",
            "Money smuggling/laundering",
            "Investment"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>It refers to the process of making \"dirty\" (illegal) money appear \"clean\" or illegal smuggling of funds.</p>",
        "id": 3931
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Money Laundering refers to—</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Legally earning & sending money abroad",
            "Illegally earning or sending money abroad",
            "Assisting economic development",
            "Earning money from abroad"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>It involves the illegal acquisition or the illegal movement of funds across borders.</p>",
        "id": 3932
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which year was the Partnership Act current in Bangladesh enacted?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "1932",
            "1991",
            "1881",
            "2010"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>The Partnership Act of 1932 governs all partnership businesses in the country.</p>",
        "id": 3933
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which Negotiable Instruments Act is effective in Bangladesh?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "1881",
            "1947",
            "1969",
            "1993"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>The Negotiable Instruments Act 1881 covers cheques, bills of exchange, and promissory notes.</p>",
        "id": 3934
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Non-bank financial institutions are operated under which Financial Institution Act?</p>",
        "meta": "City College · -",
        "type": "model",
        "options": [
            "1881",
            "1947",
            "1969",
            "1993"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>The Financial Institutions Act 1993 was specifically created for NBFIs (Non-Bank Financial Institutions).</p>",
        "id": 3935
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which year was the Foreign Exchange Regulation Act passed?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "1932",
            "1947",
            "1991",
            "1994"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>The Foreign Exchange Regulation Act was passed in 1947 to control international transactions.</p>",
        "id": 3936
    }],
            shortCQData: [
// === FIN1_CH2_SHORTCQ_START ===
{
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-001",
        "text": "What is Money Laundering?",
        "answer": "Money laundering is the illegal process of making large amounts of money generated by criminal activity appear to have come from a legitimate source.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-001",
        "text": "What is a Financial Market? Explain.",
        "answer": "1. A financial market is a platform where buyers and sellers trade financial assets such as shares, bonds, and currencies.\n\n2. It acts as an intermediary that funnels savings from surplus units (investors) to deficit units (borrowers/businesses) for economic growth.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-002",
        "text": "What is a Treasury Bill?",
        "answer": "A Treasury Bill (T-Bill) is a short-term debt instrument issued by the government to meet its short-term funding requirements, usually with a maturity of less than one year.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-002",
        "text": "Why was the Money Laundering Prevention Act introduced? Explain.",
        "answer": "1. The act was introduced to prevent the conversion of illegal wealth into legal assets and to stop the financing of terrorism.\n\n2. It aims to protect the integrity of the national financial system and ensure that the economy is not destabilized by the flow of \"black money.\"",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-003",
        "text": "What is a Share?",
        "answer": "A share is the smallest unit into which a company's total capital is divided, representing a portion of ownership in the firm.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-003",
        "text": "What is meant by the Capital Market?",
        "answer": "1. The capital market is a financial market where long-term debt or equity-backed securities are bought and sold.\n\n2. It consists of the primary market (new issues) and the secondary market (trading existing securities) and serves as a hub for long-term investment.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-004",
        "text": "Who is an Underwriter?",
        "answer": "An underwriter is an individual or financial institution (like an investment bank) that guarantees the sale of a company's new securities and assumes the risk if the public does not buy them.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-004",
        "text": "What is meant by the 'Call Money Market'?",
        "answer": "1. The Call Money Market is a segment of the money market where commercial banks and financial institutions borrow and lend funds to each other on an overnight or very short-term basis.\n\n2. It is used primarily to meet temporary liquidity shortages or to maintain the Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR) required by the central bank.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-005",
        "text": "What is the Capital Market?",
        "answer": "The capital market is a financial market in which long-term debt or equity-backed securities (like shares and bonds) are bought and sold to raise capital for businesses and the government.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-005",
        "text": "Show the difference between the Money Market and the Capital Market.",
        "answer": "1. The primary difference is the maturity period: the Money Market is for short-term borrowing (up to 1 year), while the Capital Market is for long-term borrowing (beyond 1 year).\n\n2. Instruments in the money market (like T-Bills) are safer and more liquid, whereas capital market instruments (like shares) involve higher risk but offer higher potential returns.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-006",
        "text": "What is a Bond?",
        "answer": "A bond is a long-term debt instrument under which a borrower (government or corporation) agrees to make interest and principal payments on specific dates to the holders of the bond.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-006",
        "text": "Can the general public buy Bonus Shares? Explain.",
        "answer": "1. No, the general public cannot buy bonus shares directly; they are issued for free only to the existing shareholders of the company.\n\n2. They are distributed by the company using its retained earnings to increase the total number of outstanding shares without paying out cash dividends.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-007",
        "text": "What is the name of the regulatory body for the money market in our country?",
        "answer": "Bangladesh Bank is the regulatory body for the money market in our country.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-007",
        "text": "Show the relationship between the Primary Share Market and the Secondary Share Market.",
        "answer": "1. The primary market is where new shares are issued for the first time, while the secondary market is where previously issued shares are traded among investors.\n\n2. They are complementary; the primary market creates the supply of securities, and the secondary market provides liquidity, allowing investors to sell those securities.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-008",
        "text": "Write the full form of BSEC.",
        "answer": "The full form of BSEC is the Bangladesh Securities and Exchange Commission.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-008",
        "text": "\"Money laundering creates obstacles to economic development\" – Explain.",
        "answer": "1. Money laundering distorts market competition and diverts funds from productive sectors to illegal activities, reducing tax revenue for the government.\n\n2. It increases financial volatility and damages the international reputation of a country's banking system, discouraging foreign investment.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-009",
        "text": "What is BSEC?",
        "answer": "BSEC stands for Bangladesh Securities and Exchange Commission, the regulator of the capital market in Bangladesh.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-009",
        "text": "Who are the participants in the money market?",
        "answer": "1. The main participants are the Central Bank (Bangladesh Bank), commercial banks, non-banking financial institutions (NBFIs), and large corporations.\n\n2. Discount houses and government agencies also participate to manage short-term liquidity and trade short-term debt instruments.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-010",
        "text": "What is liquidity?",
        "answer": "Liquidity refers to how quickly and easily an asset can be converted into cash without a significant loss in its value.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-010",
        "text": "What do you mean by transferable risk?",
        "answer": "1. Transferable risk (or Systematic Risk) refers to the risk that is common to the entire market or a segment and cannot be eliminated through diversification.\n\n2. However, in a financial context, certain risks can be \"transferred\" to another party through insurance or hedging instruments like derivatives.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-011",
        "text": "What is a Treasury Bill?",
        "answer": "A Treasury Bill is a short-term debt instrument issued by the government to meet its short-term funding needs.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-011",
        "text": "What do you mean by the capital market?",
        "answer": "1. The capital market is a financial market where long-term debt or equity-backed securities are traded.\n\n2. It serves as a channel for long-term productive investment in the economy, involving instruments like shares and bonds.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-012",
        "text": "What is a capital market?",
        "answer": "The capital market is the part of a financial system concerned with raising capital by dealing in shares, bonds, and other long-term investments.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-012",
        "text": "What do you mean by a financial institution?",
        "answer": "1. A financial institution is an entity that acts as an intermediary between savers and borrowers, facilitating the flow of funds.\n\n2. Examples include banks, insurance companies, and brokerage firms that provide various financial services to individuals and businesses.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-013",
        "text": "What is equity capital?",
        "answer": "Equity capital is the money raised by a company by issuing common shares, representing the ownership interest of the shareholders.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-013",
        "text": "What is meant by the OTC market?",
        "answer": "1. OTC (Over-the-Counter) market is a decentralized market where securities not listed on a formal exchange (like DSE) are traded directly between parties.\n\n2. It is typically used by smaller or newer companies that do not yet meet the strict listing requirements of a major stock exchange.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-014",
        "text": "What is the Call Money Rate?",
        "answer": "The Call Money Rate is the interest rate charged by banks for overnight or very short-term loans provided to other banks to meet liquidity needs.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-014",
        "text": "Why is credit controlled?",
        "answer": "1. Credit is controlled by the central bank to maintain price stability and manage inflation within the economy.\n\n2. It also ensures that the flow of funds is directed toward productive sectors rather than speculative or illegal activities.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-015",
        "text": "Which organization regulates the share market of Bangladesh?",
        "answer": "The Bangladesh Securities and Exchange Commission (BSEC) is the regulatory body for the share market in Bangladesh.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-015",
        "text": "What do you mean by the primary market?",
        "answer": "1. The primary market is the part of the capital market where new securities are issued and sold to the public for the first time.\n\n2. It allows companies to raise long-term capital directly from investors through instruments like an Initial Public Offering (IPO).",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-016",
        "text": "What is commercial paper?",
        "answer": "Commercial paper is a short-term, unsecured promissory note issued by large, reputable corporations to meet their immediate financial obligations.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-016",
        "text": "What do you mean by a financial market?",
        "answer": "1. A financial market is a mechanism or platform that allows people to easily buy and sell financial securities, commodities, and other fungible items.\n\n2. It facilitates the flow of funds from savers to investors, ensuring that capital is allocated efficiently within the economy.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-017",
        "text": "What is a financial market?",
        "answer": "A financial market is a system where buyers and sellers trade financial assets such as shares, bonds, currencies, and derivatives.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-b-017",
        "text": "What type of companies can sell commercial paper? Explain.",
        "answer": "1. Only large, creditworthy, and highly-rated corporations with a strong financial track record can issue commercial paper.\n\n2. Because it is unsecured (no collateral), investors rely solely on the company's reputation and ability to generate cash flow to repay the debt.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-short-a-018",
