            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is meant by the OTC market?",
                "answer": "1. OTC (Over-the-Counter) market is a decentralized market where securities not listed on a formal exchange (like DSE) are traded directly between parties.\n\n2. It is typically used by smaller or newer companies that do not yet meet the strict listing requirements of a major stock exchange."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "In which type of market does Mr. Sultan invest? Explain based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: Mr. Sultan invests in both the Primary Market and the Secondary Market.\n\n2. Evidence (Primary): The stem mentions he applies for IPOs (Initial Public Offerings), where shares are bought directly from the company.\n\n3. Evidence (Secondary): His activity of buying and selling shares of banks and manufacturing firms at \"fluctuating prices\" happens in the secondary market (Stock Exchange)."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Which method is applicable for risk-free investment? Evaluate based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Applicable Method: For a risk-free investment, the applicable method is investing in Government Securities (Treasury Bills or Bonds).\n\n2. Comparison: Unlike Mr. Sultan's shares, which \"fluctuate constantly\" and face valuation risks, government instruments have a sovereign guarantee.\n\n3. Return Certainty: Risk-free instruments provide a fixed interest rate, protecting the investor from the \"overvaluation or undervaluation\" mentioned in the stem.\n\n4. Conclusion: While Mr. Sultan seeks higher profit through market volatility, an investor seeking safety should avoid the stock market in favor of government-backed debt instruments."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-014",
        "stem": "Mr. Mahin owns an import-export business. He sent TK 10 Crore abroad through \"Hundi\" to purchase goods. The Anti-Corruption Commission noticed this and decided to investigate. When the firm was found guilty, punishment was recommended.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is the Call Money Rate?",
                "answer": "The Call Money Rate is the interest rate charged by banks for overnight or very short-term loans provided to other banks to meet liquidity needs."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is credit controlled?",
                "answer": "1. Credit is controlled by the central bank to maintain price stability and manage inflation within the economy.\n\n2. It also ensures that the flow of funds is directed toward productive sectors rather than speculative or illegal activities."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Which law has the institution mentioned in the stem violated? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: The firm has violated the Money Laundering Prevention Act, 2012.\n\n2. Violation: By sending TK 10 Crore via \"Hundi,\" Mr. Mahin bypassed the legal banking channels and regulatory oversight of the Central Bank.\n\n3. Context: Under this law, transferring money out of the country through unauthorized means is considered a criminal offense linked to money laundering."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "What punishment will the institution face under the current prevailing law? Analyze.",
                "answer": "1. Financial Penalty: Under the Act, the entity can be fined twice the amount of the laundered money (in this case, up to TK 20 Crore).\n\n2. Imprisonment: Individuals involved can face a prison sentence ranging from a minimum of 4 years to a maximum of 12 years.\n\n3. Asset Forfeiture: The court has the power to freeze and confiscate the property or funds involved in the illegal transaction.\n\n4. Conclusion: The legal consequences are severe because such actions drain the country's foreign exchange reserves and undermine the formal financial system."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-015",
        "stem": "The Bangladesh share market plays a vital role in the economy. There are two share markets in the country. The daily transaction volume here is high. A government institution regulates both. The institution works to increase investment in business and industrial firms.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "Which organization regulates the share market of Bangladesh?",
                "answer": "The Bangladesh Securities and Exchange Commission (BSEC) is the regulatory body for the share market in Bangladesh."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What do you mean by the primary market?",
                "answer": "1. The primary market is the part of the capital market where new securities are issued and sold to the public for the first time.\n\n2. It allows companies to raise long-term capital directly from investors through instruments like an Initial Public Offering (IPO)."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Which two share markets are mentioned in the stem? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: The two share markets are the Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE) and the Chittagong Stock Exchange (CSE).\n\n2. DSE: Established in 1954, it is the oldest and largest stock exchange in the country, located in the capital.\n\n3. CSE: Established in 1995, it provides a secondary platform for trading and helps decentralize the capital market activities in Bangladesh."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Describe the role of the government institution mentioned in the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Investor Protection: The BSEC ensures that the rights of small investors are protected from fraud and market manipulation.\n\n2. Market Stability: It monitors daily trade and enforces rules to prevent sudden market crashes or artificial price hikes.\n\n3. Corporate Transparency: The BSEC mandates that listed companies provide audited financial reports to keep the public informed of their true performance.\n\n4. Investment Growth: By maintaining a fair and transparent environment, the institution encourages both local and foreign investors to put money into the industrial sector, driving economic growth."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-016",
        "stem": "Moyna Company Limited is a large organization. Since the company requires short-term financing, it sells commercial paper with a maturity of 90 days. The company sells the commercial paper at a price lower than its face value.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is commercial paper?",
                "answer": "Commercial paper is a short-term, unsecured promissory note issued by large, reputable corporations to meet their immediate financial obligations."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What do you mean by a financial market?",
                "answer": "1. A financial market is a mechanism or platform that allows people to easily buy and sell financial securities, commodities, and other fungible items.\n\n2. It facilitates the flow of funds from savers to investors, ensuring that capital is allocated efficiently within the economy."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "In which market did Moyna Company sell the commercial paper? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: Moyna Company sold the commercial paper in the Money Market.\n\n2. Evidence: The stem mentions a \"short-term requirement\" and a \"90-day maturity,\" which are the defining characteristics of money market instruments.\n\n3. Nature: This market deals with highly liquid, low-risk debt instruments that mature in one year or less, providing corporations with working capital."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "What is the reason for Moyna Company selling commercial paper at a lower price in the stem? Analyze.",
                "answer": "1. Zero-Coupon Nature: Commercial paper is a non-interest-bearing instrument; the return to the investor comes solely from the difference between the purchase price and the face value.\n\n2. Discounting Mechanism: By selling at a \"lower price\" (at a discount), the company provides a built-in profit for the buyer, which serves as the compensation for lending the money.\n\n3. Yield Calculation: The difference between the face value and the discounted price represents the interest earned by the investor over the 90-day period.\n\n4. Conclusion: Therefore, selling at a lower price is the standard technical method for issuing such instruments to attract investors while fulfilling the company's short-term funding needs."
            }
        ]
    },
