    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-021",
        "stem": "Turag Ltd. recently issued new shares. Mr. Shanta applied and received 500 shares through a lottery. On the other hand, Trishna Ltd. is planning to launch a new soft drink requiring large capital. Their application to BSEC for share issuance was rejected, and they lack sufficient cash to start the project.",
        "meta": "Adamjee Cantonment College · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is a financial market?",
                "answer": "A financial market is a system or platform where buyers and sellers trade financial assets such as shares, bonds, and currencies."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is Money Laundering? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Money laundering is the illegal process of concealing the origins of money obtained through criminal activities to make it appear legitimate.\n\n2. It typically involves three stages: placement, layering, and integration to bypass the legal financial system."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Which market is Mr. Shanta's investment related to? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: Mr. Shanta's investment is related to the Primary Market.\n\n2. Evidence: He \"applied\" for \"new shares\" and received them via a \"lottery,\" which describes the Initial Public Offering (IPO) process.\n\n3. Nature: In the primary market, securities are created and sold for the first time directly from the issuer to the investor."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "From which alternative market can Trishna Ltd. collect capital? Give your logic.",
                "answer": "1. Selection: Since public share issuance was rejected by BSEC, Trishna Ltd. should look toward the Money Market or Private Debt Market.\n\n2. Bank Financing: They can apply for long-term loans from commercial banks or specialized financial institutions using their assets as collateral.\n\n3. Lease Financing: To solve the \"lack of cash\" for the project, they could lease the necessary machinery instead of buying it, reducing the upfront capital requirement.\n\n4. Conclusion: By using institutional debt or private equity, the company can still fund its project despite being barred from the public stock exchange."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-022",
        "stem": "Surma Company issues a 3-month unsecured security for TK 4,90,000, with a face value of TK 5,00,000. Meanwhile, Mr. Arif wants to invest with zero insolvency risk. He finds Shapla Co.'s 15-year 15% fixed-income security backed by assets, and a 14% fixed-income government security. On a friend's advice, he invests in Shapla Co.",
        "meta": "Holy Cross College · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is the OTC market?",
                "answer": "The Over-the-Counter (OTC) market is a decentralized market where securities not listed on a formal exchange are traded directly between parties."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why are Treasury Bills issued? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Treasury bills are issued by the government to meet short-term budget deficits and manage liquidity in the economy.\n\n2. They also serve as a tool for the central bank to control the money supply through open market operations."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Which financial market security did Surma Company issue? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: Surma Company issued Commercial Paper.\n\n2. Characteristics: It is \"3-month\" (short-term), \"unsecured\" (no collateral), and sold at a \"discount\" (issued at 4.90L for a 5L face value).\n\n3. Classification: This is a core money market instrument used by highly rated corporations to meet immediate working capital needs."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Evaluate Mr. Arif's investment decision.",
                "answer": "1. Risk Analysis: Mr. Arif’s decision is illogical based on his primary goal of \"zero insolvency risk.\"\n\n2. Default Risk: Shapla Co. is a private entity; even with asset backing, it carries a higher risk of default compared to the government.\n\n3. Sovereign Guarantee: The 14% government security is technically \"risk-free,\" as the government is unlikely to default on its own currency obligations.\n\n4. Conclusion: Mr. Arif traded absolute safety for a 1% higher return, violating his own stated preference for zero risk. He should have chosen the government security."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-023",
        "stem": "Mr. Hasib and Mr. Nasir decided to invest in the financial market. Mr. Hasib used his capital to purchase Commercial Paper and Treasury Bills. On the other hand, Mr. Nasir purchased Common Shares, Preferred Shares, and Bonds.",
        "meta": "Govt. Azizul Haque College · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "Who is the regulator of the money market?",
                "answer": "Bangladesh Bank (the central bank) is the primary regulator of the money market in Bangladesh."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "\"Money laundering creates obstacles to economic development.\" Explain.",
                "answer": "1. It distorts market competition and diverts funds from productive industries into illegal channels, reducing tax revenue.\n\n2. It increases financial instability and can lead to international sanctions, damaging the country's global trade reputation."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "In which type of market did Mr. Hasib invest? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: Mr. Hasib invested in the Money Market.\n\n2. Evidence: Commercial Paper and Treasury Bills are instruments specifically designed for short-term liquidity management.\n\n3. Nature: This market deals with low-risk, highly liquid assets with a maturity period of less than one year."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "If they want to earn profit over a long period, is the investment decision of the two friends logical? Analyze based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Nasir's Logic: Mr. Nasir’s decision is highly logical for \"long-term profit\" because he chose Capital Market instruments (shares/bonds) that offer growth over years.\n\n2. Hasib's Logic: Mr. Hasib’s decision is less logical for the long term, as money market returns usually only cover inflation and lack capital appreciation.\n\n3. Risk-Return Trade-off: Nasir accepts higher market risk for higher long-term returns, while Hasib prioritizes safety, which limits wealth growth.\n\n4. Conclusion: For long-term goals, Nasir's portfolio is superior; Hasib's strategy is only logical if he needs his cash back within a few months."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-024",
        "stem": "The Bangladesh stock market plays a vital role in the economy. There are two stock markets in the country with high daily transaction volumes. A government institution regulates both markets and works to increase investment in business and industrial firms.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Govt. College · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "Which organization regulates the stock market of Bangladesh?",
                "answer": "The Bangladesh Securities and Exchange Commission (BSEC) is the regulatory body for the stock market in Bangladesh."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is meant by the primary market?",
                "answer": "1. The primary market is the part of the capital market where new securities are issued and sold to the public for the first time.\n\n2. It allows companies to raise fresh long-term capital directly from investors through instruments like an Initial Public Offering (IPO)."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Which two stock markets are mentioned in the stem? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: The two stock markets are the Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE) and the Chittagong Stock Exchange (CSE).\n\n2. DSE: Established in 1954, it is the oldest and largest exchange in the country, acting as the primary hub for capital.\n\n3. CSE: Established in 1995, it provides a secondary platform for trading and helps decentralize capital market activities across the country."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Describe the role of the government institution mentioned in the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Investor Protection: The BSEC ensures the rights of small investors are protected from fraud and market manipulation.\n\n2. Market Stability: It monitors daily trade and enforces rules to prevent artificial price hikes or sudden market crashes.\n\n3. Corporate Transparency: It mandates that listed companies provide audited financial reports to keep the public informed of true performance.\n\n4. Investment Growth: By maintaining a fair environment, it encourages both local and foreign investors to fund the industrial sector, driving economic growth."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-025",
        "stem": "Mr. Riyadh is a low-salaried employee. Encouraged by a colleague, he applied for primary shares and now occasionally buys secondary shares. At the annual general meeting (AGM), he learned he is a part-owner of the company and can even vote to elect the board of directors.",
        "meta": "Cantonment Public School & College, Mymensingh · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is money laundering?",
                "answer": "Money laundering is the illegal process of making large amounts of money generated by criminal activity appear to have come from a legitimate source."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is the money market important? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. The money market provides short-term liquidity to banks, businesses, and the government, ensuring they can meet immediate financial obligations.\n\n2. It allows the central bank to implement monetary policy and control the money supply to maintain price stability."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What type of company's shares does Mr. Riyadh buy? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: Mr. Riyadh buys shares of a Public Limited Company.\n\n2. Ownership: Only public limited companies are allowed to issue shares to the general public through the stock exchange.\n\n3. Rights: The ability to attend an AGM and vote for the board of directors is a fundamental right of common shareholders in a public limited company."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "How logical is the investment in secondary shares for Mr. Riyadh? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Liquidity: Secondary shares are highly liquid, meaning Mr. Riyadh can sell them quickly if he needs cash for an emergency.\n\n2. Dividend Income: As a low-salaried employee, the periodic dividends provide an additional source of income to supplement his earnings.\n\n3. Capital Gains: If the company performs well, the market price of the shares will rise, increasing his overall wealth.\n\n4. Conclusion: It is logical as long as he diversifies his risk; it offers a path to wealth accumulation that a simple savings account cannot provide."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-026",
        "stem": "Harun, Rafiq, and Sarkar formed a business based on an agreement. Though they provided equal capital, Harun enjoys half the profits and losses. To raise new capital, they want to add 20 more members. They need a registration certificate but not a certificate of commencement.",
        "meta": "Ispahani Public School & College, Cumilla · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is the money market?",
                "answer": "The money market is a component of the financial market for short-term borrowing and lending with a maturity of one year or less."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "\"Money laundering is an obstacle to economic development.\" Explain.",
                "answer": "1. It distorts market competition and diverts funds from productive sectors to illegal activities, reducing tax revenue for the government.\n\n2. It damages the international reputation of a country's financial system, which can discourage foreign direct investment."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What type of business did the three friends first form based on ownership? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: The initial business is a Partnership Business.\n\n2. Agreement: The mention of a \"consensual basis\" or agreement where profits are shared unequally (Harun getting half) is a hallmark of a partnership.\n\n3. Capital: Partners contribute capital and share risks based on the terms specified in their partnership deed."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "What type of institution do you think the new institution will be? Give logic based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Member Count: The intention to add \"20 more members\" fits within the legal limit for a certain type of corporate entity.\n\n2. Legal Requirement: Needing a \"registration certificate\" but NOT a \"certificate of commencement\" is the defining legal trait of a Private Limited Company.\n\n3. Capital Structure: Private limited companies allow for more members than a partnership (up to 50) but do not trade shares publicly on the stock exchange.\n\n4. Conclusion: Therefore, based on the specific legal document requirements mentioned, they are forming a Private Limited Company."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-027",
        "stem": "Mr. Karim and 15 entrepreneurs formed Talukdar Capital Ltd. with a paid-up capital of TK 400 Crore. The firm acts as an underwriter and invests in shares of various companies. Meanwhile, Mr. Zaman, financial manager of Rahim Traders Ltd., wants to profit from the stock market by considering price fluctuations and liquidity.",
        "meta": "Abdul Kadir Mollah City College, Narsingdi · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is the full form of IDRA?",
                "answer": "IDRA stands for the Insurance Development and Regulatory Authority of Bangladesh."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is credit controlled? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Credit is controlled to maintain price stability and prevent high inflation within the economy.\n\n2. It also ensures that financial resources are directed toward productive sectors rather than speculative or illegal activities."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What type of institution is Mr. Karim's firm? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: Mr. Karim’s firm is a Non-Banking Financial Institution (NBFI), specifically an Investment Bank or Merchant Bank.\n\n2. Evidence: The stem mentions the firm acts as an \"underwriter\" and invests in other companies' shares, which are core functions of investment banking.\n\n3. Capital Structure: With 15 entrepreneurs and TK 400 Crore capital, it operates as a specialized intermediary in the capital market."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Between the two markets in the stem, which one should Mr. Zaman invest in? Give logic.",
                "answer": "1. Market Choice: Mr. Zaman should prioritize the Secondary Market.\n\n2. Liquidity: Since he is concerned with \"liquidity,\" the secondary market allows him to sell shares instantly to convert them into cash.\n\n3. Price Fluctuations: The stem notes he considers \"constant price changes,\" which only occur in the secondary market (Stock Exchange) rather than the fixed-price primary market.\n\n4. Conclusion: For an active manager looking for profit through trading and price movement, the secondary market is the most logical choice."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-028",
        "stem": "Mr. Rafiq and Mr. Aslam decided to invest in the financial market. Mr. Rafiq used his total capital to purchase Commercial Paper and Treasury Bills. On the other hand, Mr. Aslam used his total capital to purchase Common Shares, Preferred Shares, and Bonds.",
        "meta": "Safiuddin Sarker Academy & College, Gazipur · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "Who is an underwriter?",
                "answer": "An underwriter is a financial intermediary (usually a bank) that guarantees the sale of a company's new securities and assumes the risk of unsold shares."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Can the general public buy bonus shares? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. No, the general public cannot buy bonus shares directly; they are issued for free only to existing shareholders.\n\n2. They are distributed from the company's retained earnings to capitalize profits without paying out cash."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Based on the stem, in which type of market did Mr. Rafiq invest? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: Mr. Rafiq invested in the Money Market.\n\n2. Evidence: Commercial Paper and Treasury Bills are short-term debt instruments with maturities of less than one year.\n\n3. Nature: This market is suitable for investors seeking high liquidity and low risk for their capital."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "If they want to earn profit over a long period, whose investment decision is more logical? Evaluate based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Aslam's Logic: Mr. Aslam’s decision is more logical for long-term profit as he invested in Capital Market instruments (shares/bonds).\n\n2. Growth Potential: Common shares offer capital appreciation and dividends over time, which short-term money market instruments cannot provide.\n\n3. Compounding: Long-term debt like bonds and equity provides higher cumulative returns compared to 90-day commercial papers.\n\n4. Conclusion: While Mr. Rafiq is safe in the short term, Mr. Aslam’s portfolio is better designed for long-term wealth maximization."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch2-cq-029",
        "stem": "Abir Company Ltd. decided to collect capital by selling shares for expansion. Meanwhile, Mr. Atiq, a garment importer, earned a large amount of money through illegal means and deposited it in 'NX' Bank in Kolkata. Bangladesh Bank investigated and took legal action against him.",
        "meta": "Govt. Commerce College, Chattogram · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is a financial market?",
                "answer": "A financial market is a platform or system where buyers and sellers trade financial assets like shares, bonds, and currencies."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What type of institution is the Microcredit Regulatory Authority (MRA)? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. The MRA is a Statutory Regulatory Body established by the government to monitor and regulate microfinance institutions in Bangladesh.\n\n2. It ensures transparency, protects borrowers, and sets the standards for micro-lending operations."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "From which type of market did Abir Company Ltd. collect capital? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Identification: Abir Company Ltd. collected capital from the Capital Market (specifically the Primary Market).\n\n2. Method: By \"selling shares,\" they are inviting the public to provide permanent capital for the business.\n\n3. Purpose: The capital market is the appropriate venue for \"business expansion\" which requires long-term, non-refundable funding."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "According to the law, Mr. Atiq's business activity is illegal—Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Legal Violation: Mr. Atiq's activity falls under Money Laundering and Capital Flight.\n\n2. Money Laundering Act: Under the Money Laundering Prevention Act, 2012, earning money through \"illegal means\" is a primary offense.\n\n3. Unauthorized Transfer: Smuggling money to a foreign bank (Kolkata) without legal declaration violates the Foreign Exchange Regulation Act.\n\n4. Conclusion: Such actions undermine the national economy and drain foreign reserves, making the legal action by Bangladesh Bank entirely justified."
            }
        ]
    }
