    {
        "text": "<p>Which is the formula for calculating Effective Interest Rate (EIR)?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "$$EIR = (1 + \\frac{i}{m})^m - 1$$",
            "$EIR = (1 + \\frac{i}{m})^{mn} - 1$",
            "$EIR = (1 + i)^m = 1$",
            "$EIR = (1 + \\frac{i}{m})^n - 1$"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>The Effective Interest Rate represents the real return on an investment or the real cost of a loan. When interest is compounded multiple times within a single year, the actual rate paid or earned is slightly higher than the nominal rate.Option (b) is incorrect because it includes $n$ (total number of years) in the exponent. EIR is calculated for a single year to compare different compounding frequencies.Option (c) is incorrect as it uses an equals sign ($=$) instead of a minus sign ($-$) before the 1, and it misses the division of the rate by the compounding frequency $m$.Option (d) is incorrect because it uses $n$ as the exponent instead of $m$. The exponent must match the number of times interest is divided and added within that year.</p>",
        "id": 3998
    },
    {
