        "explanation": "<p>Compound interest is calculated on the accumulated balance (Principal + previous Interest).</p>",
        "id": 4000
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which annual annuity must be paid/received at the end of the period?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Perpetuity",
            "Annuity Due",
            "Ordinary Annuity",
            "Deferred Annuity"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Payments at the end of each period are classified as an Ordinary Annuity.</p>",
        "id": 4001
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Elements considered in each installment of a loan amortization schedule—\n\ni. Principal\n\nii. Interest\n\niii. Commission</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Installments consist only of principal repayment and interest. Commission is not part of the schedule.</p>",
        "id": 4002
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Miss Sworna invests TK 4,00,000 in CBC Bank for 10 years at 8% interest.\n\nQ: According to Rule 72, in how much time will her investment double?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "7 years",
            "10 years",
            "8 years",
            "9 years"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$n = 72 \\div 8 = 9$ years.</p>",
        "id": 4003
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: (Same as above)\n\nQ: If the bank provides semi-annual compounding, what is the Effective Interest Rate (EIR)?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "7.16%",
            "9.16%",
            "8.16%",
            "10.16%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$EIR = (1 + \\frac{0.08}{2})^2 - 1 = (1.04)^2 - 1 = 0.0816 \\rightarrow 8.16\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4004
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is it called when equal amounts are paid or received at the beginning of each year?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Annuity Due",
            "Ordinary Annuity",
            "Deferred Annuity",
            "Future Value"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Payments at the start/beginning of a period are called Annuity Due (অগ্রীম বার্ষিকী).</p>",
        "id": 4005
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If TK 9,000 doubles in 9 years, what is the interest rate according to Rule 72?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "5%",
            "8%",
            "9%",
            "10%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$i = 72 \\div 9 = 8\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4006
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Reasons for time preference of money are—\n\ni. Inflation\n\nii. Uncertainty\n\niii. Investment opportunity</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>These three factors make a Taka today worth more than a Taka tomorrow.</p>",
        "id": 4007
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>With the passage of time—\n\ni. Purchasing power decreases\n\nii. Value of money increases\n\niii. Price of goods increases</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Inflation causes prices to rise (iii), which means the value/purchasing power of money falls (i).</p>",
        "id": 4008
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the number of compounding periods ($m$) for Fortnightly (Bi-weekly) compounding?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "24",
            "18",
            "12",
            "6"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>A fortnight is 2 weeks. Since there are 52 weeks in a year, $m = 52 \\div 2 = 26$. (Note: Exams often use 24 as a simplified \"twice-a-month\" calculation).</p>",
        "id": 4009
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the cash outflow that occurs at the beginning of a project called?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Investment Flow",
            "Mixed Flow",
            "Annuity Flow",
            "Cumulative Flow"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>The initial money spent to start a project is the Investment Outlay/Flow.</p>",
        "id": 4010
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which compounding frequency will the Future Value be the highest?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Fortnightly",
            "Quarterly",
            "Monthly",
            "Semi-annually"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>The higher the frequency ($m$), the higher the <code>FV</code>. Fortnightly (24 or 26) > Monthly (12) > Quarterly (4).</p>",
        "id": 4011
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What kind of relationship exists between Compounding and Discounting?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Direct",
            "Proportional",
            "Inverse/Opposite",
            "Neutral"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>They are mathematical opposites; one moves money forward in time, the other brings it back.</p>",
        "id": 4012
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Mr. Shakil opens an account for 10 years by depositing TK 27,000 at 12% interest.\n\nQ: What type of cash flow is this?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Lump Sum",
            "Annuity",
            "Mixed",
            "Unequal"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>A single deposit left for a duration is a Lump Sum (এককালীন) flow.</p>",
        "id": 4013
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which is the formula for the Future Value of a single cash flow?</p>",
        "meta": "Ctg · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "$FV = PV(1 + i)^{nm}$",
            "$FV = PV(1 + i)^n$",
            "$FV = PV(1 + i)n$",
            "$FV = PV(1 + \\frac{i}{m})^n$"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Since the question asks for the standard formula for a single cash flow (typically assuming annual compounding), Option B is the fundamental choice.</p>",
        "id": 4014
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Factors to consider in determining Time Value of Money—\n\ni. Time\n\nii. Interest Rate\n\niii. No. of compounding periods</p>",
        "meta": "Ctg · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three variables ($n, i, m$) are essential for the calculation.</p>",
        "id": 4015
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Mr. Babu deposits TK 5,00,000 for 6 years and receives double the amount at the end.\n\nQ: What type of cash flow is this?</p>",
        "meta": "Ctg · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Ordinary Annuity",
            "Mixed Cash Flow",
            "Annuity Due",
            "Single Cash Flow"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>One deposit at the start and one receipt at the end makes it a Single (Lump Sum) flow.</p>",
        "id": 4016
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Mr. Babu deposits TK 5,00,000 for 6 years and receives double the amount at the end.\n\nQ: What is the interest rate received by Mr. Babu?</p>",
        "meta": "Ctg · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "8.91%",
            "12.25%",
            "16.67%",
            "20%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Using Rule 72: $i = 72 \\div 6 = 12\\%$. Option (b) 12.25% is the precise compounded value.</p>",
        "id": 4017
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The main reason for the decrease in money's purchasing power over time is—</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Deflation",
            "Inflation",
            "Exchange rate increase",
            "Deposit rate increase"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Inflation is the persistent rise in prices, reducing what a single Taka can buy.</p>",
        "id": 4018
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>How much must be invested to receive TK 1,000 annually forever at 10% interest?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "10,000",
            "11,000",
            "11,500",
            "11,100"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Perpetuity formula: <code>PV</code> = \\frac{A}{i} = \\frac{1,000}{0.10} = 10,000$.</p>",
        "id": 4019
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>To determine the Future Value of money, you need—\n\ni. Present Value\n\nii. Interest Rate\n\niii. Number of years</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three (<code>PV</code>, i, n$) are variables in the formula <code>FV</code> = <code>PV</code>(1+i)^n$.</p>",
        "id": 4020
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>For which compounding frequency will the Present Value (<code>PV</code>) be the lowest?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Fortnightly",
            "Monthly",
            "Quarterly",
            "Semi-annually"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>The more frequent the compounding ($m$), the lower the <code>PV</code> (and the higher the <code>FV</code>).</p>",
        "id": 4021
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Mr. Hanif deposits TK 20,000 for 10 years at 10% compound interest.\n\nQ: What type of cash flow is his deposit?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Ordinary Annuity",
            "Annuity Due",
            "Lump Sum Flow",
            "Mixed Cash Flow"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>A single deposit made once is a Lump Sum (এককালীন) cash flow.</p>",
        "id": 4022
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: (Same as above)\n\nQ: How much will Mr. Hanif receive after 10 years?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "61,446",
            "51,975",
            "51,875",
            "7,711"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p><code>FV</code> = 20,000(1.10)^{10} = 20,000 \\times 2.5937 \\approx 51,875$ (rounded to 51,975 in some tables).</p>",
        "id": 4023
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the reverse method of Discounting?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Devaluation",
            "Compounding",
            "Annualization",
            "Valuation"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Compounding moves money forward; Discounting brings it back.</p>",
        "id": 4024
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In the case of compound interest—\n\ni. Interest is calculated on Principal + Interest\n\nii. Calculated only on principal\n\niii. Previous year's interest is treated as principal</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Compound interest reinvests previous earnings (iii), effectively charging interest on the new total (i).</p>",
        "id": 4025
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is required to determine the Present Value of a cash flow?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Liquidity",
            "Net Profit",
            "NPV",
            "Discount Rate"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>You cannot calculate <code>PV</code> without a discount rate (the required rate of return).</p>",
        "id": 4026
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Reasons for time preference of money—\n\ni. Risk reduction\n\nii. Consumption preference\n\niii. Uncertainty</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>People prefer money now to avoid risk/uncertainty and to spend it immediately.</p>",
        "id": 4027
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which rule helps find the time to double an amount with continuous/bi-annual compounding?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Rule 75",
            "Rule 68",
            "Rule 69",
            "Rule 70"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Rule 69 is used for non-annual or continuous compounding doubling periods.</p>",
        "id": 4028
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which is the formula for Simple Interest?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "$P \\times n \\times i$",
            "$PV(1+i)^n$",
            "$A/i$",
            "$m(1+i/m)$"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Simple Interest ($I$) = Principal $\\times$ Time $\\times$ Rate.</p>",
        "id": 4029
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Ms. Shamima wants to build a fund of TK 50,00,000 in 5 years at 9% interest.\n\nQ: How much should she deposit now?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "32,49,659 Tk",
            "30,49,659 Tk",
            "31,49,659 Tk",
            "33,49,659 Tk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p><code>PV</code> = \\frac{5,000,000}{(1.09)^5} = 3,249,658.7$.</p>",
        "id": 4030
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: (Same as above)\n\nQ: The benefit she receives by keeping money in the bank can be called?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Production Cost",
            "Opportunity Cost",
            "Capital Cost",
            "Future Cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>By choosing the bank, she \"gives up\" other uses for that money; the return is the benefit of her choice.</p>",
        "id": 4031
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>A deposit/receipt of TK 2,000 made on Jan 1, 2023 for 5 years is what type of flow?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Annuity Due",
            "Ordinary Annuity",
            "Deferred Annuity",
            "Perpetual Annuity"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Since it starts on January 1 (start of the period), it is an Annuity Due.</p>",
        "id": 4032
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is interest charged on both principal and interest called?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Simple Interest",
            "Nominal Interest",
            "Real Interest",
            "Compound Interest"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>This is the fundamental definition of Compound Interest.</p>",
        "id": 4033
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In a loan amortization schedule, which of these is always equal?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Ending Balance",
            "Installment amount",
            "Principal portion",
            "Starting Balance"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>In standard amortization, the Installment (PMT) remains constant throughout the term.</p>",
        "id": 4034
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Mr. Sajib borrows TK 1,200 at 6% interest.\n\nQ: How much extra (interest) must he pay after 3 years in simple interest?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "116",
            "216",
            "261",
            "332"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$I = 1,200 \\times 3 \\times 0.06 = 216$.</p>",
        "id": 4035
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: (Same as above)\n\nQ: Under compound interest, after 3 years—\n\ni. <code>FV</code> will be 1,429\n\nii. Interest will be 229\n\niii. Compound > Simple</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p><code>FV</code> = 1,200(1.06)^3 = 1,429.21$. Interest $= 229$. Compound (229) > Simple (216).</p>",
        "id": 4036
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Tawsif took a loan of TK 2,00,000 from Bank \"Y\". The bank will collect it over the next 5 years in installments with 10% interest. How much is the installment?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "49,390 Tk",
            "51,790 Tk",
            "52,760 Tk",
            "53,600 Tk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Using <code>PV</code>A = A \\times [\\frac{1-(1+i)^{-n}}{i}]$:\n\n$200,000 = A \\times 3.7908$; $A \\approx 52,760$.</p>",
        "id": 4037
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Determinants of Time Value of Money—\n\ni. Consumption\n\nii. Liquidity of money\n\niii. Interest Rate</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Liquidity and Interest Rates are the core financial determinants. Consumption is a behavioral preference but not a mathematical determinant.</p>",
        "id": 4038
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Mr. Abir deposited TK 1,00,000 in Bank \"P\" for 5 years. The amount will double at the end of the term.\n\nQ: What type of cash flow is this?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Mixed Cash Flow",
            "Lump Sum Flow",
            "Annuity Due",
            "Ordinary Annuity"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>A single deposit left to grow is a Lump Sum (এককালীন) flow.</p>",
        "id": 4039
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: (Same as above)\n\nQ: What interest rate will Mr. Abir receive?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "14.40%",
            "14.87%",
            "15.45%",
            "15.87%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Using Rule 72: $i = 72 \\div 5 = 14.4\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4040
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Mr. Shakil opens an account by depositing TK 27,000 for 10 years at 12% interest.\n\nQ: How much will his deposit be worth after 10 years?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "81,253",
            "82,757",
            "83,858",
            "84,525"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p><code>FV</code> = 27,000(1.12)^{10} = 27,000 \\times 3.1058 \\approx 83,858$.</p>",
        "id": 4041
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>When are the Present Value and Future Value of an investment equal?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Tenure is zero",
            "Tenure is 1 year",
            "Interest is 1%",
            "Compounding is 1"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>If time ($n$) is 0, no interest is added, so <code>PV</code> = <code>FV</code>.</p>",
        "id": 4042
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What remains indefinite/unknown in a Perpetuity?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Amount of flow",
            "Time interval",
            "Final deadline",
            "Interest Rate"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>A perpetuity is an infinite stream of payments, so it has no end date (deadline).</p>",
        "id": 4043
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Simple interest is calculated based on what?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Principal",
            "Interest + Principal",
            "Profit",
            "Expenditure"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Simple interest only applies to the original principal.</p>",
        "id": 4044
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: Mr. Rafiq wants to buy a bike for TK 80,000 in 5 years. Janata Bank offers 8% annual interest. Pubali Bank offers 7% semi-annual interest.\n\nQ: How much must he deposit now in Janata Bank?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "40,450",
            "50,447",
            "45,450",
            "54,447"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p><code>PV</code> = \\frac{80,000}{(1.08)^5} = 54,446.6 \\approx 54,447$.</p>",
        "id": 4045
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Stem: (Same as above)\n\nQ: Which of the following is correct for Mr. Rafiq?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Less deposit in Janata",
            "Less deposit in Pubali",
            "Equal in both",
            "Pubali is half of Janata"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Pubali Bank's EAR is higher due to compounding ($7.12\\%$), but its nominal rate is lower. Actually, calculating both: <code>PV</code>_{Pubali} = 56,713$. Therefore, Janata Bank requires a lower initial deposit.</p>",
        "id": 4046
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The Effective Interest Rate is higher than the Nominal Interest Rate because—\n\ni. Interest is calculated after specific intervals (compounding).\nii. Interest is calculated on the initial deposit.\niii. Interest is calculated on the principal plus interest (compounded amount).</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Compounding (i) and interest-on-interest (iii) are why EIR > Nominal rate.</p>",
        "id": 4047
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is Compounding?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Technique for PV",
            "Technique for FV",
            "Technique for Annuity",
            "Technique for $m$"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Compounding is finding Future Value by adding periodic interest.</p>",
        "id": 4048
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is it called when equal cash flows occur at the end of every year for a specific period?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Present Value",
            "Future Value",
            "Annuity Due",
            "Ordinary Annuity"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>\"End of period\" + \"Equal amounts\" = Ordinary Annuity.</p>",
        "id": 4049
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>When will the Effective Interest Rate (EIR) be the highest?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "If the interest rate is $1\\%$",
            "If the number of compounding periods is $1$ (Annual)",
