        "id": 4335
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>AB Ltd. sells toys for 90. Unit variable cost is 50 and annual fixed cost is 1,80,000. What is the BEP in units?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "2,000",
            "3,600",
            "4,500",
            "6,000"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$$BEP = \\frac{1,80,000}{90 - 50} = \\frac{1,80,000}{40} = 4,500$$ units.</p>",
        "id": 4336
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>AB Ltd. wants to earn 1,20,000 profit. What should be the total Sales in Taka? (Price: 90, VC: 50, FC: 1,80,000)</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "3,00,000",
            "4,20,000",
            "6,75,000",
            "7,25,000"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$$Units = \\frac{1,80,000+1,20,000}{40} = 7,500$$. $$Sales = 7,500 \\t\t\times 90 = 6,75,000$$ TK.</p>",
        "id": 4337
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Nasir: Variable cost 120, Selling price 180, Rent 36,000, and Salary 60,000. What is the Contribution Margin per packet?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "300",
            "180",
            "120",
            "60"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$$CM = Price - VC = 180 - 120 = 60$$ TK.</p>",
        "id": 4338
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Nasir: VC 120, Price 180, Total Fixed Cost (36k+60k)=96,000. What is the BEP in units?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "1,100",
            "1,200",
            "1,300",
            "1,600"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$$BEP = \\frac{96,000}{180 - 120} = \\frac{96,000}{60} = 1,600$$ units.</p>",
        "id": 4339
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the distance between the Break-Even Point and actual sales called?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Safety Distance",
            "Operating Leverage",
            "Cost Distance",
            "Surplus Distance"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>This is commonly known as the \"Margin of Safety.\"</p>",
        "id": 4340
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following influences the determination of the Break-Even Point?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Operating Ratio",
            "Fixed Cost",
            "Financial Leverage",
            "Net Income"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>BEP is directly affected by Fixed Costs, Selling Price, and Variable Costs.</p>",
        "id": 4341
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Abu Jafar Cotton Mills: Price 120, VC 80, BEP units 200. What is the Total Fixed Cost?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "7,000",
            "8,000",
            "9,000",
            "10,000"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$$Fixed Cost = BEP (Units) \\t\t\times (Price - VC) = 200 \\t\t\times (120 - 80) = 8,000$$ TK.</p>",
        "id": 4342
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Salam Enterprise: Price 20, Production Cost (VC) 15. What additional information is needed to calculate BEP?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Variable Cost",
            "Annual Expense",
            "Fixed Cost",
            "All of these"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Since Price and VC are known, the missing component for the BEP formula is the Fixed Cost.</p>",
        "id": 4343
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>To increase profit, what could Salam Enterprise do? (i) Increase unit price (ii) Reduce annual expense (iii) Reduce fixed cost.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three actions (increasing revenue or decreasing costs) result in higher profit.</p>",
        "id": 4344
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Saif & Co: Price 10, VC 4, Fixed Cost 1,800. What is the BEP in units?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "200",
            "300",
            "400",
            "500"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$$BEP = \\frac{1,800}{10 - 4} = \\frac{1,800}{6} = 300$$ units.</p>",
        "id": 4345
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What step can Saif & Co. take to increase profit?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Reduce VC",
            "Increase Price",
            "Increase Sales Volume",
            "Reduce Fixed Cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>While all help, reducing Fixed Cost (Option D) is a direct structural improvement to profit margins.</p>",
        "id": 4346
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which condition indicates the Break-Even Point?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Sales = VC",
            "Sales = FC",
            "VC = FC",
            "Total Sales = Total Cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>The BEP is the point where Total Revenue (Sales) exactly covers Total Costs (FC + VC).</p>",
        "id": 4347
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Arif Ltd. sold 10,000 units at 20 each. VC is 10 and FC is 1,15,000. What is the BEP?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "10,000 units",
            "11,500 units",
            "12,000 units",
            "12,500 units"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$$BEP = \\frac{1,15,000}{20 - 10} = 11,500$$ units.</p>",
        "id": 4348
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Arif Ltd: Fixed Cost 1,15,000, Unit Price 20, VC 10. To earn a profit of 50,000, how many units must be sold?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "10,000",
            "11,500",
            "12,000",
            "16,500"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$$Required Units = \\frac{1,15,000 + 50,000}{20 - 10} = \\frac{1,65,000}{10} = 16,500$$ units.</p>",
        "id": 4349
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Factors influencing the determination of the Break-Even Point (BEP): (i) Fixed Cost (ii) Variable Cost (iii) Opportunity Cost. Which is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Standard BEP calculation relies on Fixed Cost, Variable Cost, and Selling Price. Opportunity cost is not a direct variable in the BEP formula.</p>",
        "id": 4350
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Ashraf runs City Park Restaurant. VC per meal is 120, Selling Price 180, Monthly Rent 3,000, and Salary 15,000. What is the Contribution Margin per meal?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "300",
            "180",
            "120",
            "60"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$$Contribution Margin = Price - VC = 180 - 120 = 60$$ TK.</p>",
        "id": 4351
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>City Park Restaurant: Monthly Fixed Cost (3,000 + 15,000) = 18,000. CM per meal = 60. How many meals result in zero profit/loss?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "300",
            "250",
            "150",
            "100"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$$BEP (Units) = \\frac{18,000}{60} = 300$$ meals.</p>",
        "id": 4352
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Components for calculating Operating Break-Even Point: (i) Fixed Cost (ii) Unit Selling Price (iii) Unit Variable Cost. Which is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three components are necessary to solve the BEP equation: $$BEP = \\frac{FC}{P - VC}$$.</p>",
        "id": 4353
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Fixed cost is 30,000, Unit VC is 40, and Unit Price is 70. How many units must be sold for operating profit to be zero?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "700",
            "800",
            "1,000",
            "1,150"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$$BEP = \\frac{30,000}{70 - 40} = \\frac{30,000}{30} = 1,000$$ units.</p>",
        "id": 4354
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which condition indicates the Break-Even Point?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Cost > Income",
            "Income = Cost",
            "Current Cost < Fixed Cost",
            "Sales = Profit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>BEP is defined as the point where Total Revenue equals Total Cost.</p>",
        "id": 4355
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the point where a firm's income and expenses are equal?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Equal Point",
            "Break-Even Point",
            "Equal Income Point",
            "Equal Expense Point"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>The formal term is Break-Even Point (or সম আয়-ব্যয় বিন্দু in Bengali).</p>",
        "id": 4356
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>A factory produces 200 units for TK 2,000. Now they decide to produce 240 units for TK 2,400. What is the Marginal Cost?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "40",
            "100",
            "400",
            "1,000"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$$Marginal Cost = Change in Total Cost = 2,400 - 2,000 = 400$$ TK (for the extra 40 units).</p>",
        "id": 4357
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a fixed operating cost?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Rent",
            "Interest",
            "Tax",
            "Wages"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Rent is a typical fixed operating cost. Interest is a financial cost; wages are often variable/semi-variable.</p>",
        "id": 4358
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a variable cost?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Employee Salary",
            "Raw material purchase",
            "Office Rent",
            "Depreciation"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Raw material costs change directly with production volume.</p>",
        "id": 4359
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the difference between Total Sales and Total Variable Cost called?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Contribution Margin",
            "Margin of Safety",
            "Profit Margin",
            "Total Margin"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Contribution Margin = Sales - Variable Costs.</p>",
        "id": 4360
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If Fixed Costs increase, what change occurs in the Break-Even Point (Units)?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Decreases",
            "Increases",
            "Both possible",
            "Unchanged"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Since Fixed Cost is the numerator in the BEP formula, an increase leads to a higher BEP.</p>",
        "id": 4361
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Methods for determining the Break-Even Point: (i) Equation Method (ii) Ratio Analysis (iii) Graphic/Linear Method. Which is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>BEP is primarily solved via algebraic equations or graphical representation.</p>",
        "id": 4362
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Fixed Cost 3,50,000, Target Profit 1,00,000, Price 50, and VC 25. What is the Break-Even Sales in units?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "24,000",
            "14,000",
            "1,400",
            "1,500"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$$BEP = \\frac{3,50,000}{50 - 25} = \\frac{3,50,000}{25} = 14,000$$ units.</p>",
        "id": 4363
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Fixed Cost 3,50,000, Target Profit 1,00,000, Price 50, and VC 25. How many units to sell to reach the target profit?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "20,000",
            "18,000",
            "40,000",
            "45,000"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$$Required Units = \\frac{3,50,000 + 1,00,000}{25} = \\frac{4,50,000}{25} = 18,000$$ units.</p>",
        "id": 4364
    }], shortCQData: [], fullCQData: [] },
        "5": { subjectName: "Finance 1st Paper", chapterName: "Chapter 5 : Short-term Finance", mcqData: [{
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is considered a source of spontaneous financing?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh Board · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Trade Credit",
            "Commercial Bank",
            "Bank Loan",
            "Microfinance Institution"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Spontaneous financing arises from daily operations without formal negotiation.</p>",
        "id": 4365
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is an example of an institutional source of finance?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh Board · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Village Moneylender",
            "Shares",
            "Commercial Bank",
            "Bond"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Commercial banks are formal, regulated financial institutions.</p>",
        "id": 4366
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What type of debt is created when goods and materials are purchased on credit?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Cash Loan",
            "Bank Loan",
            "Trade Credit",
            "Overdraft"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Trade credit is the debt created between a buyer and a seller during a credit purchase.</p>",
        "id": 4367
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which type of loan does the borrower NOT keep possession of the mortgaged goods?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Warehouse Receipt Loan",
            "Trust Receipt Loan",
            "Floating Mortgage",
            "Legal Mortgage"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>In warehouse receipt loans, the bank or a third party holds the goods as security.</p>",
        "id": 4368
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Tuya Potato Chips Ltd. uses 9,000 maunds of potatoes annually. If the ordering cost is 300 per order and the carrying cost is 60 per maund, how many maunds should be purchased per order (EOQ)?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "100",
            "150",
            "240",
            "300"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 9,000 \\times 300}{60}} = 300$.</p>",
        "id": 4369
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Tuya Potato Chips Ltd. uses 9,000 maunds of potatoes annually. If the ordering cost is 300 and the carrying cost is 60, how many orders will be placed in a year?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "15",
            "30",
            "50",
            "60"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Orders = $9,000 / 300 = 30$.</p>",
        "id": 4370
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Sources of non-institutional credit include: (i) Line of credit (ii) Trade credit (iii) Advance from customers. Which is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Line of credit is institutional (bank-provided).</p>",
        "id": 4371
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Ahsan is a small businessman who needs capital for his day-to-day business operations. Which source of funding should he choose?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Short-term",
            "Mid-term",
            "Long-term",
            "Any source"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Day-to-day operations are funded by short-term working capital.</p>",
        "id": 4372
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is EXCLUDED from the category of spontaneous financing?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Trade Credit",
            "Debentures",
            "Accruals",
            "Advance from customers"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Debentures are formal long-term debt, not spontaneous.</p>",
        "id": 4373
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Tabassum is a successful businessman whose products are sold on cash and credit. The credit terms are \"2/10, net 30.\" What is the periodic cost of this trade credit?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "3%",
            "3.04%",
            "2.90%",
            "2.04%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$Periodic Cost = \\frac{2}{100 - 2} = 2.04\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4374
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which tool of short-term financing is primarily used in international import-export trade?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Savings Certificate",
            "Commercial Paper",
            "Treasury Bill",
            "Letter of Credit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Letters of Credit (L/C) facilitate international payments.</p>",
        "id": 4375
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which of the following financial arrangements is a \"Commitment Fee\" usually applicable?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Line of Credit",
            "Trade Credit",
            "Transaction Loan",
            "Revolving Credit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Banks charge commitment fees for the unused portion of revolving credit.</p>",
        "id": 4376
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Typical users of mid-term financing include: (i) Service industries (ii) Farm projects (iii) New and small industries. Which is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three categories often utilize 1-5 year financing.</p>",
        "id": 4377
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is an external source of short-term financing?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Retained Earnings",
            "Depreciation Fund",
            "Commercial Bank",
            "Reserve Fund"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Commercial banks are outside entities, unlike internal reserves.</p>",
        "id": 4378
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Who ultimately bears the cost of trade credit?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Seller",
            "Manufacturer",
            "Buyer",
            "Wholesaler"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>The buyer pays more if they do not utilize the cash discount.</p>",
        "id": 4379
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the cost of credit for a loan provided with terms \"3/20, net 60\"?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "3%",
            "20%",
            "27.84%",
            "55.67%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$Cost = \\frac{3}{97} \\times \\frac{360}{40} = 27.84\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4380
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>A firm requires 20,000 units of raw materials annually. If the carrying cost per unit is 2 and the ordering cost is 200, what is the Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "20",
            "100",
            "200",
            "2,000"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 20,000 \\times 200}{2}} = 2,000$.</p>",
        "id": 4381
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is NOT a source of spontaneous financing?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Trade Credit",
            "Bank Loan",
            "Accrued Expenses",
            "Advance from customers"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Bank loans require formal negotiation and are not spontaneous.</p>",
        "id": 4382
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Muwahidul purchased goods worth 40,000 on credit with terms \"2/10, net 40.\" What type of debt is this?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Revolving Credit",
            "Secured Loan",
            "Term Loan",
            "Trade Credit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Credit extended by a supplier is trade credit.</p>",
        "id": 4383
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Muwahidul purchased goods with terms \"2/10, net 40\" and paid within 10 days. Regarding this: (i) It involves low formality (ii) It is spontaneous (iii) The cost is zero.</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Paying within the discount period makes the financing cost-free.</p>",
        "id": 4384
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Sigma Company has an annual demand of 15,000 units. Carrying cost per unit is TK 2 and ordering cost per order is TK 40. What is the Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?</p>",
        "meta": "Combined Board · 2018",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "764 units",
            "775 units",
            "874 units",
            "974 units"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 15,000 \\times 40}{2}} = \\sqrt{6,00,000} \\approx 774.59$, rounded to 775.</p>",
        "id": 4385
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Goods were purchased on credit with terms \"2/10, net 60.\" What is the annual cost of this trade credit?</p>",
        "meta": "Combined Board · 2018",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "14.69%",
            "16.69%",
            "17.38%",
            "19.21%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$Cost = \\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{60-10} \\times 100 \\approx 14.69\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4386
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is considered a secured (collateralized) loan?</p>",
        "meta": "Combined Board · 2018",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Notes Payable",
            "Letter of Credit",
            "Line of Credit",
            "Trust Receipt"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>A Trust Receipt is a document where the bank retains title to the goods used as security.</p>",
        "id": 4387
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Sources of spontaneous financing include: (i) Trade Credit (ii) Advance from customers (iii) Accrued expenses. Which is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three arise naturally from operations without formal negotiations.</p>",
        "id": 4388
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following types of capital generally carries a higher interest rate?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Long-term capital",
            "Short-term capital",
            "Optimum capital",
            "Variable capital"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Long-term capital usually carries higher risk and interest rates compared to short-term.</p>",
        "id": 4389
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If the terms of trade credit are \"2/10, net 30,\" what is the annual cost of the trade credit?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "30.73%",
            "32.73%",
            "34.73%",
            "36.73%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$Cost = \\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{30-10} \\times 100 \\approx 36.73\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4390
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>FL Company Ltd. sells fans with an annual demand of 90,000 units. Ordering cost is TK 500 per order and carrying cost is TK 10 per unit. What is the EOQ?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "2,000 units",
            "3,000 units",
            "4,000 units",
            "5,000 units"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 90,000 \\times 500}{10}} = \\sqrt{90,00,000} = 3,000$ units.</p>",
        "id": 4391
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>FL Company Ltd. sells fans with an annual demand of 90,000 units, ordering cost of TK 500, and carrying cost of TK 10. What is the Total Inventory Cost?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "20,000 TK",
            "30,000 TK",
            "40,000 TK",
            "50,000 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Total Inventory Cost at EOQ = $\\sqrt{2 \\times 90,000 \\times 500 \\times 10} = 30,000$ TK.</p>",
        "id": 4392
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the typical duration for short-term financing?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "1 year or less",
            "1 year or more",
            "2 years",
            "3 years"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Short-term financing is defined as capital required for a period of up to one year.</p>",
        "id": 4393
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a tool of short-term financing?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Preferred Share",
            "Mutual Fund",
            "Commercial Paper",
            "Bond"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Commercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument issued by corporations.</p>",
        "id": 4394
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Capital raised through short-term financing is used for: (i) Paying wages (ii) Buying raw materials (iii) Marketing. Which is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Short-term funds are used to manage all aspects of working capital/operational costs.</p>",
        "id": 4395
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Current Asset Management involves: (i) Accounts Receivable management (ii) Accounts Payable management (iii) Inventory management.</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>While AR and Inventory are current assets, AP is a current liability management task.</p>",
        "id": 4396
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Haq Traders, a renowned manufacturer, leased a machine from Hasib Leasing Company for 5 years. What type of financing is this?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
