        "id": 4436
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>JEX Company sells 3-month commercial paper (Face Value 1,000) for 975. Issuance cost is 50. What is the cost of the commercial paper?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "12.37%",
            "12.90%",
            "13%",
            "32.43%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$Cost = \\frac{1000 - (975-50)}{975-50} \\times \\frac{360}{90} \\approx 32.43\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4437
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Non-institutional sources of credit include: (i) Line of Credit (ii) Trade Credit (iii) Advances from customers.</p>",
        "meta": "DRMC · -",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Line of credit is a formal bank facility (Institutional).</p>",
        "id": 4438
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following are short-term debt instruments? (i) Shares (ii) Commercial Paper (iii) Negotiable Certificates of Deposit.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Shares represent long-term equity, not short-term debt.</p>",
        "id": 4439
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>ABC Co. has a Re-order Level of 50,000 units. Average monthly usage is 9,000 units. Lead time is 2–6 months. What is the Minimum Inventory Level?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "4,000",
            "14,000",
            "32,000",
            "41,000"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$Min Level = Reorder Level - (Avg Usage \\times Avg Lead Time) = 50,000 - (9,000 \\times 4) = 14,000$.</p>",
        "id": 4440
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Genius Ballpen: Payment period 25 days, Collection period 65 days, Inventory period 80 days. What is the Cash Conversion Cycle?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka/Chittagong · -",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "100 days",
            "120 days",
            "130 days",
            "140 days"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$CCC = Inventory Period + Collection Period - Payment Period = 80 + 65 - 25 = 120$ days.</p>",
        "id": 4441
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>For Genius Ballpen (CCC = 120 days), what is the Cash Turnover?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka/Chittagong · -",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "1",
            "2",
            "3",
            "4"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$Cash Turnover = 360 / CCC = 360 / 120 = 3$ times.</p>",
        "id": 4442
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is included in \"Carrying Costs\" when determining EOQ?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Warehousing cost",
            "Transportation cost",
            "Ordering cost",
            "Material cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Carrying costs include storage, insurance, and obsolescence. Transportation is usually an ordering/purchase cost.</p>",
        "id": 4443
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following are current assets? (i) Loans (ii) Inventory (iii) Debtors.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Inventory and Debtors are current assets; Loans (given) are assets, but Loans (taken) are liabilities.</p>",
        "id": 4444
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Afsana Ltd: Production time 5 days, Payables paid in 15 days, Receivables collected in 30 days. What is the Cash Conversion Cycle?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "10 days",
            "20 days",
            "40 days",
            "50 days"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$CCC = Production (5) + Collection (30) - Payment (15) = 20$ days.</p>",
        "id": 4445
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>How can Afsana Ltd. increase its Cash Turnover? (i) Increase production time (ii) Reduce collection time by 5 days (iii) Delay payments by 5 days.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Reducing collection time or delaying payments shortens the CCC, which increases turnover.</p>",
        "id": 4446
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Rahman, a rice trader, borrowed 20,000 at 10% for daily expenses and another 30,000 at the same rate for inventory (working capital). Which policy did he apply?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Hedging (Matching)",
            "Aggressive",
            "Conservative",
            "Going Concern"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Using short-term debt to finance all current assets (both temporary and permanent) is an Aggressive Policy.</p>",
        "id": 4447
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Regarding Mr. Rahman's funding method: (i) Risk may increase (ii) Profit may increase (iii) Cost may increase. Which is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Aggressive policies increase risk due to short-term refinancing needs but can increase profit as short-term rates are usually lower.</p>",
        "id": 4448
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which is the correct formula for Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "$\\sqrt{\\frac{2AO}{C}}$",
            "$\\sqrt{\\frac{AO}{2C}}$",
            "$\\sqrt{\\frac{2AC}{O}}$",
            "$\\sqrt{\\frac{2C}{AO}}$"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times \\text{Annual Demand} \\times \\text{Ordering Cost}}{\\text{Carrying Cost}}}$.</p>",
        "id": 4449
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Current assets of a business include: (i) Cash (ii) Bank Balance (iii) Bills Receivable. Which is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three are highly liquid assets expected to be converted to cash within a year.</p>",
        "id": 4450
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>[Based on Cycle Diagram: Raw Materials $\\rightarrow$ WIP $\\rightarrow$ Finished Goods $\\rightarrow$ Receivables $\\rightarrow$ Cash] What does this cycle represent?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Cash Conversion",
            "Cash Turnover",
            "Operating Cycle",
            "Production Cycle"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>The Operating Cycle covers the time from purchasing raw materials to the final collection of cash.</p>",
        "id": 4451
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is a component of inventory management?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Raw materials",
            "Machinery",
            "Furniture",
            "Buildings"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Inventory management specifically deals with raw materials, work-in-progress, and finished goods.</p>",
        "id": 4452
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What type of financing source is \"Accrued Expenses\"?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "External",
            "Mid-term",
            "Internal",
            "Long-term"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Accrued expenses (like unpaid wages) are an internal, spontaneous source of short-term financing.</p>",
        "id": 4453
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Objectives of inventory management include: (i) Buying materials at lower cost (ii) Reducing lead time (iii) Preventing inventory shortages.</p>",
        "meta": "Bogra · -",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Effective inventory management balances cost reduction with the continuous availability of stock.</p>",
        "id": 4454
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Flora Ltd. pays suppliers in 30 days, collects from customers in 45 days, and takes 25 days to sell inventory. What is the Cash Conversion Cycle (CCC)?</p>",
        "meta": "Bogra · -",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "40 days",
            "10 days",
            "50 days",
            "45 days"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$CCC = 25 (\\text{Inv}) + 45 (\\text{Rec}) - 30 (\\text{Pay}) = 40$ days.</p>",
        "id": 4455
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>For Flora Ltd. (CCC = 40 days), what is the Cash Turnover (assuming a 360-day year)?</p>",
        "meta": "Bogra · -",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "9 times",
            "7.2 times",
            "36 times",
            "8 times"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$Cash Turnover = 360 / 40 = 9$ times.</p>",
        "id": 4456
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the primary purpose of short-term financing?</p>",
        "meta": "Milestone · -",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Business expansion",
            "Machine installation",
            "Meeting current expenses",
            "Business relocation"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Short-term financing is designed to manage liquidity and cover daily operational costs.</p>",
        "id": 4457
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which case is short-term financing used?</p>",
        "meta": "Bogra · -",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "Buying Furniture",
            "Buying Raw Materials",
            "Buying Buildings",
            "Buying Machinery"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Short-term funds are used for circulating assets like raw materials, not fixed assets.</p>",
        "id": 4458
    }],
            shortCQData: [
// === FIN1_CH5_SHORTCQ_START ===
{
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-001",
        "text": "What is Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?",
        "answer": "EOQ is the ideal order quantity a company should purchase to minimize inventory costs such as holding costs, shortage costs, and order costs.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-001",
        "text": "What is current asset management? Explain.",
        "answer": "Current asset management involves managing a firm's short-term assets (cash, inventory, accounts receivable) to ensure the company has enough liquidity to meet its obligations and operate efficiently.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-002",
        "text": "What is trade credit?",
        "answer": "Trade credit is an agreement where a customer can purchase goods on account and pay the supplier at a later date.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-002",
        "text": "Why is commercial paper used?",
        "answer": "Commercial paper is used by large, highly-rated corporations to raise short-term funds for working capital needs at a lower interest rate than bank loans.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-003",
        "text": "What is mid-term financing?",
        "answer": "Mid-term financing refers to loans or funding obtained for a period typically ranging from one to five years.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-003",
        "text": "Why is inventory management important?",
        "answer": "It is important because it prevents both overstocking (which ties up capital) and understocking (which leads to lost sales and production delays).",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-004",
        "text": "What is commercial paper?",
        "answer": "Commercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument issued by a corporation, typically for the financing of accounts receivable and inventories and meeting short-term liabilities.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-004",
        "text": "What is meant by a line of credit?",
        "answer": "A line of credit is a flexible loan from a bank or financial institution that allows a borrower to access funds up to a pre-approved limit at any time, paying interest only on the amount actually borrowed.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-005",
        "text": "What is working capital?",
        "answer": "Working capital is the difference between a company's current assets (like cash, accounts receivable, and inventories) and its current liabilities (like accounts payable).",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-005",
        "text": "What is the effect on cash turnover if the cash conversion cycle changes?",
        "answer": "1. Cash turnover and the cash conversion cycle have an inverse relationship.\n\n2. If the cash conversion cycle decreases, cash turnover increases, meaning the company uses its cash more efficiently.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-006",
        "text": "What is mid-term financing?",
        "answer": "Mid-term financing refers to borrowing money for a period that typically ranges from one to five years.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-006",
        "text": "What is meant by re-order level?",
        "answer": "The re-order level is the specific level of inventory at which a new order must be placed to replenish stock before it runs out during the lead time.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-007",
        "text": "What is capital rationing?",
        "answer": "Capital rationing is the process of placing a limit on the amount of new projects or investments a company can undertake by setting a budget for capital expenditures.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-007",
        "text": "What is meant by mutually exclusive projects?",
        "answer": "1. These are projects where the acceptance of one automatically results in the rejection of others.\n\n2. They compete for the same resource or solve the same problem, so only the best one is chosen.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-008",
        "text": "What is safety stock?",
        "answer": "Safety stock is an extra quantity of an item carried in inventory to prevent stockouts due to uncertainties in demand or supply.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-008",
        "text": "\"There is a positive relationship between lead time and inventory cost.\"—Explain.",
        "answer": "1. Longer lead time requires a higher re-order point and more safety stock to avoid stockouts.\n\n2. Higher safety stock increases the average inventory held, leading to higher carrying costs.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-009",
        "text": "What is short-term financing?",
        "answer": "Short-term financing refers to the collection of funds for a period of less than one year to meet daily operating expenses.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-009",
        "text": "What are the advantages of short-term financing?",
        "answer": "1. It is typically less expensive than long-term financing and offers greater flexibility.\n\n2. It can be arranged quickly to meet seasonal demands or sudden cash needs.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-010",
        "text": "What is a revolving credit?",
        "answer": "Revolving credit is a formal, legal commitment by a bank to lend up to a maximum amount to a firm for a specific period, where the firm pays a commitment fee on the unused portion.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-010",
        "text": "How is the cost of trade credit determined?",
        "answer": "1. The cost of trade credit is determined by calculating the annual interest rate \"lost\" by not taking the cash discount.\n\n2. It depends on the discount percentage, the discount period, and the final credit period.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-011",
        "text": "What is trade credit?",
        "answer": "Trade credit is a short-term financing source where a buyer purchases goods or services on account and pays the supplier at a later, agreed-upon date.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-011",
        "text": "What is meant by current asset management?",
        "answer": "1. Current asset management refers to managing short-term assets like cash, inventory, and receivables to ensure liquidity.\n\n2. Its goal is to balance the trade-off between maintaining enough liquidity and maximizing profitability.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-012",
        "text": "What is Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?",
        "answer": "EOQ is the specific order size that minimizes the total annual cost of ordering and carrying inventory.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-012",
        "text": "Is commercial paper sold at a premium? Explain.",
        "answer": "1. No, commercial paper is not sold at a premium; it is typically sold at a discount from its face value.\n\n2. The difference between the discount price and the face value represents the interest earned by the investor.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-013",
        "text": "What is mid-term financing?",
        "answer": "Mid-term financing refers to the sourcing of funds for a period usually ranging from more than one year to five years.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-013",
        "text": "Who bears the cost of trade credit? Explain.",
        "answer": "1. Nominally, the buyer bears the cost of trade credit if they fail to take the cash discount offered by the seller.\n\n2. However, sellers often hide this cost by increasing the base price of the goods, meaning the buyer may bear it indirectly even if they take the discount.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-014",
        "text": "What is inventory management?",
        "answer": "Inventory management is the process of ordering, storing, using, and selling a company's inventory, including raw materials, components, and finished products.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-014",
        "text": "\"Inventory cost affects the selling price of a product\"—Explain.",
        "answer": "1. Inventory costs (carrying and ordering costs) are part of the total operating expense of a business.\n\n2. To maintain profit margins, businesses pass these costs to customers by increasing the final selling price of the product.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-015",
        "text": "What is commercial paper?",
        "answer": "Commercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument issued by a corporation, typically to finance accounts receivable and inventories.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-015",
        "text": "Who bears the cost of trade credit? Explain.",
        "answer": "1. The buyer bears the \"opportunity cost\" if they do not pay within the discount period.\n\n2. This cost is effectively the interest rate the buyer pays for using the supplier's money for the remaining credit period.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-016",
        "text": "What is spontaneous financing?",
        "answer": "Spontaneous financing refers to the sources of funds that arise naturally from day-to-day business operations, such as accounts payable and accrued expenses.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-016",
        "text": "Differentiate between a line of credit and revolving credit.",
        "answer": "1. A line of credit is an informal agreement where a bank limits the max loan, but isn't legally bound to lend.\n\n2. Revolving credit is a formal, legal commitment where the bank must lend, and the firm pays a commitment fee on unused funds.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-017",
        "text": "What is trade credit?",
        "answer": "Trade credit is a short-term financing arrangement where a buyer is allowed to purchase goods and pay the supplier at a later date.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-017",
        "text": "Why is maintaining working capital at an optimal level a key responsibility of a financial manager?",
        "answer": "1. Excessive working capital ties up funds unproductively, while insufficient working capital leads to liquidity crises.\n\n2. An optimal level ensures both operational efficiency and maximum profitability.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-018",
        "text": "What is Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?",
        "answer": "EOQ is the ideal order quantity that minimizes the total annual costs of ordering and carrying inventory.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-018",
        "text": "What will be the total inventory cost for BGF Ltd.?",
        "answer": "1. Data: $A = 64,000; O = 500; C = 1000 \\times 1\\% = 10$.\n\n2. EOQ: $\\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 64,000 \\times 500}{10}} = 2,530$ units.\n\n3. Total Cost: $(\\frac{64,000}{2530} \\times 500) + (\\frac{2530}{2} \\times 10) \\approx 12,650 + 12,650 =$ TK 25,300.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-019",
        "text": "What is trade credit?",
        "answer": "Trade credit is a short-term financing arrangement where a buyer is allowed to purchase goods and pay the supplier at a later date.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-019",
        "text": "Why is trade credit called spontaneous financing?",
        "answer": "1. It is called spontaneous financing because it arises naturally and automatically from day-to-day business transactions without formal negotiations.\n\n2. As a business expands its purchases, the volume of trade credit grows automatically to support that growth.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-020",
        "text": "What is short-term financing?",
        "answer": "Short-term financing refers to the collection of funds for a period of less than one year to meet daily operating expenses.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-020",
        "text": "What do you mean by the cash cycle?",
        "answer": "1. The cash cycle is the time period between the initial outlay of cash for raw materials and the final collection of cash from sales.\n\n2. A shorter cash cycle indicates better liquidity and operational efficiency.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-021",
        "text": "What is trade credit?",
        "answer": "Trade credit is a spontaneous source of financing where a buyer receives goods now and pays the supplier later.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-021",
        "text": "Why is inventory maintained?",
        "answer": "1. Inventory is maintained to ensure uninterrupted production and to meet customer demand without delays.\n\n2. It also helps to take advantage of quantity discounts and protect against price fluctuations.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-022",
        "text": "What is Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?",
        "answer": "EOQ is the ideal order quantity a company should purchase to minimize its total inventory costs, such as ordering and carrying costs.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-022",
        "text": "Who bears the cost of trade credit?",
        "answer": "1. Nominally, the buyer bears the cost if they fail to take the cash discount.\n\n2. Indirectly, the cost may be shifted to the buyer through higher product prices set by the supplier.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-023",
        "text": "What is short-term financing?",
        "answer": "Short-term financing refers to the collection of funds for a period of less than one year to meet daily operating expenses.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-023",
        "text": "What do you mean by trade credit?",
        "answer": "1. Trade credit is a spontaneous source of financing where a buyer receives goods now and pays the supplier at a later date.\n\n2. It is an agreement between two businesses that allows for the purchase of goods without immediate cash payment.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-024",
        "text": "What is lead time?",
        "answer": "Lead time is the total time that elapses between the placement of an order and the receipt of the goods in the warehouse.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-024",
        "text": "What do you mean by accounts receivable management? Explain.",
        "answer": "1. It is the process of ensuring that customers pay their dues on time to maintain cash flow.\n\n2. It involves setting credit policies, evaluating creditworthiness, and implementing collection procedures.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-025",
        "text": "What is revolving credit?",
        "answer": "Revolving credit is a formal and legal commitment by a bank to lend up to a maximum amount to a firm for a specific period.",
        "meta": "RAJUK Uttara Model College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-025",
        "text": "Why is inventory management important?",
        "answer": "1. It ensures an uninterrupted production process and sales flow by preventing stockouts.\n\n2. It minimizes total costs by balancing ordering and carrying costs, ensuring funds are not unnecessarily tied up.",
        "meta": "RAJUK Uttara Model College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-026",
        "text": "What is spontaneous financing?",
        "answer": "Spontaneous financing refers to sources of funds that arise naturally from day-to-day business operations, such as accounts payable.",
        "meta": "Notre Dame College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-026",
        "text": "Who bears the cost of trade credit?",
        "answer": "1. Nominally, the buyer bears the \"opportunity cost\" if they fail to take the cash discount.\n\n2. Sellers may also shift the cost to buyers by increasing the base price of goods.",
        "meta": "Notre Dame College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-027",
        "text": "What is spontaneous financing?",
        "answer": "Spontaneous financing refers to funds that arise naturally from operations, like trade credit and accruals.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Commerce College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-027",
        "text": "How does a change in the cash conversion cycle affect cash turnover?",
        "answer": "1. There is an inverse relationship; if the cash conversion cycle decreases, cash turnover increases.\n\n2. A shorter cycle means the company completes the cash-to-cash process more times per year, requiring less idle cash.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Commerce College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-028",
        "text": "What is Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?",
        "answer": "EOQ is the order size that minimizes the total annual cost of ordering and carrying inventory.",
        "meta": "Adamjee Cantonment College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-028",
        "text": "What is the optimal cash balance? Explain with the formula.",
        "answer": "1. It is the cash level that minimizes the sum of opportunity costs (lost interest) and transaction costs.\n\n2. Formula (Baumol Model): $Q = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times T \\times F}{i}}$, where $T$ = Annual cash need, $F$ = Fixed cost, $i$ = Interest rate.",
        "meta": "Adamjee Cantonment College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-029",
        "text": "What is the cost of trade credit?",
        "answer": "It is the annual interest cost a firm effectively pays by not taking a cash discount from a supplier.",
        "meta": "Holy Cross College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-029",
        "text": "What is meant by revolving credit?",
        "answer": "Revolving credit is a formal, legal agreement where a bank is committed to lending a firm up to a specific limit, and the firm pays a commitment fee on unused funds.",
        "meta": "Holy Cross College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-030",
        "text": "What is commercial paper?",
        "answer": "Commercial paper is an unsecured, short-term promissory note issued by large corporations to raise funds.",
        "meta": "Govt. Azizul Haque College, Bogra · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-030",
        "text": "Why is current asset management important? Explain.",
        "answer": "1. It ensures the company has enough liquidity to meet day-to-day operational expenses.\n\n2. It helps maintain the right balance between risk and profitability by avoiding excessive or insufficient investment in current assets.",
        "meta": "Govt. Azizul Haque College, Bogra · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-031",
        "text": "What is short-term financing?",
        "answer": "Short-term financing refers to the collection of funds for a period of less than one year to meet daily operating expenses.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Govt. College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-b-031",
        "text": "What do you mean by trade credit?",
        "answer": "Trade credit is a spontaneous source of financing where a buyer receives goods now and pays the supplier later.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Govt. College · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-short-a-032",
        "text": "What is trade credit?",
