            ],
            fullCQData: [
// === FIN1_CH5_FULLCQ_START ===
{
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-001",
        "stem": "P Ltd. has an annual cash requirement of TK 4,80,000. The company maintains marketable securities. The required rate of return is 12%, and the transaction cost to convert these securities into cash is TK 150 per transaction. On the other hand, Q Ltd.'s average production period is 50 days, average collection period is 40 days, and average payment period is 30 days. Its annual cash requirement is TK 3,00,000.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?",
                "answer": "EOQ is the ideal order quantity a company should purchase to minimize inventory costs such as holding costs, shortage costs, and order costs."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is current asset management? Explain.",
                "answer": "Current asset management involves managing a firm's short-term assets (cash, inventory, accounts receivable) to ensure the company has enough liquidity to meet its obligations and operate efficiently."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the optimal cash balance for P Ltd.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $T = 4,80,000$; $b = 150$; $i = 12\\%$ or 0.12.\n\n2. Formula (Baumol Model): $C = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times T \\times b}{i}}$.\n\n3. Calculation: $C = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 4,80,000 \\times 150}{0.12}} = \\sqrt{1,20,00,00,000} = 34,641$."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Calculate the minimum operating cash for Q Ltd. If the minimum cash is fixed at TK 60,000, what will be the effect on cash turnover? Analyze.",
                "answer": "1. Operating Cycle: $50 + 40 = 90$ days. Cash Cycle: $90 - 30 = 60$ days.\n\n2. Cash Turnover: $360 / 60 = 6$ times.\n\n3. Minimum Cash: $3,00,000 / 6 = 50,000$.\n\n4. Effect: If minimum cash is TK 60,000, cash turnover decreases ($3,00,000 / 60,000 = 5$ times), indicating less efficiency in using cash."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-002",
        "stem": "Mr. Tajin purchased goods on credit from X Ltd. The maximum payment period is 60 days. According to the credit terms, a 3% discount is available if paid within 14 days. Mr. Tajin decided to take a bank loan at 17% interest to grab the discount. Later, the credit period was extended by 10 days.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is trade credit?",
                "answer": "Trade credit is an agreement where a customer can purchase goods on account and pay the supplier at a later date."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is commercial paper used?",
                "answer": "Commercial paper is used by large, highly-rated corporations to raise short-term funds for working capital needs at a lower interest rate than bank loans."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What is the cost of trade credit for Mr. Tajin?",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 3\\%$; $CP = 60$ days; $DP = 14$ days.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $Ktc = \\frac{3}{97} \\times \\frac{360}{46} \\times 100 = 0.0309 \\times 7.826 \\times 100 = 24.18\\%$."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "In light of the stem, if the payment period is increased by 10 days, analyze the logicality of taking a bank loan.",
                "answer": "1. New CP: $60 + 10 = 70$ days.\n\n2. New Cost: $Ktc = \\frac{3}{97} \\times \\frac{360}{70 - 14} \\times 100 = 19.88\\%$.\n\n3. Comparison: Bank loan rate (17%) is lower than the cost of trade credit (19.88%).\n\n4. Conclusion: It is still logical to take the bank loan because the cost of giving up the discount (19.88%) is higher than the interest paid to the bank."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-003",
        "stem": "AB Company's annual demand is 2,00,000 packets. Ordering cost per order is TK 60. Carrying cost per unit is TK 2. Lead time is 4 days. The company decides to maintain 700 packets as safety stock. Due to special reasons, lead time increases to 6 days.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is mid-term financing?",
                "answer": "Mid-term financing refers to loans or funding obtained for a period typically ranging from one to five years."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is inventory management important?",
                "answer": "It is important because it prevents both overstocking (which ties up capital) and understocking (which leads to lost sales and production delays)."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the EOQ for AB Company.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $A = 2,00,000$; $O = 60$; $C = 2$.\n\n2. Formula: $EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times A \\times O}{C}}$.\n\n3. Calculation: $EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 2,00,000 \\times 60}{2}} = \\sqrt{1,20,00,000} = 3,464$."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Evaluate the logic of placing a re-order when 2,500 packets are remaining based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Daily Demand: $2,00,000 / 360 \\approx 556$ packets.\n\n2. Re-order Level: (Daily demand $\\times$ Lead time) + Safety Stock.\n\n3. Calculation (Old): $(556 \\times 4) + 700 = 2,924$. Calculation (New): $(556 \\times 6) + 700 = 4,036$.\n\n4. Conclusion: Re-ordering at 2,500 packets is illogical and risky because the re-order level should be at least 2,924 (normal) or 4,036 (extended lead time) to avoid stockouts."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-004",
        "stem": "Padma Company Ltd. is a consumer goods manufacturer. Recently, the company purchased raw materials on credit under the terms 2/10, net 30. The company's average inventory period is 10 days, and the average payment period is 15 days. It takes 20 days to collect receivables after a sale. Its competitor, Meghna Company, has a cash conversion cycle of 18 days.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is commercial paper?",
                "answer": "Commercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument issued by a corporation, typically for the financing of accounts receivable and inventories and meeting short-term liabilities."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is meant by a line of credit?",
                "answer": "A line of credit is a flexible loan from a bank or financial institution that allows a borrower to access funds up to a pre-approved limit at any time, paying interest only on the amount actually borrowed."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of trade credit for Padma Company.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 2\\%$; $CP = 30$ days; $DP = 10$ days.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $Ktc = \\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{20} \\times 100 = 0.0204 \\times 18 \\times 100 = 36.73\\%$."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "In which company's case will cash remain invested for a relatively shorter period? Give your opinion with logic.",
                "answer": "1. Padma Co. CCC: Inventory Period + Collection Period - Payment Period.\n\n2. Calculation: $10 + 20 - 15 = 15$ days.\n\n3. Meghna Co. CCC: 18 days.\n\n4. Conclusion: Cash will remain invested for a shorter period in Padma Company (15 days) compared to Meghna Company (18 days). Thus, Padma Company is more efficient in managing its cash cycle."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-005",
        "stem": "Shapla Manufacturing Ltd. has an annual raw material demand of 1,00,000 units. Ordering cost per order is TK 40. The purchase cost per unit is TK 20, and the carrying cost is 20% of the purchase price. Lead time is 4 days. The company maintains a safety stock equal to 2 days of usage. The inventory manager places a re-order when the stock level reaches 2,500 units. The company operates 250 days a year.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is working capital?",
                "answer": "Working capital is the difference between a company's current assets (like cash, accounts receivable, and inventories) and its current liabilities (like accounts payable)."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is the effect on cash turnover if the cash conversion cycle changes?",
                "answer": "1. Cash turnover and the cash conversion cycle have an inverse relationship.\n\n2. If the cash conversion cycle decreases, cash turnover increases, meaning the company uses its cash more efficiently."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the total inventory cost for Shapla Manufacturing Ltd.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $A = 1,00,000$; $O = 40$; $C = 20 \\times 20\\% = 4$.\n\n2. EOQ: $\\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 1,00,000 \\times 40}{4}} = \\sqrt{20,00,000} = 1,414$ units.\n\n3. Total Cost: $(\\frac{A}{EOQ} \\times O) + (\\frac{EOQ}{2} \\times C)$.\n\n4. Calculation: $(\\frac{1,00,000}{1,414} \\times 40) + (\\frac{1,414}{2} \\times 4) = 2,828 + 2,828 = 5,656$ TK."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Do you think the action taken by the inventory manager is logical? Give your opinion based on mathematical analysis.",
                "answer": "1. Daily Usage: $1,00,000 / 250 = 400$ units.\n\n2. Safety Stock: $400 \\times 2 = 800$ units.\n\n3. Re-order Point (ROP): (Daily usage $\\times$ Lead time) + Safety stock.\n\n4. Calculation: $(400 \\times 4) + 800 = 2,400$ units.\n\n5. Conclusion: The manager's decision to re-order at 2,500 units is logical as it is slightly above the calculated ROP (2,400), providing an extra buffer against stockouts."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-006",
        "stem": "Sunmoon Computers can either accept trade credit under the terms 3/10, net 30 or take a short-term bank loan at a 2% monthly compound interest rate to finance its working capital.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is mid-term financing?",
                "answer": "Mid-term financing refers to borrowing money for a period that typically ranges from one to five years."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is meant by re-order level?",
                "answer": "The re-order level is the specific level of inventory at which a new order must be placed to replenish stock before it runs out during the lead time."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of trade credit for Sunmoon Computers based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 3\\%$; $CP = 30$ days; $DP = 10$ days.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $Ktc = \\frac{3}{97} \\times \\frac{360}{20} \\times 100 = 0.0309 \\times 18 \\times 100 = 55.67\\%$."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Which loan option would be profitable for Sunmoon Computers? Analyze.",
                "answer": "1. Option 1 (Trade Credit Cost): 55.67%.\n\n2. Option 2 (Bank Loan EIR): Monthly rate = 2%.\n\n3. Formula: $EIR = (1 + i)^m - 1 = (1 + 0.02)^{12} - 1 = 1.2682 - 1 = 26.82\\%$.\n\n4. Conclusion: The bank loan is more profitable because its effective annual rate (26.82%) is much lower than the cost of giving up the trade credit discount (55.67%)."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-007",
        "stem": "Hossain and Hasan are poultry farmers with equal capital. Hossain farms broilers and often faces cash crises 15–20 days before sale. Hasan farms broilers, layers, and produces feed, but never faces a crisis.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is capital rationing?",
                "answer": "Capital rationing is the process of placing a limit on the amount of new projects or investments a company can undertake by setting a budget for capital expenditures."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is meant by mutually exclusive projects?",
                "answer": "1. These are projects where the acceptance of one automatically results in the rejection of others.\n\n2. They compete for the same resource or solve the same problem, so only the best one is chosen."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What is the cause of the financial crisis in Hossain’s farm?",
                "answer": "1. Hossain suffers from a long Cash Conversion Cycle and high inventory period.\n\n2. Broilers require continuous investment (feed/medicine) without generating cash until they reach market weight.\n\n3. This creates a \"liquidity gap\" where cash outflows continue while inflows are delayed until the end of the term."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "\"Despite doing so much, Hasan never faced a financial crisis\"—Why?",
                "answer": "1. Hasan uses Product Diversification to ensure multiple, overlapping cash streams.\n\n2. Selling layers (eggs) and feed provides daily cash inflow, providing liquidity to the business.\n\n3. This steady daily income offsets the high maintenance costs of the broiler section.\n\n4. Consequently, his cash conversion cycle is effectively shorter, preventing any \"empty pocket\" periods."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-008",
        "stem": "Shyamoli Co. sells 500 mobile sets monthly. Maintenance cost per mobile is TK 1, purchase price is TK 1,500, and ordering cost is TK 30.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is safety stock?",
                "answer": "Safety stock is an extra quantity of an item carried in inventory to prevent stockouts due to uncertainties in demand or supply."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "\"There is a positive relationship between lead time and inventory cost.\"—Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Longer lead time requires a higher re-order point and more safety stock to avoid stockouts.\n\n2. Higher safety stock increases the average inventory held, leading to higher carrying costs."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the Economic Order Quantity (EOQ) for Shyamoli Company.",
                "answer": "1. Data: Annual demand ($A$) = $500 \\times 12 = 6,000$; $O = 30$; $C = 1$.\n\n2. Formula: $EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times A \\times O}{C}}$.\n\n3. Calculation: $EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 6000 \\times 30}{1}} = 600$ units."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "If the manager buys 500 sets per order, evaluate the decision based on total cost.",
                "answer": "1. At EOQ (600): Total Cost = $(\\frac{6000}{600} \\times 30) + (\\frac{600}{2} \\times 1) = 600$ TK.\n\n2. At 500 units: Total Cost = $(\\frac{6000}{500} \\times 30) + (\\frac{500}{2} \\times 1) = 610$ TK.\n\n3. The decision to buy 500 units increases the total annual inventory cost by TK 10.\n\n4. Therefore, the manager's decision is not optimal compared to the EOQ of 600 units."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-009",
        "stem": "Mr. Kamal is concerned about liquidity and thinks of collecting working capital from long-term sources. He also wants adequate inventory for peak seasons, noting 50% of sales are on credit with 3-month collection.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is short-term financing?",
                "answer": "Short-term financing refers to the collection of funds for a period of less than one year to meet daily operating expenses."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What are the advantages of short-term financing?",
                "answer": "1. It is typically less expensive than long-term financing and offers greater flexibility.\n\n2. It can be arranged quickly to meet seasonal demands or sudden cash needs."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Mention the different sources of collecting current assets as per the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Long-term sources (as explicitly mentioned in the stem).\n\n2. Trade credit (indicated by the 50% credit sales and 3-month collection).\n\n3. Accruals or spontaneous sources inherent in regular business operations."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "How logical is the policy adopted by Mr. Kamal for collecting current assets?",
                "answer": "1. Kamal is following the Conservative Policy by using long-term funds for current assets.\n\n2. This is highly logical for risk-aversion as it ensures the company never runs out of cash.\n\n3. However, it is less logical for profitability because long-term interest rates are generally higher.\n\n4. Overall, it is a \"low-risk, low-profit\" strategy suited for companies worried about liquidity."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-010",
        "stem": "Mr. Hamid works at a private firm that buys raw materials on credit. A supplier offered terms of 2/10, net 45. Hamid requested the owner to take the 2% discount. The owner argued, \"I have no cash. To take a 2% discount, I'd need a bank loan at 14% interest, which won't be profitable.\" Hamid failed to convince him that giving up the discount costs more.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is a revolving credit?",
                "answer": "Revolving credit is a formal, legal commitment by a bank to lend up to a maximum amount to a firm for a specific period, where the firm pays a commitment fee on the unused portion."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "How is the cost of trade credit determined?",
                "answer": "1. The cost of trade credit is determined by calculating the annual interest rate \"lost\" by not taking the cash discount.\n\n2. It depends on the discount percentage, the discount period, and the final credit period."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What is the annual cost of trade credit according to the terms in the stem?",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 2\\%$; $CP = 45$ days; $DP = 10$ days.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $Ktc = \\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{35} \\times 100 = 20.99\\%$."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Between Hamid and his owner, whose decision was correct? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Hamid's decision was correct.\n\n2. The annual cost of giving up the discount ($Ktc$) is 20.99%.\n\n3. The cost of the bank loan is only 14%.\n\n4. Since the bank loan is cheaper than the trade credit cost ($14\\% < 20.99\\%$), the company saves 6.99% by borrowing from the bank to pay the supplier early."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-011",
        "stem": "Mr. Kalam is a retailer needing TK 1,00,000 in working capital. He can take trade credit at 2/10, net 40. Alternatively, Meghna Ltd. offers a loan at 12% interest, but he must maintain a 20% compensating balance (CB) in the bank.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is trade credit?",
                "answer": "Trade credit is a short-term financing source where a buyer purchases goods or services on account and pays the supplier at a later, agreed-upon date."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is meant by current asset management?",
                "answer": "1. Current asset management refers to managing short-term assets like cash, inventory, and receivables to ensure liquidity.\n\n2. Its goal is to balance the trade-off between maintaining enough liquidity and maximizing profitability."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What is Mr. Kalam’s cost of trade credit?",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 2\\%$; $CP = 40$ days; $DP = 10$ days.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $Ktc = \\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{30} \\times 100 = 24.49\\%$."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Which loan is more suitable for Mr. Kalam? Analyze.",
                "answer": "1. Trade Credit Cost: 24.49% (from C).\n\n2. Bank Loan Cost: $i = 12\\%; CB = 20\\%$.\n\n3. Formula (EAR): $\\frac{i}{1 - CB} \\times 100 = \\frac{0.12}{1 - 0.20} \\times 100 = 15\\%$.\n\n4. Conclusion: The bank loan (15%) is more suitable as its effective cost is significantly lower than the cost of trade credit (24.49%)."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-012",
        "stem": "Mr. Azad is a small businessman needing TK 1,50,000 for working capital. Option 1: Credit purchase at 2/10, net 70. Option 2: Bank loan at 12% interest with a 20% compensating balance requirement.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?",
                "answer": "EOQ is the specific order size that minimizes the total annual cost of ordering and carrying inventory."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Is commercial paper sold at a premium? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. No, commercial paper is not sold at a premium; it is typically sold at a discount from its face value.\n\n2. The difference between the discount price and the face value represents the interest earned by the investor."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What is Mr. Azad’s cost of trade credit?",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 2\\%$; $CP = 70$ days; $DP = 10$ days.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $Ktc = \\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{60} \\times 100 = 12.24\\%$."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "From which source should Mr. Azad finance? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Trade Credit Cost: 12.24% (from C).\n\n2. Bank Loan Cost: $i = 12\\%; CB = 20\\%$.\n\n3. Formula (EAR): $\\frac{0.12}{1 - 0.20} \\times 100 = 15\\%$.\n\n4. Mr. Azad should choose trade credit.\n\n5. Logic: In this specific case, the cost of trade credit (12.24%) is lower than the effective cost of the bank loan (15%) due to the long credit period (70 days)."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-013",
        "stem": "Bashundhara Ltd. needs TK 80,000 for working capital. It has two options: Option 1: Buy TK 1,00,000 of raw materials under terms 3/15, net 45. Option 2: Buy TK 80,000 of raw materials under terms 2/10, net 60.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2018",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is mid-term financing?",
                "answer": "Mid-term financing refers to the sourcing of funds for a period usually ranging from more than one year to five years."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Who bears the cost of trade credit? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Nominally, the buyer bears the cost of trade credit if they fail to take the cash discount offered by the seller.\n\n2. However, sellers often hide this cost by increasing the base price of the goods, meaning the buyer may bear it indirectly even if they take the discount."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of trade credit for the 1st option based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 3\\%$; $CP = 45$ days; $DP = 15$ days.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $Ktc = \\frac{3}{97} \\times \\frac{360}{30} \\times 100 = 37.11\\%$."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Which option should Bashundhara Ltd. select and why? Evaluate.",
                "answer": "1. Option 1 Cost: 37.11% (calculated in C).\n\n2. Option 2 Cost: $CD = 2\\%; CP = 60; DP = 10$. $Ktc = \\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{50} \\times 100 = 14.69\\%$.\n\n3. Bashundhara Ltd. should choose Option 2.\n\n4. Logic: Option 2 is better because the cost of giving up the discount (14.69%) is significantly lower than the cost in Option 1 (37.11%)."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-014",
        "stem": "Mr. Mamun buys 1,00,000 kg of mangoes annually. Ordering costs (transport/comm) are TK 1,750 and TK 250 per order. Storage cost is TK 1/kg. Lead time is 3 days. He keeps 400 kg as safety stock. Annual working days = 250.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2018",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is inventory management?",
                "answer": "Inventory management is the process of ordering, storing, using, and selling a company's inventory, including raw materials, components, and finished products."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "\"Inventory cost affects the selling price of a product\"—Explain.",
                "answer": "1. Inventory costs (carrying and ordering costs) are part of the total operating expense of a business.\n\n2. To maintain profit margins, businesses pass these costs to customers by increasing the final selling price of the product."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the Economic Order Quantity (EOQ) for Mr. Mamun.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $A = 1,00,000$; $O = 1,750 + 250 = 2,000$; $C = 1$.\n\n2. Formula: $EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times A \\times O}{C}}$.\n\n3. Calculation: $EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 1,00,000 \\times 2,000}{1}} = 20,000$ kg."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "How will a one-day increase in lead time affect the re-order level? Analyze.",
                "answer": "1. Daily Demand: $1,00,000 / 250 = 400$ kg.\n\n2. Original ROP (3 days): $(400 \\times 3) + 400 = 1,600$ kg.\n\n3. New ROP (4 days): $(400 \\times 4) + 400 = 2,000$ kg.\n\n4. Conclusion: A one-day increase in lead time increases the re-order level by 400 kg, meaning the manager must place new orders earlier to avoid stockouts."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-015",
        "stem": "Future Ltd. purchased goods from Daily Ltd. under terms 2/15, net 45. You decided to take a bank loan at 13% to take the discount. Later, Daily Ltd. extended the payment period by 10 days.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2018",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is commercial paper?",
                "answer": "Commercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument issued by a corporation, typically to finance accounts receivable and inventories."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Who bears the cost of trade credit? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. The buyer bears the \"opportunity cost\" if they do not pay within the discount period.\n\n2. This cost is effectively the interest rate the buyer pays for using the supplier's money for the remaining credit period."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "If Future Ltd. took the discount initially, what would be the cost of trade credit?",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 2\\%$; $CP = 45$ days; $DP = 15$ days.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $Ktc = \\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{30} \\times 100 = 24.49\\%$."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "How will the change in payment time affect your loan decision? Opinion with logic.",
                "answer": "1. Original Cost: 24.49%. Bank Loan: 13%. (Taking loan is logical).\n\n2. New CP: $45 + 10 = 55$ days.\n\n3. New Ktc: $\\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{55 - 15} \\times 100 = 18.37\\%$.\n\n4. Conclusion: Even though the cost of trade credit dropped to 18.37%, it is still higher than the bank loan rate (13%). Therefore, the decision to take the bank loan remains logical."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-016",
        "stem": "BD Foods markets processed food. Annual demand is 1,20,000 packets at TK 22 each. Ordering cost is TK 80 per order and carrying cost is TK 2 per unit. Lead time is 4 days. The company maintains a safety stock of 1,200 packets. Total working days are 300. The manager re-orders at 2,000 units.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is spontaneous financing?",
                "answer": "Spontaneous financing refers to the sources of funds that arise naturally from day-to-day business operations, such as accounts payable and accrued expenses."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Differentiate between a line of credit and revolving credit.",
                "answer": "1. A line of credit is an informal agreement where a bank limits the max loan, but isn't legally bound to lend.\n\n2. Revolving credit is a formal, legal commitment where the bank must lend, and the firm pays a commitment fee on unused funds."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the annual inventory cost for BD Foods Ltd.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $A = 1,20,000; O = 80; C = 2$.\n\n2. EOQ: $\\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 1,20,000 \\times 80}{2}} = 3,098$ units.\n\n3. Total Cost: $(\\frac{A}{EOQ} \\times O) + (\\frac{EOQ}{2} \\times C)$.\n\n4. Calculation: $(\\frac{1,20,000}{3,098} \\times 80) + (\\frac{3,098}{2} \\times 2) \\approx 3,100 + 3,098 =$ TK 6,198."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Evaluate the logic of the manager's re-order decision mathematically.",
                "answer": "1. Daily Demand: $1,20,000 / 300 = 400$ units.\n\n2. Re-order Point (ROP): (Daily Demand $\\times$ Lead Time) + Safety Stock.\n\n3. Calculation: $(400 \\times 4) + 1,200 = 2,800$ units.\n\n4. Conclusion: The manager's decision to re-order at 2,000 units is illogical and risky because it is below the required 2,800 units, likely leading to a stockout."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-017",
        "stem": "Mr. Emran, a cloth merchant, purchased winter clothes worth TK 10,00,000 on credit from Jesico Garments. The credit terms are 4/10, net 30.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is trade credit?",
                "answer": "Trade credit is a short-term financing arrangement where a buyer is allowed to purchase goods and pay the supplier at a later date."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is maintaining working capital at an optimal level a key responsibility of a financial manager?",
                "answer": "1. Excessive working capital ties up funds unproductively, while insufficient working capital leads to liquidity crises.\n\n2. An optimal level ensures both operational efficiency and maximum profitability."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What will be Mr. Emran’s cost of trade credit if he pays on the 30th day?",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 4\\%; CP = 30; DP = 10$.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $Ktc = \\frac{4}{96} \\times \\frac{360}{20} \\times 100 = 0.0417 \\times 18 \\times 100 =$ 75%."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "By what day must Mr. Emran pay to pay less than the total debt, and how much less will it be?",
                "answer": "1. To pay less, Mr. Emran must pay within the discount period (10 days).\n\n2. Total Debt = TK 10,00,000.\n\n3. Discount: $10,00,000 \\times 4\\% = 40,000$.\n\n4. Conclusion: He will pay TK 40,000 less (Total: 9,60,000) if he pays by the 10th day."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-018",
        "stem": "BGF Ltd. needs 64,000 units annually for a new clothing brand. Purchase price is TK 1,000/unit, ordering cost is TK 500/order, and carrying cost is 1% of the price. Safety stock is 500 units and lead time is 3 days.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?",
                "answer": "EOQ is the ideal order quantity that minimizes the total annual costs of ordering and carrying inventory."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What will be the total inventory cost for BGF Ltd.?",
                "answer": "1. Data: $A = 64,000; O = 500; C = 1000 \\times 1\\% = 10$.\n\n2. EOQ: $\\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 64,000 \\times 500}{10}} = 2,530$ units.\n\n3. Total Cost: $(\\frac{64,000}{2530} \\times 500) + (\\frac{2530}{2} \\times 10) \\approx 12,650 + 12,650 =$ TK 25,300."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Determine the re-order point (ROP) for BGF Ltd. based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Daily Demand: $64,000 / 360 \\approx 178$ units.\n\n2. ROP: (Daily Demand $\\times$ Lead Time) + Safety Stock.\n\n3. Calculation: $(178 \\times 3) + 500 =$ 1,034 units."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "If the lead time increases from 3 days to 5 days, what problems will occur in the inventory system?",
                "answer": "1. A longer lead time increases the risk of stockouts if the re-order point is not adjusted upward.\n\n2. To compensate, safety stock must be increased, which raises carrying costs.\n\n3. Operating efficiency may drop if production halts due to late delivery.\n\n4. New ROP Requirement: $(178 \\times 5) + 500 = 1,390$ units."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-019",
        "stem": "You are the Finance Manager of FC Ltd. Your company purchased goods from MB Ltd. on terms 2.5/15, net 60. You decided to take a short-term bank loan at 18% to grab the discount. Later, MB Ltd. extended the payment period by 10 days.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is trade credit?",
                "answer": "Trade credit is a short-term financing arrangement where a buyer is allowed to purchase goods and pay the supplier at a later date."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is trade credit called spontaneous financing?",
                "answer": "1. It is called spontaneous financing because it arises naturally and automatically from day-to-day business transactions without formal negotiations.\n\n2. As a business expands its purchases, the volume of trade credit grows automatically to support that growth."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of trade credit for FC Ltd. based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 2.5\\%$; $CP = 60$; $DP = 15$.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $Ktc = \\frac{2.5}{97.5} \\times \\frac{360}{45} \\times 100 = 0.0256 \\times 8 \\times 100 =$ 20.51%."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "How will the change in payment time affect your loan decision?",
                "answer": "1. Original Cost: 20.51%. Bank Loan: 18%. (Loan is logical as $18\\% < 20.51\\%$).\n\n2. New CP: $60 + 10 = 70$ days.\n\n3. New Ktc: $\\frac{2.5}{97.5} \\times \\frac{360}{70 - 15} \\times 100 = 0.0256 \\times 6.545 \\times 100 =$ 16.78%.\n\n4. Conclusion: After the extension, the bank loan (18%) becomes more expensive than the trade credit (16.78%). Therefore, the decision should change: the company should stop the bank loan and utilize the trade credit period instead."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-020",
        "stem": "Otol Co. sells 700 lights monthly. Each light costs TK 2,000 and the carrying cost is TK 1. On the other hand, Adhora Co. sells 15,000 lights annually. Their ordering and carrying costs are TK 50 and TK 3 respectively.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is short-term financing?",
                "answer": "Short-term financing refers to the collection of funds for a period of less than one year to meet daily operating expenses."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What do you mean by the cash cycle?",
                "answer": "1. The cash cycle is the time period between the initial outlay of cash for raw materials and the final collection of cash from sales.\n\n2. A shorter cash cycle indicates better liquidity and operational efficiency."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the EOQ for Otol Company.",
                "answer": "1. Data: Annual ($A$) = $700 \\times 12 = 8,400$; $O$ (not given, assume standard or compare costs); $C = 1$.\n\n2. Note: Since $O$ is missing for Otol Co. in the stem, assume $O=0$ or focus on carrying costs. If $O=50$ (same as Adhora): $EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 8400 \\times 50}{1}} =$ 917 units."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "\"The total inventory cost of Otol Co. is higher than Adhora Co.\"—Evaluate this statement.",
                "answer": "1. Otol Cost: $(\\frac{8400}{917} \\times 50) + (\\frac{917}{2} \\times 1) \\approx 458 + 458 =$ TK 916.\n\n2. Adhora EOQ: $\\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 15000 \\times 50}{3}} = 707$ units.\n\n3. Adhora Cost: $(\\frac{15000}{707} \\times 50) + (\\frac{707}{2} \\times 3) \\approx 1060 + 1060 =$ TK 2,120.\n\n4. Conclusion: The statement is false. Adhora Co. has a higher total inventory cost (TK 2,120) than Otol Co. (TK 916)."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-021",
        "stem": "Nobogonga Co. Ltd. requires 10,000 ball bearings annually at TK 75 each. Carrying cost is TK 2 and ordering cost is TK 150. Lead time is 4 days. The company keeps 600 units as safety stock. Due to natural disasters, the lead time increases to 7 days.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is trade credit?",
                "answer": "Trade credit is a spontaneous source of financing where a buyer receives goods now and pays the supplier later."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is inventory maintained?",
                "answer": "1. Inventory is maintained to ensure uninterrupted production and to meet customer demand without delays.\n\n2. It also helps to take advantage of quantity discounts and protect against price fluctuations."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Determine the EOQ based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $A = 10,000; O = 150; C = 2$.\n\n2. Formula: $EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times A \\times O}{C}}$.\n\n3. Calculation: $\\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 10,000 \\times 150}{2}} = \\sqrt{15,00,000} =$ 1,225 units."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Will the delay in arrival due to natural disasters cause any problems in the inventory system?",
                "answer": "1. Daily Usage: $10,000 / 360 \\approx 28$ units.\n\n2. Normal ROP: $(28 \\times 4) + 600 = 712$ units.\n\n3. Natural Disaster Usage: $28 \\times 7 = 196$ units required during wait time.\n\n4. Conclusion: Yes, it will cause a problem. If the inventory was ordered at 712 units, they will only have 600 (Safety) + 112 (Working) units. During the 7-day delay, they consume 196 units. While they won't run out of total stock (since safety stock is 600), their safety buffer will be significantly depleted, leaving them vulnerable to further shocks."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-022",
        "stem": "A shoe manufacturer trades under terms 2/10, net 60. The owner has a bank loan of TK 5,00,000 and is thinking of using it to take the cash discount. Later, the owner extends the payment period by 10 days. The bank loan interest rate is 12%.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?",
                "answer": "EOQ is the ideal order quantity a company should purchase to minimize its total inventory costs, such as ordering and carrying costs."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Who bears the cost of trade credit?",
                "answer": "1. Nominally, the buyer bears the cost if they fail to take the cash discount.\n\n2. Indirectly, the cost may be shifted to the buyer through higher product prices set by the supplier."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of trade credit for the firm.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 2\\%$; $CP = 60$; $DP = 10$.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $\\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{50} \\times 100 =$ 14.69%."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Will the extension of the payment period affect the decision to take the cash discount? Give your opinion.",
                "answer": "1. Original Cost: 14.69%. Bank Loan: 12%. (Loan is better as $12\\% < 14.69\\%$).\n\n2. New CP: $60 + 10 = 70$ days.\n\n3. New Ktc: $\\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{70 - 10} \\times 100 =$ 12.24%.\n\n4. Conclusion: Even with the extension, the bank loan (12%) is still slightly cheaper than the trade credit cost (12.24%). Therefore, the decision to use the bank loan to take the discount remains logical."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-023",
        "stem": "Mr. Sojib can take trade credit under terms 2/15, net 45, or issue 120-day commercial paper. The face value of each commercial paper is TK 100 and the selling price is TK 95.",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is short-term financing?",
                "answer": "Short-term financing refers to the collection of funds for a period of less than one year to meet daily operating expenses."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What do you mean by trade credit?",
                "answer": "1. Trade credit is a spontaneous source of financing where a buyer receives goods now and pays the supplier at a later date.\n\n2. It is an agreement between two businesses that allows for the purchase of goods without immediate cash payment."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of the commercial paper.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $FV = 100$; $SV = 95$; $MP = 120$ days.\n\n2. Formula: $Kcp = \\frac{FV - SV}{SV} \\times \\frac{360}{MP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $\\frac{100 - 95}{95} \\times \\frac{360}{120} \\times 100 = 0.0526 \\times 3 \\times 100 =$ 15.79%."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Which one should Mr. Sojib accept: trade credit or commercial paper? Comment.",
                "answer": "1. Commercial Paper Cost: 15.79% (from C).\n\n2. Trade Credit Cost: $CD = 2\\%; CP = 45; DP = 15$.\n\n3. Calculation: $\\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{30} \\times 100 =$ 24.49%.\n\n4. Conclusion: Sojib should choose commercial paper because its cost (15.79%) is much lower than the cost of giving up the trade credit discount (24.49%)."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-024",
        "stem": "Kids Zone and Child Zone are toy car manufacturers. Kids Zone produces 2,50,000 cars annually. Its ordering cost is TK 400 and carrying cost is TK 2 per unit. Child Zone has a total ordering cost of TK 14,000 and a total carrying cost of TK 8,000.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is lead time?",
                "answer": "Lead time is the total time that elapses between the placement of an order and the receipt of the goods in the warehouse."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What do you mean by accounts receivable management? Explain.",
                "answer": "1. It is the process of ensuring that customers pay their dues on time to maintain cash flow.\n\n2. It involves setting credit policies, evaluating creditworthiness, and implementing collection procedures."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the EOQ for Kids Zone.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $A = 2,50,000$; $O = 400$; $C = 2$.\n\n2. Formula: $EOQ = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times A \\times O}{C}}$.\n\n3. Calculation: $\\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 2,50,000 \\times 400}{2}} = \\sqrt{10,00,00,000} =$ 10,000 units."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Is the total inventory cost of Child Zone higher? Provide a comparative mathematical analysis.",
                "answer": "1. Kids Zone Total Cost: $(\\frac{2,50,000}{10,000} \\times 400) + (\\frac{10,000}{2} \\times 2) = 10,000 + 10,000 =$ TK 20,000.\n\n2. Child Zone Total Cost: $14,000 + 8,000 =$ TK 22,000.\n\n3. Conclusion: Yes, Child Zone’s total inventory cost (TK 22,000) is higher than Kids Zone’s (TK 20,000)."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-025",
        "stem": "Kohinoor Chemicals needs TK 15,00,000. Option 1: Credit purchase at 3/15, net 45. Option 2: Bank loan at 12% interest with 10% compensating balance and interest paid in advance (discount loan). Option 3: 3-month commercial paper, face value TK 2,000, sold at 10% discount, with 3% dealer commission and 2% stamp duty.",
        "meta": "RAJUK Uttara Model College · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is revolving credit?",
                "answer": "Revolving credit is a formal and legal commitment by a bank to lend up to a maximum amount to a firm for a specific period."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is inventory management important?",
                "answer": "1. It ensures an uninterrupted production process and sales flow by preventing stockouts.\n\n2. It minimizes total costs by balancing ordering and carrying costs, ensuring funds are not unnecessarily tied up."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of trade credit for the 1st option.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 3\\%; CP = 45; DP = 15$.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100-CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP-DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $\\frac{3}{97} \\times \\frac{360}{30} \\times 100 =$ 37.11%."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Which option should Kohinoor Chemicals select? Give your opinion.",
                "answer": "1. Opt 1: 37.11% (from C).\n\n2. Opt 2 (Bank): $\\frac{i}{1-i-CB} = \\frac{0.12}{1-0.12-0.10} = 15.38\\%$.\n\n3. Opt 3 (CP): Costs = $10\\%+3\\%+2\\% = 15\\%$. $Kcp = \\frac{15}{85} \\times \\frac{360}{90} \\times 100 = 70.59\\%$.\n\n4. Conclusion: Kohinoor should choose Option 2 (Bank Loan) as it has the lowest effective cost."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-026",
        "stem": "Jaflong Foods sells processed foods. Monthly demand is 10,000 packets. Lead time is 3–5 days. Safety stock is 1,200 units. Working days = 300. Manager re-orders at 2,000 units. AB Co. has annual cash outflow of TK 50,00,000, operating cycle of 100 days, and average payable period of 30 days.",
        "meta": "Notre Dame College · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is spontaneous financing?",
                "answer": "Spontaneous financing refers to sources of funds that arise naturally from day-to-day business operations, such as accounts payable."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Who bears the cost of trade credit?",
                "answer": "1. Nominally, the buyer bears the \"opportunity cost\" if they fail to take the cash discount.\n\n2. Sellers may also shift the cost to buyers by increasing the base price of goods."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What is the Minimum Operating Cash (MOC) for AB Company?",
                "answer": "1. Cash Conversion Cycle (CCC): $100 - 30 = 70$ days.\n\n2. Cash Turnover (CT): $360 / 70 = 5.14$ times.\n\n3. MOC: $50,00,000 / 5.14 =$ TK 9,72,763."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Evaluate the logic of the manager's re-order decision mathematically.",
                "answer": "1. Daily Demand: $(10,000 \\times 12) / 300 = 400$ units.\n\n2. Max ROP: $(Daily Demand \\times Max Lead Time) + Safety Stock$.\n\n3. Calculation: $(400 \\times 5) + 1,200 = 3,200$ units.\n\n4. Conclusion: The decision to re-order at 2,000 units is illogical as it is far below the required 3,200 units, risking a stockout."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-027",
        "stem": "Syedpur Enterprise sells jute products. Annual demand is 12,00,000 units at TK 220 each. Ordering cost is TK 800 and carrying cost is TK 20 per unit. Lead time is 4 days. Safety stock is 12,000 units. Total working days = 300. Manager re-orders at 20,000 units.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Commerce College · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is spontaneous financing?",
                "answer": "Spontaneous financing refers to funds that arise naturally from operations, like trade credit and accruals."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "How does a change in the cash conversion cycle affect cash turnover?",
                "answer": "1. There is an inverse relationship; if the cash conversion cycle decreases, cash turnover increases.\n\n2. A shorter cycle means the company completes the cash-to-cash process more times per year, requiring less idle cash."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the annual total inventory cost for Syedpur Enterprise.",
                "answer": "1. EOQ: $\\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times 12,00,000 \\times 800}{20}} = 9,798$ units.\n\n2. Total Cost: $(\\frac{A}{EOQ} \\times O) + (\\frac{EOQ}{2} \\times C) + (Safety Stock \\times C)$.\n\n3. Calculation: $98,000 + 98,000 + (12,000 \\times 20) =$ TK 4,36,000."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Evaluate the logic of the manager's re-order decision mathematically.",
                "answer": "1. Daily Demand: $12,00,000 / 300 = 4,000$ units.\n\n2. ROP: $(4,000 \\times 4) + 12,000 = 28,000$ units.\n\n3. Conclusion: The manager's decision to re-order at 20,000 units is incorrect. The company should re-order when stock hits 28,000 units to ensure safety."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-028",
        "stem": "Labib Co. purchases on credit under terms 2/20, net 45. Annual sales are 12,000 units, carrying cost is TK 60/unit, ordering cost is TK 800/order, and lead time is 7 days. They maintain safety stock for 3 days. The manager re-orders at 650 units.",
        "meta": "Adamjee Cantonment College · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)?",
                "answer": "EOQ is the order size that minimizes the total annual cost of ordering and carrying inventory."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is the optimal cash balance? Explain with the formula.",
                "answer": "1. It is the cash level that minimizes the sum of opportunity costs (lost interest) and transaction costs.\n\n2. Formula (Baumol Model): $Q = \\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\times T \\times F}{i}}$, where $T$ = Annual cash need, $F$ = Fixed cost, $i$ = Interest rate."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of trade credit for Labib Company.",
                "answer": "1. Data: $CD = 2\\%; CP = 45; DP = 20$.\n\n2. Formula: $Ktc = \\frac{CD}{100 - CD} \\times \\frac{360}{CP - DP} \\times 100$.\n\n3. Calculation: $\\frac{2}{98} \\times \\frac{360}{25} \\times 100 =$ 29.39%."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Mathematically analyze the purchase manager's re-order decision based on the stem.",
                "answer": "1. Daily Demand: $12,000 / 360 = 33.33$ units.\n\n2. Safety Stock: $33.33 \\times 3 = 100$ units.\n\n3. Re-order Point (ROP): $(Daily Demand \\times Lead Time) + Safety Stock$.\n\n4. Calculation: $(33.33 \\times 7) + 100 = 333$ units.\n\n5. Conclusion: The manager re-ordered at 650 units, which is much higher than the required 333 units. While safe, it causes unnecessary carrying costs."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch5-cq-029",
        "stem": "Sigma Co. sells 6,000 watches monthly. Carrying cost is TK 2, price is TK 2,000, and ordering cost is TK 100. Beta Co. sells 50,000 watches annually. Their ordering cost is TK 80 and carrying cost is TK 3.",
        "meta": "Holy Cross College · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
