        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Because it has a specified interest rate (coupon), it is classified as a Coupon Bond.</p>",
        "id": 4598
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>A 10-year bond has 1,000 face value, 1,050 market price, 10% coupon, and 9% required return. (i) CY is 9.52% (ii) Sold at premium (iii) Maturity value is 1,000.</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$$CY = 100/1050 \\approx 9.52\\%$$. Price (1050) > <code>FV</code> (1000), so it's a premium bond. Maturity value equals <code>FV</code>.</p>",
        "id": 4599
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is a bond issued by the government called?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Treasury Bill",
            "Treasury Bond",
            "Corporate Bond",
            "Income Bond"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Treasury bonds are long-term debt instruments issued by the government.</p>",
        "id": 4600
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Who can issue bonds? (i) Government (ii) Foreign company (iii) Corporation.</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three entities have the legal authority to issue debt instruments like bonds to raise capital.</p>",
        "id": 4601
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Who is directly involved in the secondary market? (i) Share buyer (ii) Share seller (iii) Broker.</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>The secondary market (Stock Exchange) involves buyers and sellers trading existing shares through brokers.</p>",
        "id": 4602
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>A bond has 120 interest, 1,000 face value, and 850 market price. What is the approximate Yield to Maturity (YTM)?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "12%",
            "12.12%",
            "14.12%",
            "16.35%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$$YTM \\approx \\frac{120 + (1000-850)/10}{(1000+850)/2} = \\frac{135}{925} \\approx 14.59\\%$$. C is the closest.</p>",
        "id": 4603
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If the YTM is less than the coupon rate, the bond's market price will be:</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Higher than Par",
            "Lower than Par",
            "Equal to Par",
            "Equivalent"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>When market rates are lower than the coupon, the bond becomes more valuable and sells at a premium.</p>",
        "id": 4604
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Face value 2,000, sold at 10% premium. Coupon rate 13%. What is the Current Yield (CY)?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "10%",
            "11.82%",
            "12.82%",
            "13%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Price = 2,200. Int = 260. $$CY = 260 / 2200 \\approx 11.82\\%$$.</p>",
        "id": 4605
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If the market interest rate increases, the value of an existing bond:</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2022",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Increases",
            "Decreases",
            "Remains unchanged",
            "Doubles"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>There is an inverse relationship between market interest rates and bond prices.</p>",
        "id": 4606
    },
