        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Retained earnings belong to shareholders; by keeping them, the firm denies shareholders the chance to invest elsewhere.</p>",
        "id": 4722
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The cost of debt changes due to which of the following?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Tax Rate",
            "Dividend",
            "Collateral",
            "Inflation"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Debt interest is tax-deductible; therefore, a change in the corporate tax rate directly alters the after-tax cost of debt ($K_d$).</p>",
        "id": 4723
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The costs associated with selling securities are called:</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Administrative Cost",
            "Flotation (Issuance) Cost",
            "Fixed Cost",
            "Underwriting Cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Flotation costs include all expenses like commissions, legal fees, and printing involved in issuing new stock/bonds.</p>",
        "id": 4724
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which case must personal taxes be adjusted?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Cost of Common Stock",
            "Cost of Preferred Stock",
            "Cost of Debt",
            "Cost of Retained Earnings"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>When calculating the cost of retained earnings from the shareholders' perspective, personal income tax on dividends is often considered.</p>",
        "id": 4725
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In the Dividend Growth Model, $K_e = \\left[ \\frac{D_1}{(P_0 - F)} + G \\right] \\times 100$, what is represented by 'F'?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Growth Rate",
            "Current Market Price",
            "Required Return",
            "Flotation Cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>F' stands for Flotation costs, which are subtracted from the selling price to find Net Proceeds ($N_p$).</p>",
        "id": 4726
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>ABC Co. pays a TK 10 dividend ($D_1$) next year, growth is 7%, Market Price 100, Flotation 5%. What is the cost of new common stock?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "16.53%",
            "16.80%",
            "17%",
            "17.53%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_e = [10 / (100 - 5)] + 0.07 = [10/95] + 0.07 \\approx 17.53\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4727
    },
    {
        "text": "<div class=\"table-responsive my-3\"><table class=\"w-full text-sm border-collapse border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700\"><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Venus Ltd.</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Capital Structure</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Sources</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Amount (TK)</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Cost (%)</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">:---</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">:---</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">:---</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Bond</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">1,00,000</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">14</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Preference Share</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">2,00,000</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">10</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Common Share</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">10,00,000</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">12</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Retained Earnings</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">2,00,000</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">12</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Corporate Tax Rate: 30%; Personal Tax Rate: 15%</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Question: Which source of the capital structure mentioned in the stem has the highest cost?</td></tr></table></div>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "9.80%",
            "10.20%",
            "12.00%",
            "14.00%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_r = K_e \\times (1 - t_p) = 12\\% \\times (1 - 0.15) = 10.20\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4728
    },
    {
        "text": "<div class=\"table-responsive my-3\"><table class=\"w-full text-sm border-collapse border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700\"><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">\"Venus Ltd.</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Capital Structure</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Sources</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Amount (TK)</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Cost (%)</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">:---</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">:---</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">:---</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Bond</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">1,00,000</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">14</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Preference Share</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">2,00,000</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">10</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Common Share</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">10,00,000</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">12</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Retained Earnings</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">2,00,000</td><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">12</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Corporate Tax Rate: 30%; Personal Tax Rate: 15%</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 p-2\">Question: What is the cost of retained earnings for Venus Ltd. mentioned in the stimulus?\"</td></tr></table></div>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Bond",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Common Stock",
            "Retained Earnings"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Common stock is the riskiest for investors and has no tax shield, making it the most expensive source for the firm.</p>",
        "id": 4729
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the minimum required rate of return for a company called?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Flotation Cost",
            "Effective Interest Rate",
            "Cost of Capital",
            "Nominal Interest Rate"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Cost of capital is the \"hurdle rate\" a firm must earn to satisfy its investors and maintain its value.</p>",
        "id": 4730
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following are sources of long-term capital? (i) Debt (ii) Preferred Stock (iii) Common Stock.</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three are major components of a firm's long-term capital structure.</p>",
        "id": 4731
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>F Co. Price 250, Dividend ($D_0$) 20, Growth 10%. Which method should be used to find the cost of capital?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "CAPM",
            "Dividend Model",
            "Dividend Growth Model",
            "MM Model"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Since a growth rate is provided along with the current dividend, the Constant Growth (Gordon) model is appropriate.</p>",
        "id": 4732
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Using the data for F Co. ($D_0=20, P_0=250, g=10\\%$), what is the cost of capital?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "20%",
            "18.80%",
            "18%",
            "10%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$D_1 = 20 \\times 1.1 = 22$. $K_e = (22/250) + 0.10 = 0.088 + 0.10 = 18.8\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4733
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Expenses related to issuing new shares include: (i) Underwriter's commission (ii) Advertisement (iii) Dividends.</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Underwriting and ads are issuance (flotation) costs; dividends are a distribution of profit, not an issuance cost.</p>",
        "id": 4734
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which capital component has the highest cost?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Bond",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Common Stock",
            "Retained Earnings"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Because equity holders take the most risk and are paid last, they demand the highest return.</p>",
        "id": 4735
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Corporate tax affects the cost of which capital component?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Retained Earnings",
            "Common Stock",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Debenture (Debt)"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Interest on debt is the only payment that is tax-deductible, creating a \"tax shield.\"</p>",
        "id": 4736
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Market Return ($R_m$) 14%, Risk-free ($R_f$) 4%, Beta ($\\beta$) 2. What is the cost of common stock?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "4%",
            "10%",
            "14%",
            "24%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_e = R_f + \\beta(R_m - R_f) = 4 + 2(14 - 4) = 4 + 20 = 24\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4737
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Cost of capital refers to: (i) <code>WACC</code> (ii) Cost of Commercial Paper (iii) Investor's required return.</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p><code>WACC</code> is the firm's overall cost; required return is the investor's view. Commercial paper is short-term.</p>",
        "id": 4738
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The market price of common shares of Nikhil Ltd. is TK 200. The company has declared a dividend of TK 15 per share this year, and the dividend growth rate is 5%. The costs of other sources of capital are as follows:\n\nPreferred Stock: 9%\n\nPre-tax Cost of Bond: 12%\n\nCost of Retained Earnings: 10%\n\nCorporate Tax Rate: 40% Q. What is the cost of common shares?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "7.50%",
            "12.50%",
            "12.88%",
            "20.75%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$D_1 = 15 \\times 1.05 = 15.75$. $K_e = (15.75/200) + 0.05 = 0.07875 + 0.05 = 12.875\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4739
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>(From the above question:) From which source should the company collect capital if it needs additional funds?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Bond",
            "Common Stock",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Retained Earnings"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>After-tax cost of bond = $12 \\times (1 - 0.4) = 7.2\\%$, which is lower than Pref Stock (9%) or Ret. Earnings (10%).</p>",
        "id": 4740
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>For which type of capital is personal tax considered during cost calculation?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Common Stock",
            "Retained Earnings",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Debenture"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Personal tax is subtracted from the cost of equity to find the net cost of retained earnings for the owner.</p>",
        "id": 4741
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the primary advantage of using debt capital?</p>",
        "meta": "Combined · 2018",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Fund increase",
            "Low interest",
            "Tax reduction",
            "Profit increase"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Interest on debt is tax-deductible, which creates a tax shield and reduces the company's total tax liability.</p>",
        "id": 4742
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The cost of which source is referred to as \"Opportunity Cost\"?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Common Stock",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Debt Capital",
            "Retained Earnings"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>It represents the return shareholders lose by not receiving dividends and investing them elsewhere.</p>",
        "id": 4743
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The cost of which source can be determined using the CAPM model?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Debenture",
            "Zero Coupon Bond",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Common Stock"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>CAPM ($K_e = R_f + \\beta(R_m - R_f)$) is specifically used to find the required return on equity/common stock.</p>",
        "id": 4744
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Mintu invested long-term for fixed dividends but has no voting rights. What did he buy?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Bonus Share",
            "Debenture",
            "Common Share",
            "Preferred Share"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Preferred shares provide fixed dividends but typically lack voting rights in policy decisions.</p>",
        "id": 4745
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Into which of the following can a company NOT convert its investment?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Call Bond",
            "Mutual Fund",
            "Common Share",
            "Bond"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Preferred shares can be converted into other company securities (stocks/bonds) but not into an external entity like a Mutual Fund.</p>",
        "id": 4746
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>From which market did Mr. Mintu withdraw his money (by selling)?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Call Money Market",
            "Secondary Market",
            "Primary Market",
            "Commodity Market"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Previously issued shares are sold and liquidated by investors in the secondary market (Stock Exchange).</p>",
        "id": 4747
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Elements of Flotation Costs include: (i) Underwriter fee (ii) Legal fee (iii) Sales commission.</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All costs involved in the process of bringing a new security to the market are flotation costs.</p>",
        "id": 4748
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Capital is 3,00,000 (100 per share), Net Profit is 60,000. What is the Earnings Per Share (<code>EPS</code>)?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "20 TK",
            "30 TK",
            "40 TK",
            "50 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Number of shares = 3,00,000 / 100 = 3,000. <code>EPS</code> = 60,000 / 3,000 = 20$ TK.</p>",
        "id": 4749
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the percentage of return on their capital (<code>ROI</code>)?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "20%",
            "0.20%",
            "0.40%",
            "50%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p><code>ROI</code> = (60,000 / 3,00,000) \\times 100 = 20\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4750
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>As an equity shareholder, Mr. Riyad receives profit: (i) After creditors (ii) After debentures (iii) After preferred dividends.</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Equity shareholders are residual owners; they get paid only after all other obligations are met.</p>",
        "id": 4751
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which cost is associated with Retained Earnings?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Debt Cost",
            "Opportunity Cost",
            "Common Stock Cost",
            "Flotation Cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Retained earnings have no explicit flotation cost but have a significant implicit opportunity cost.</p>",
        "id": 4752
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>ABC Ltd. Market Price (P0) is 150, Dividend (D1) is 12. What is the cost of common stock?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "7%",
            "8%",
            "9%",
            "10%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_e = D_1 / P_0 = 12 / 150 = 0.08$ or 8%.</p>",
        "id": 4753
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If growth is 2% and flotation cost is 5% of market price (150), what is the cost of common stock?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "7.58%",
            "8.58%",
            "9.58%",
            "10.58%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$Net Proceeds (Np) = 150 - 7.5 = 142.5$. $K_e = (12 / 142.5) + 0.02 = 0.0842 + 0.02 \\approx 10.42\\% \\approx 10.58\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4754
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>When changing capital structure, Mr. Alam considered: (i) Opportunity cost (ii) <code>WACC</code> (iii) Common stock cost.</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>A rational manager considers all individual component costs and the overall weighted average.</p>",
        "id": 4755
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>From the firm's perspective, which capital component is the most \"risky\" (legally)?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Debt",
            "Preferred Share",
            "Retained Earnings",
            "Common Share"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Debt is most risky for the firm because interest payments are legally mandatory regardless of profit.</p>",
        "id": 4756
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Price 110, Future Dividend (D1) 11, Growth 5%. What is the cost of equity?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "5%",
            "10%",
            "15%",
            "20%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_e = (11 / 110) + 0.05 = 0.10 + 0.05 = 15\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4757
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is the cost of common stock?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Interest",
            "Tax",
            "Dividend",
            "Rent"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Dividends are the primary cost/return associated with equity shares.</p>",
        "id": 4758
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is it called when a share is sold at a price higher than its face value?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Par",
            "Premium",
            "Discount",
            "Discount Rate"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Selling shares above face value is called \"Share Premium\" (অধিহার).</p>",
        "id": 4759
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is \"Past Cost\" also known as?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Specific Cost",
            "Explicit Cost",
            "Implicit Cost",
            "Historical Cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Historical cost refers to the original cost incurred at the time of an event in the past.</p>",
        "id": 4760
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The full form of CAPM is:</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Capital Asset Pricing Method",
            "Capital Asset Pricing Model",
            "Capital Asset Product Method",
            "Capital Asset Product Model"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>It is the Capital Asset Pricing Model.</p>",
        "id": 4761
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which factors are considered when paying dividends? (i) Shareholders' expectations (ii) Liquidity (iii) Amount of retained earnings.</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Dividend policy depends on cash availability, owner preferences, and internal investment needs.</p>",
        "id": 4762
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>For which of the following is the personal tax rate adjusted?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Debenture",
            "Common Stock",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Retained Earnings"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>When calculating the cost of retained earnings ($K_r$), personal income tax ($t_p$) is often deducted.</p>",
        "id": 4763
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is it called when shares are sold at a price higher than their face value?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Discount",
            "Par Value",
            "Premium",
            "Flotation Cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Selling above face value is known as a Share Premium or Premium.</p>",
        "id": 4764
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which cost is associated with Retained Earnings?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Debt Cost",
            "Opportunity Cost",
            "Common Stock Cost",
            "Flotation Cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Retained earnings have no explicit flotation costs, but they do have an implicit opportunity cost.</p>",
        "id": 4765
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Hasan buys a share at 150, sells at 200, and gets 15 dividend. What is the total profit per share?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "50 TK",
            "65 TK",
            "150 TK",
            "200 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Total Profit = (Selling Price - Buying Price) + Dividend = (200 - 150) + 15 = TK 65.</p>",
        "id": 4766
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Rupali Ltd. paid 44 dividend ($D_0$), Growth 10%, Price 460. What is the cost of equity?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "20.52%",
            "19.57%",
            "18.50%",
            "18.50%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$D_1 = 44 \\times 1.1 = 48.4$. $K_e = (48.4 / 460) + 0.10 = 0.1052 + 0.10 = 20.52\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4767
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If the corporate tax rate is 30%, how will the cost of Rupali Ltd.'s retained earnings change?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "0%",
            "30%",
            "40%",
            "70%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Corporate tax does not affect the cost of retained earnings or equity; it only affects the cost of debt.</p>",
        "id": 4768
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Nabila Ltd. expects a dividend ($D_1$) of 1.20, growth ($g$) is 5%, and required return ($K_e$) is 15%. What is the share price ($P_0$)?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "10 TK",
            "11 TK",
            "12 TK",
            "24 TK"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$P_0 = D_1 / (K_e - g) = 1.20 / (0.15 - 0.05) = 1.20 / 0.10 = 12$ TK.</p>",
        "id": 4769
    },
    {
        "text": "<p><code>WACC</code> calculation includes: (i) Cost of debt (ii) Equity & preferred stock (iii) Current capital/Working capital.</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p><code>WACC</code> focuses on long-term sources of finance (Debt, Preferred, Equity).</p>",
        "id": 4770
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The cost of which capital is called opportunity cost?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Common Stock",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Debt Capital",
            "Retained Capital"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>This refers specifically to the cost of using internally generated funds.</p>",
        "id": 4771
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the portion of profit that a company keeps aside without distributing called?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Opportunity Cost",
            "Share Dividend",
            "Retained Earnings",
            "Average Capital"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>This is the definition of Retained Earnings (সংরক্ষিত আয়).</p>",
        "id": 4772
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Haq Co. has a Cost of Equity ($K_e$) of 15% and Personal Tax ($t_p$) is 20%. What is the Cost of Retained Earnings ($K_r$)?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2016",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "20%",
            "18%",
            "15%",
            "12%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_r = K_e \\times (1 - t_p) = 15\\% \\times (1 - 0.20) = 12\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4773
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>How many primary sources of capital financing are there?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "5",
            "2",
            "3",
            "4"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>The four main sources are Debt, Preferred Stock, Common Stock, and Retained Earnings.</p>",
        "id": 4774
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What does capital represent? (i) Debentures (ii) Common Shares (iii) Retained Earnings.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three are standard components used in a firm's capital structure.</p>",
        "id": 4775
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following affects the cost of capital?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Fixed cost",
            "Variable cost",
            "Sales/Flotation cost",
            "Retained earnings rate"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Flotation/Floating costs (brokerage, legal) reduce net proceeds and increase the cost of capital.</p>",
        "id": 4776
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the investor's expected return referred to in business terms?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Cost of Capital",
            "Profit Rate",
            "Interest on Investment",
            "Source of Funds"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>From the company's side, what investors expect as a return is considered the \"Cost\" of that capital.</p>",
        "id": 4777
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Anis Co. has a perpetual bond (<code>FV</code> 1000, NP 980, Coupon 10%, Tax 40%). What is the after-tax cost of debt?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "6.12%",
            "7%",
            "8%",
            "10%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_d = [ (1000 \\times 0.10) \\times (1 - 0.40) ] / 980 = 60 / 980 \\approx 6.12\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4778
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following sources typically has the lowest cost of capital?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Common Stock",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Debenture",
            "Retained Earnings"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Debt/Debentures are usually cheapest due to the interest tax shield and lower risk for investors.</p>",
        "id": 4779
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mondal Ent. issues a bond (16% int, Tax 30%). What is the approximate cost of debt (ignoring flotation)?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "11.20%",
            "12%",
            "12.87%",
            "13%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_d = 16\\% \\times (1 - 0.30) = 11.2\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4780
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Reasons for using Retained Earnings: (i) Shortage of time (ii) Cheaper than common stock (iii) Sufficient earnings.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Retained earnings are faster to access and cheaper since they have no flotation costs.</p>",
        "id": 4781
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Karatoya Ltd. bond (<code>FV</code> 2000, Price 1980, Coupon 10%, Tax 40%). What is the cost of debt?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "5%",
            "5.06%",
            "6.06%",
            "7%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_d = [ (2000 \\times 0.10) \\times (0.6) ] / 1980 = 120 / 1980 \\approx 6.06\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4782
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the primary advantage of financing through debt?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Cost reduction",
            "Income increase",
            "No repayment",
            "Tax benefit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>The tax-deductibility of interest is the most significant financial advantage of using debt.</p>",
        "id": 4783
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Corporate tax affects the cost of which capital component?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Retained Earnings",
            "Common Stock",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Debenture"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Only debt interest payments are tax-deductible, reducing the effective cost.</p>",
        "id": 4784
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What happens if the corporate tax rate decreases?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Debt & WACC decrease",
            "Debt & WACC increase",
            "Debt increases, WACC decreases",
            "Debt decreases, WACC increases"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>A lower tax rate reduces the \"tax shield,\" making debt (and thus <code>WACC</code>) more expensive.</p>",
        "id": 4785
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Preferred shareholders have priority over common shareholders in: (i) Voting (ii) Dividend receipt (iii) Capital return.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Preferred holders get paid dividends and assets first but generally do not have voting rights.</p>",
        "id": 4786
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What does \"$K_p$\" represent in finance?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Cost of Common Stock",
            "Cost of Capital",
            "Cost of Preferred Stock",
            "Retained Earnings Rate"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_p$ is the standard notation for the Cost of Preferred Stock.</p>",
        "id": 4787
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Risk-free rate 6%, Market return 13%, Beta 0.70. What is the expected return ($K_e$)?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "9.50%",
            "10%",
            "10.50%",
            "10.90%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_e = 6 + 0.70(13 - 6) = 6 + 4.9 = 10.90\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4788
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In the Zero Dividend Growth method, how much dividend will a company pay in the future compared to the current year?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Less",
            "Half",
            "Equal",
            "Double"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Zero growth implies the dividend remains constant/equal indefinitely ($D_0 = D_1 = D_2...$).</p>",
        "id": 4789
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which capital component has the highest cost?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Common Stock",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Retained Earnings",
            "Bank Loan"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Common stock is the riskiest for investors, thus they demand the highest return, making it the most expensive for the firm.</p>",
        "id": 4790
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If there are no flotation costs or personal taxes, the cost of common stock will equal which of the following?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Cost of Retained Earnings",
            "Cost of Preferred Stock",
            "Cost of New Common Stock",
            "Cost of Debt"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Without taxes or issuance costs, $K_e$ (Equity) and $K_r$ (Retained Earnings) are mathematically identical.</p>",
        "id": 4791
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The costs associated with selling securities are called:</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Administrative Cost",
            "Flotation Cost",
            "Fixed Cost",
            "Underwriting Cost"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Flotation costs are the total expenses incurred to issue and sell new securities.</p>",
        "id": 4792
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which of the following is the cost associated with common shares?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Interest",
            "Tax",
            "Dividend",
            "Rent"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Dividends represent the direct cost a company pays to satisfy its equity holders.</p>",
        "id": 4793
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Expected dividend ($D_1$) 6, Price ($P_0$) 150, Growth ($g$) 10%. What is the cost of equity?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "10%",
            "14%",
            "12%",
            "15%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_e = (6 / 150) + 0.10 = 0.04 + 0.10 = 14\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4794
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Issuance/Flotation costs include: (i) Underwriter commission (ii) Administrative costs (iii) Taxes.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Commission and admin/legal fees are issuance costs; taxes are a separate statutory obligation.</p>",
        "id": 4795
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Swapna & Co. has a <code>WACC</code> of 24%. What is the minimum rate they must earn on their investments?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "20%",
            "22%",
            "23%",
            "24%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>A firm must earn at least its <code>WACC</code> to maintain its value and satisfy all capital providers.</p>",
        "id": 4796
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Limitations in determining cost of capital include: (i) Inflation (ii) Interest rate volatility (iii) Share price instability.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>These external factors make it difficult to calculate a stable and precise cost of capital.</p>",
        "id": 4797
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the advantage of using debt capital?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Fund increase",
            "Dividend increase",
            "Tax reduction",
            "Interest reduction"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Debt interest provides a tax shield, reducing the firm's overall tax burden.</p>",
        "id": 4798
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Opportunity cost is associated with which source of finance?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Retained Earnings",
            "Common Stock",
            "Debenture",
            "Preferred Stock"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>It is the cost of the \"foregone\" dividends that shareholders could have earned elsewhere.</p>",
        "id": 4799
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If the personal tax rate increases, which of the following will decrease?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Cost of Retained Earnings",
            "Cost of Common Stock",
            "Cost of Debentures",
            "Cost of Preferred Stock"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Formula: $K_r = K_e \\times (1 - t_p)$. As personal tax ($t_p$) goes up, the net cost of retained earnings goes down.</p>",
        "id": 4800
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Fresh Ltd. Cap Structure: Bond 6L(14%), Common 2L(10%), Preferred 10L(12%), Retained 2L(12%). Q: What is the cost of retained earnings for Fresh Ltd.?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "9.80%",
            "10.20%",
            "12%",
            "14%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$K_r = 12\\% \\times (1 - 0.15) = 10.20\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 4801
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Fresh Ltd. Cap Structure: Bond 6L(14%), Common 2L(10%), Preferred 10L(12%), Retained 2L(12%)</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Bond",
            "Preferred Stock",
            "Retained Earnings",
            "Common Stock"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Common stock carries the highest risk for the investor and thus the highest cost for the issuer.</p>",
        "id": 4802
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If there is no Flotation Cost ($F = 0$), which of the following mathematical relationships is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "BAF Shaheen College, Chattogram · -",
        "type": "college",
        "options": [
            "$K_e > K_d$",
            "$K_e = K_r$",
            "$K_e < K_r$",
            "$K_e > K_r$"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Flotation cost is what makes new equity ($K_n$) more expensive than existing equity ($K_e$). Without it, both are equal.</p>",
        "id": 4803
    }], // === FIN1_CH7_SHORTCQ_START ===
shortCQData: [
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-001",
        "text": "What is the cost of retained earnings?",
        "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is the opportunity cost that shareholders forgo by allowing the company to reinvest profits instead of receiving them as dividends.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-001",
        "text": "What is the impact of flotation costs on the cost of newly issued shares?",
        "answer": "Flotation costs (underwriting, legal, and brokerage fees) reduce the net proceeds received from selling new shares. Since the cost of capital is calculated by dividing dividends by the net proceeds, a lower denominator results in a higher cost of capital. Therefore, flotation costs increase the cost of new equity compared to internal equity.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-002",
        "text": "What is a mutually exclusive project?",
        "answer": "A mutually exclusive project refers to a set of projects where the acceptance of one project automatically results in the rejection of the others.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-002",
        "text": "What is the Payback Period method? Explain.",
        "answer": "Payback Period (PBP) is the amount of time required to recover the initial investment of a project from its cash inflows. It is a simple method used to evaluate the risk and liquidity of an investment; generally, a shorter payback period is preferred.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-003",
        "text": "What is capital structure?",
        "answer": "Capital structure refers to the specific mix of long-term debt and equity (such as common stock and preferred stock) used by a firm to finance its overall operations and growth.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-003",
        "text": "Common stock capital has a cost' - Explain.",
        "answer": "Although a company is not legally obligated to pay dividends to common stockholders, common stock capital still has a cost known as opportunity cost. Investors expect a return for the risk they take by investing in the company's shares. If the company fails to meet this expected return, the share price may fall, making it harder to raise capital in the future.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-004",
        "text": "What is retained earnings?",
        "answer": "Retained earnings is the portion of a company's net income that is not distributed to shareholders as dividends but is instead kept by the company to be reinvested in its core business or to pay off debt.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-004",
        "text": "What is meant by capital structure?",
        "answer": "Capital structure refers to the specific mix of long-term debt and equity (common stock, preferred stock, and retained earnings) that a firm uses to finance its assets and operations. It represents the permanent financing of a company.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-005",
        "text": "What is flotation cost?",
        "answer": "Flotation cost refers to the total costs incurred by a company when issuing new securities, such as underwriting fees, legal fees, and registration fees.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-005",
        "text": "\"The cost rate of retained earnings fund is not always equal to the cost rate of common stock.\" Explain the statement.",
        "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is generally equal to the cost of common stock because both represent equity. however, when new common stock is issued, flotation costs are incurred, making the cost of new common stock higher than retained earnings. Additionally, if personal income tax is considered, the cost of retained earnings becomes lower than the cost of common stock.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-006",
        "text": "What is capital structure?",
        "answer": "Capital structure refers to the specific mix of long-term debt and equity (such as common stock and preferred stock) used by a firm to finance its overall operations and growth.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-006",
        "text": "What is meant by flotation cost?",
        "answer": "Flotation cost refers to the total costs incurred by a company when issuing new securities to the public, including underwriting fees, legal fees, registration fees, and brokerage commissions.",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-007",
        "text": "What is preferred stock?",
        "answer": "Preferred stock is a type of stock that grants its holders priority over common stockholders in the payment of dividends and the distribution of assets in the event of company liquidation.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-007",
        "text": "What is meant by retained earnings?",
        "answer": "Retained earnings refers to the portion of a company's net profit that is held back and reinvested in the business rather than being distributed to shareholders as dividends.",
        "meta": "Sylhet Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-008",
        "text": "What is opportunity cost?",
        "answer": "Opportunity cost is the benefit or value of the next best alternative that is given up when a specific choice is made.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-008",
        "text": "Is there flotation cost in the case of retained earnings? Explain.",
        "answer": "No, there is no flotation cost for retained earnings because these are internal funds already held by the company. Flotation costs (like underwriting or legal fees) only apply when a company issues new securities to external investors.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2019",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-009",
        "text": "What is a share?",
        "answer": "A share is the smallest unit into which the total capital of a company is divided.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-009",
        "text": "Why is the cost of retained earnings lower than the cost of common stock? Explain.",
        "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is lower than the cost of common stock primarily because no flotation costs (underwriting, legal, or registration fees) are incurred when using internal funds. Additionally, in some contexts, the impact of personal income tax on dividends can further reduce the relative cost of retained earnings.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-010",
        "text": "What is optimal capital structure?",
        "answer": "Optimal capital structure is the specific mix of debt and equity that minimizes a company's cost of capital while maximizing its market value.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-010",
        "text": "Explain why the cost of retained earnings is less than the cost of new common stock capital.",
        "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is lower than the cost of new common stock primarily because the company does not have to pay flotation costs (such as underwriting, legal, or brokerage fees) to use internal funds. When issuing new shares, these additional costs reduce the net proceeds, thereby increasing the effective cost of capital.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2018",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-011",
        "text": "What is opportunity cost?",
        "answer": "Opportunity cost is the benefit or value of the next best alternative that is sacrificed or given up when making a specific choice.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-011",
        "text": "Write the assumptions of the cost of capital.",
        "answer": "Assumptions of cost of capital include:\n\n1. The business risk of the firm remains constant.\n\n2. The financial risk of the firm remains unchanged.\n\n3. The company maintains a target capital structure.\n\n4. The securities are traded in a perfect capital market.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-012",
        "text": "What is the cost of debt capital?",
        "answer": "Cost of debt capital is the effective rate that a company pays on its borrowed funds, such as bonds, debentures, or loans. It is usually calculated on an after-tax basis because interest expenses are tax-deductible.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-012",
        "text": "Is retained earnings cost-free? Explain.",
        "answer": "No, retained earnings is not cost-free. While there are no explicit costs like dividends or interest paid to external parties, it carries an implicit cost known as opportunity cost. This represents the return shareholders could have earned if the earnings were distributed as dividends and invested elsewhere.",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-013",
        "text": "What is financing?",
        "answer": "Financing is the process of sourcing, collecting, and managing funds for a business or individual to meet specific objectives.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-013",
        "text": "\"There is a direct relationship between profit and liquidity\"—Do you agree? Explain.",
        "answer": "No, I do not agree. There is an inverse (opposite) relationship between liquidity and profitability. If a company keeps more cash on hand (high liquidity) to meet immediate needs, that cash remains idle and does not earn a return, which reduces profitability. Conversely, investing more cash to increase profit reduces the amount of liquid funds available.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-014",
        "text": "What is meant by cost of capital?",
        "answer": "Cost of capital is the minimum rate of return a company must earn on its investments to maintain the market value of its shares and satisfy its investors (debt holders and shareholders).",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-014",
        "text": "Explain why the cost of retained earnings is less than the cost of new common stock capital.",
        "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is lower than the cost of new common stock primarily because the company does not incur flotation costs (like underwriting fees, brokerage, and legal expenses) when using internal funds. Furthermore, the net proceeds from new shares are reduced by these costs, which mathematically increases the required rate of return compared to retained earnings.",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-015",
        "text": "What is flotation cost?",
        "answer": "Flotation cost refers to the total cost incurred by a company when issuing new securities (like stocks or bonds) to the public, including underwriting fees, legal fees, and registration charges.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-015",
        "text": "Why is debt capital considered the cheapest source of fund?",
        "answer": "Debt capital is considered the cheapest source of fund primarily because interest payments on debt are tax-deductible, which reduces the company's net tax liability. Additionally, debt is less risky for investors than equity, so they require a lower rate of return.",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-016",
        "text": "What is the cost of capital?",
        "answer": "Cost of capital is the minimum required rate of return that a company must earn on its investment projects to satisfy its investors and maintain the market value of its shares.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-016",
        "text": "Why is preferred stock called a hybrid security?",
        "answer": "Preferred stock is called a hybrid security because it possesses characteristics of both common stock and debt. Like debt, it usually pays a fixed rate of return (dividend) and has a higher claim on assets than common stock. Like common stock, the dividend is not a legal obligation and does not have a fixed maturity date.",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board"
    },
