    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-022",
        "text": "Why does the cost of capital increase due to issuing new shares? Explain.",
        "answer": "The cost of capital increases when issuing new shares primarily due to flotation costs. These include underwriting fees, legal fees, and registration charges that reduce the net proceeds received by the company from the sale of each share. Consequently, the company must earn a higher rate of return on the remaining capital to provide the same expected return to shareholders.",
        "meta": "Dhaka Commerce College · 2026",
