    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-026",
        "text": "Calculate the cost of common stock.",
        "answer": "Calculation of Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$):\n\nSelling Price ($P_0$) = 10 Taka\n\nExpected Dividend ($D_1$) = 2 Taka\n\nGrowth Rate ($g$) = 0% (as no growth is mentioned)\n\nFormula: $K_e = (\\frac{D_1}{P_0}) \\times 100$\n\n$K_e = (\\frac{2}{10}) \\times 100$\n\n$K_e = 20\\%$\n\nAnswer: 20%",
        "meta": "College · Finance",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-027",
        "text": "What is cost of capital?",
        "answer": "Cost of capital is the minimum rate of return that a business must earn on its investments to satisfy its investors (shareholders and debt holders) and maintain its market value.",
        "meta": "Cantonment College, Jashore · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-027",
        "text": "What is meant by opportunity cost? Explain.",
        "answer": "Opportunity cost is the value of the next best alternative that is foregone when a choice is made. In finance, if a firm uses its funds for Project A, the return it could have earned from Project B (the next best option) is considered the opportunity cost of Project A.",
        "meta": "Cantonment College, Jashore · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-028",
        "text": "What is flotation cost?",
        "answer": "Flotation cost refers to the total expenses incurred by a company when issuing new securities to the public, such as underwriting fees, legal fees, and brokerage.",
        "meta": "Cantonment College, Jashore · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-028",
        "text": "\"The cost of retained earnings is not always equal to the cost of common stock.\" Explain the statement.",
        "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is generally equal to the cost of common stock, but they differ if there are personal taxes or flotation costs. When a company issues new common stock, it must pay flotation costs, making the cost of new equity higher than the cost of retained earnings. Additionally, if shareholders pay personal income tax on dividends, the opportunity cost (cost of retained earnings) is adjusted downward.",
        "meta": "Cantonment College, Jashore · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-029",
        "text": "What is flotation cost?",
        "answer": "Flotation cost refers to the total expenses incurred by a company when issuing new securities (like stocks or bonds) to the public, such as underwriting fees, legal fees, and brokerage commissions.",
        "meta": "Ispahani Public School and College, Cumilla · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-029",
        "text": "What is meant by opportunity cost? Explain.",
        "answer": "Opportunity cost is the value or benefit lost by choosing one alternative over another. In finance, if a company invests its funds in a specific project, the return it could have earned by investing that same money in the next best available project is considered the opportunity cost.",
        "meta": "Ispahani Public School and College, Cumilla · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-030",
        "text": "What is capital structure?",
        "answer": "Capital structure refers to the specific mix of long-term debt and equity used by a firm to finance its overall operations and growth.",
        "meta": "Abdul Kadir Mollah City College, Narsingdi · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-030",
        "text": "Common stock capital has a cost' - Explain.",
        "answer": "Common stock capital has a cost because shareholders expect a return on their investment in exchange for the risk they take. This is an opportunity cost for the company, as it represents the rate of return the firm must earn to satisfy its investors and maintain the share price.",
        "meta": "Abdul Kadir Mollah City College, Narsingdi · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-031",
        "text": "What is optimal capital structure?",
        "answer": "Optimal capital structure is the specific mix of debt and equity that minimizes a company's Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) while maximizing the overall market value of the firm.",
        "meta": "Abdul Kadir Mollah City College, Narsingdi · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-031",
        "text": "Why is the cost of retained earnings lower than the cost of common stock?",
        "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is lower than the cost of common stock primarily because of flotation costs. When a company issues new common shares, it must pay underwriting fees, legal fees, and other issuance expenses. Retained earnings are internal funds, so no such flotation costs are incurred, making them a cheaper source of equity.",
        "meta": "Abdul Kadir Mollah City College, Narsingdi · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-032",
        "text": "What is cost of capital?",
        "answer": "Cost of capital is the minimum rate of return a company must earn on its investments to satisfy its investors and maintain its market value.",
        "meta": "Safiuddin Sarker Academy and College, Tongi, Gazipur · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-032",
        "text": "What impact does flotation cost have on the cost of newly issued shares? Explain.",
        "answer": "Flotation cost increases the cost of newly issued shares. When a company issues new shares, it incurs expenses like underwriting fees and brokerage. These costs reduce the net proceeds received from the sale, which in turn increases the effective percentage cost of that capital for the firm.",
        "meta": "Safiuddin Sarker Academy and College, Tongi, Gazipur · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-a-033",
        "text": "What is cost of capital?",
        "answer": "Cost of capital is the minimum rate of return that a business must earn on its investments to satisfy its investors (stockholders and debt holders) and maintain its market value.",
        "meta": "Government Commerce College, Chattogram · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-short-b-033",
        "text": "What impact does flotation cost have on the cost of newly issued shares? Explain.",
        "answer": "Flotation cost increases the cost of newly issued shares. When a company issues new shares, it incurs expenses such as underwriting fees, legal fees, and brokerage. These costs reduce the net proceeds ($NSV$) received from the sale, and since $NSV$ is the denominator in the cost of equity formula, the total percentage cost of that capital increases.",
        "meta": "Government Commerce College, Chattogram · 2026",
        "type": "college"
    }
],
