fullCQData: [
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-001",
        "stem": "Chitra Ltd. has issued a 5-year bond with a face value of 1,000 taka at a 12% coupon rate. Flotation cost per bond is 2%. On the other hand, Ganga Ltd. operates its business with debt, preferred stock, and common equity capital, where the specific costs and capital ratios are 12%, 14%, & 15% and 30%, 30%, & 40% respectively. The company's rate of return on investment is 15%. The corporate tax rate for both companies is 30%.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is the cost of retained earnings?",
                "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is the opportunity cost that shareholders forgo by allowing the company to reinvest profits instead of receiving them as dividends."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is the impact of flotation costs on the cost of newly issued shares?",
                "answer": "Flotation costs (underwriting, legal, and brokerage fees) reduce the net proceeds received from selling new shares. Since the cost of capital is calculated by dividing dividends by the net proceeds, a lower denominator results in a higher cost of capital. Therefore, flotation costs increase the cost of new equity compared to internal equity."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What is the cost of the issued bond of Chitra Ltd. mentioned in the stem?",
                "answer": "Calculation for Chitra Ltd. Irredeemable Bond Cost:\n\nFace Value (FV) = 1,000\n\nCoupon Rate = 12%\n\nInterest (I) = 1,000 × 12% = 120\n\nTax Rate (T) = 30% or 0.30\n\nFlotation Cost (FC) = 2% of 1,000 = 20\n\nNet Sale Value (NSV) = 1,000 - 20 = 980\n\nFormula: $K_d = \\frac{I(1-T)}{NSV} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{120(1-0.30)}{980} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{84}{980} \\times 100 = 8.57\\%$\n\nAnswer: 8.57%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Analyze the efficiency of the capital structure of Ganga Ltd. mentioned in the stem.",
                "answer": "Calculation for Ganga Ltd. WACC:\n\nCost of Debt ($K_d$) = 12% × (1 - 0.30) = 8.4%\n\nCost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$) = 14%\n\nCost of Common Equity ($K_e$) = 15%\n\nWeights: $W_d = 0.30, W_p = 0.30, W_e = 0.40$\n\nWACC = $(K_d \\times W_d) + (K_p \\times W_p) + (K_e \\times W_e)$\n\nWACC = $(8.4 \\times 0.30) + (14 \\times 0.30) + (15 \\times 0.40)$\n\nWACC = $2.52\\% + 4.2\\% + 6.0\\% = 12.72\\%$\n\nAnalysis: The company's Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) is 12.72%, while its Return on Investment (ROI) is 15%. Since $ROI (15\\%) > WACC (12.72\\%)$, the capital structure is efficient as the company is generating more value than the cost of its funds."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-002",
        "stem": "Mr. S Alam is the financial manager of a company. He is considering investing in a project. The initial estimated cash outflow of the project is 2,00,000 taka. The project duration is 4 years and there is no salvage value. The company charges depreciation using the straight-line method. The required rate of return is 10% and the corporate tax rate is 40%. The projected pre-tax cash inflows are as follows:\n\n*table\n| Description | Year-1 | Year-2 | Year-3 | Year-4 |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Pre-tax Cash Inflow (Taka) | 80,000 | 70,000 | 80,000 | 1,00,000 |",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is a mutually exclusive project?",
                "answer": "A mutually exclusive project refers to a set of projects where the acceptance of one project automatically results in the rejection of the others."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is the Payback Period method? Explain.",
                "answer": "Payback Period (PBP) is the amount of time required to recover the initial investment of a project from its cash inflows. It is a simple method used to evaluate the risk and liquidity of an investment; generally, a shorter payback period is preferred."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the Average Rate of Return (ARR) of the project.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate Annual Depreciation\n\nDepreciation = (Initial Investment - Salvage Value) / Life\n\nDepreciation = (2,00,000 - 0) / 4 = 50,000 Taka.\n\nStep 2: Calculate Average After-Tax Profit\n\nYear 1: (80k-50k) * (1-0.4) = 18,000\n\nYear 2: (70k-50k) * (1-0.4) = 12,000\n\nYear 3: (80k-50k) * (1-0.4) = 18,000\n\nYear 4: (100k-50k) * (1-0.4) = 30,000\n\nTotal Profit = 78,000\n\nAvg Profit = 78,000 / 4 = 19,500.\n\nStep 3: Calculate Average Investment\n\nAvg Investment = (2,00,000 + 0) / 2 = 1,00,000.\n\nStep 4: Calculate ARR\n\nARR = (19,500 / 1,00,000) * 100 = 19.5%."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Calculate the Net Present Value (NPV) of the project and comment on its acceptability.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate Cash Flow After Tax (CFAT)\n\nCFAT = (Pre-tax Cash Flow - Depreciation) * (1 - Tax) + Depreciation\n\nYear 1: (30,000 * 0.6) + 50,000 = 68,000\n\nYear 2: (20,000 * 0.6) + 50,000 = 62,000\n\nYear 3: (30,000 * 0.6) + 50,000 = 68,000\n\nYear 4: (50,000 * 0.6) + 50,000 = 80,000\n\nStep 2: Calculate Present Value (PV) at 10%\n\nPV1: 68,000 / (1.1)^1 = 61,818\n\nPV2: 62,000 / (1.1)^2 = 51,240\n\nPV3: 68,000 / (1.1)^3 = 51,089\n\nPV4: 80,000 / (1.1)^4 = 54,641\n\nTotal PV = 2,18,788\n\nStep 3: Calculate NPV\n\nNPV = Total PV - Initial Investment\n\nNPV = 2,18,788 - 2,00,000 = 18,788 Taka.\n\nComment: Since the NPV is positive (18,788 > 0), the project is financially viable and should be accepted."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-003",
        "stem": "The capital structure of Nusrat Ltd. is as follows:\n\n*table\n| Source of Capital | Amount (Taka) |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| Common Stock Capital | 5,00,000 |\n| 8% Preferred Stock Capital | 2,00,000 |\n| 10% Bond | 3,00,000 |\n| **Total** | **10,00,000** |\n\nThe market price per common share is 200 Taka. The company decided to pay a dividend of 15 Taka per share next year. The dividend growth rate is 4%. The company's tax rate is 40%.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is capital structure?",
                "answer": "Capital structure refers to the specific mix of long-term debt and equity (such as common stock and preferred stock) used by a firm to finance its overall operations and growth."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Common stock capital has a cost' - Explain.",
                "answer": "Although a company is not legally obligated to pay dividends to common stockholders, common stock capital still has a cost known as opportunity cost. Investors expect a return for the risk they take by investing in the company's shares. If the company fails to meet this expected return, the share price may fall, making it harder to raise capital in the future."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of common stock capital of the company.",
                "answer": "Calculation for Cost of Common Equity ($K_e$):\n\nCurrent Market Price ($P_0$) = 200 Taka\n\nExpected Dividend ($D_1$) = 15 Taka\n\nGrowth Rate ($g$) = 4% or 0.04\n\nFormula (Constant Growth Model):\n\n$K_e = (\\frac{D_1}{P_0} + g) \\times 100$\n\n$K_e = (\\frac{15}{200} + 0.04) \\times 100$\n\n$K_e = (0.075 + 0.04) \\times 100$\n\n$K_e = 0.115 \\times 100 = 11.5\\%$\n\nAnswer: 11.5%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Calculate the Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) of the firm.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate individual costs\n\n1. Cost of Equity ($K_e$) = 11.5% (from Question C)\n\n2. Cost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$) = 8%\n\n3. After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$):\n\n$K_d = I(1 - T) = 10\\% \\times (1 - 0.40) = 6\\%$\n\nStep 2: Determine Weights ($W$)\n\nTotal Capital = 10,00,000\n\n$W_e$ (Equity) = 5,00,000 / 10,00,000 = 0.5\n\n$W_p$ (Preferred) = 2,00,000 / 10,00,000 = 0.2\n\n$W_d$ (Debt) = 3,00,000 / 10,00,000 = 0.3\n\nStep 3: Calculate WACC\n\nWACC = $(K_e \\times W_e) + (K_p \\times W_p) + (K_d \\times W_d)$\n\nWACC = $(11.5 \\times 0.5) + (8 \\times 0.2) + (6 \\times 0.3)$\n\nWACC = $5.75\\% + 1.6\\% + 1.8\\% = 9.15\\%$\n\nAnswer: 9.15%"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-004",
        "stem": "The market price of each share of Tonni Ltd. is 250 Taka. The company pays a dividend of 16 Taka per share. The dividend growth rate of the company is 6%.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is retained earnings?",
                "answer": "Retained earnings is the portion of a company's net income that is not distributed to shareholders as dividends but is instead kept by the company to be reinvested in its core business or to pay off debt."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is meant by capital structure?",
                "answer": "Capital structure refers to the specific mix of long-term debt and equity (common stock, preferred stock, and retained earnings) that a firm uses to finance its assets and operations. It represents the permanent financing of a company."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of retained earnings for Tonni Ltd.",
                "answer": "Calculation for Cost of Retained Earnings ($K_r$):\n\nCurrent Market Price ($P_0$) = 250 Taka\n\nCurrent Dividend ($D_0$) = 16 Taka\n\nGrowth Rate ($g$) = 6% or 0.06\n\nNext year's expected dividend ($D_1$) = $D_0(1+g)$ = $16(1+0.06)$ = 16.96 Taka\n\nFormula:\n\n$K_r = (\\frac{D_1}{P_0} + g) \\times 100$\n\n$K_r = (\\frac{16.96}{250} + 0.06) \\times 100$\n\n$K_r = (0.06784 + 0.06) \\times 100$\n\n$K_r = 0.12784 \\times 100$\n\n$K_r$ = 12.78%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "If the personal tax rate is 30%, what will be the impact on the cost of retained earnings for Tonni Ltd.? Analyze.",
                "answer": "Impact of Personal Tax on Cost of Retained Earnings:\n\nPersonal Tax Rate ($T_p$) = 30% or 0.30\n\nWhen personal tax is considered, the formula for the cost of retained earnings changes because shareholders only receive the after-tax portion of dividends if they were distributed.\n\nFormula:\n\n$K_r = [(\\frac{D_1}{P_0} + g)] \\times (1 - T_p)$\n\n$K_r = 12.784\\% \\times (1 - 0.30)$\n\n$K_r = 12.784\\% \\times 0.70$\n\n$K_r$ = 8.95%\n\nAnalysis: The cost of retained earnings decreases from 12.78% to 8.95% when a 30% personal tax rate is applied. This is because the opportunity cost to the shareholder is lower; if the earnings were paid out as dividends, the shareholder would have lost 30% to taxes anyway. Therefore, the effective cost to the firm for using these internal funds is reduced."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-005",
        "stem": "Source of Capital and Amount (Taka):\n\n*table\n| Source of Capital | Amount (Taka) |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| Common Stock | 20,00,000 |\n| 14% Preferred Stock | 5,00,000 |\n| 15% Debenture | 15,00,000 |\n| **Total** | **40,00,000** |\n\nThe company's Beta value is 2, the Market Portfolio return rate is 15%, and the Risk-free return rate is 7%. Corporate tax rate is 40%. The company's expected rate of return is 25%. The financial manager considers the overall cost of capital for investment.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2019",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is flotation cost?",
                "answer": "Flotation cost refers to the total costs incurred by a company when issuing new securities, such as underwriting fees, legal fees, and registration fees."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "\"The cost rate of retained earnings fund is not always equal to the cost rate of common stock.\" Explain the statement.",
                "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is generally equal to the cost of common stock because both represent equity. however, when new common stock is issued, flotation costs are incurred, making the cost of new common stock higher than retained earnings. Additionally, if personal income tax is considered, the cost of retained earnings becomes lower than the cost of common stock."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost rate of the company's common stock.",
                "answer": "Calculation of Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$) using CAPM:\n\nRisk-free rate ($R_f$) = 7% or 0.07\n\nMarket return ($R_m$) = 15% or 0.15\n\nBeta ($\\beta$) = 2\n\nFormula: $K_e = R_f + (R_m - R_f) \\times \\beta$\n\n$K_e = 7\\% + (15\\% - 7\\%) \\times 2$\n\n$K_e = 7\\% + (8\\%) \\times 2$\n\n$K_e = 7\\% + 16\\% = 23\\%$\n\nAnswer: 23%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Will the company be profitable if it invests using the current capital structure? Comment through mathematical analysis.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate individual costs\n\n1. Cost of Equity ($K_e$) = 23% (from Question C)\n\n2. Cost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$) = 14%\n\n3. After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$) = $I(1 - T) = 15\\% \\times (1 - 0.40) = 9\\%$\n\nStep 2: Determine Weights ($W$)\n\nTotal Capital = 20,00,000 + 5,00,000 + 15,00,000 = 40,00,000\n\n$W_e$ = 20/40 = 0.50\n\n$W_p$ = 5/40 = 0.125\n\n$W_d$ = 15/40 = 0.375\n\nStep 3: Calculate WACC\n\nWACC = $(K_e \\times W_e) + (K_p \\times W_p) + (K_d \\times W_d)$\n\nWACC = $(23 \\times 0.50) + (14 \\times 0.125) + (9 \\times 0.375)$\n\nWACC = $11.5\\% + 1.75\\% + 3.375\\% = 16.625\\%$\n\nConclusion: The company's expected return is 25%, while the overall cost of capital (WACC) is 16.625%. Since Expected Return (25%) > WACC (16.625%), the company will be profitable and the investment is acceptable."
            }
        ]
