        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-009",
        "stem": "Usha Ltd. is considering raising 10,00,000 Taka of additional capital by selling new shares. Currently, each share of the company is selling for 85 Taka and a dividend of 4 Taka per share was paid last year. The cost of issuing new shares is 2 Taka per share, and the dividend will increase at a rate of 7% per year. On the other hand, the firm has sold 10-year bonds with a face value of 1,000 Taka at 12% interest. However, currently, the bond is being sold at a 5% discount and the flotation cost per bond is 15 Taka. The company's tax rate is 40%.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Dhaka Board · 2018",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is a share?",
                "answer": "A share is the smallest unit into which the total capital of a company is divided."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is the cost of retained earnings lower than the cost of common stock? Explain.",
                "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is lower than the cost of common stock primarily because no flotation costs (underwriting, legal, or registration fees) are incurred when using internal funds. Additionally, in some contexts, the impact of personal income tax on dividends can further reduce the relative cost of retained earnings."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of issuing new shares for Usha Ltd.",
                "answer": "Calculation for Cost of New Common Stock ($K_{ns}$):\n\nCurrent Market Price ($P_0$) = 85 Taka\n\nLast year's dividend ($D_0$) = 4 Taka\n\nGrowth Rate ($g$) = 7% or 0.07\n\nFlotation Cost ($FC$) = 2 Taka\n\nNet Sale Value ($NSV$) = $P_0 - FC = 85 - 2 = 83$ Taka\n\nNext year's expected dividend ($D_1$) = $D_0(1+g) = 4(1+0.07) = 4.28$ Taka\n\nFormula:\n\n$K_{ns} = (\\frac{D_1}{NSV} + g) \\times 100$\n\n$K_{ns} = (\\frac{4.28}{83} + 0.07) \\times 100$\n\n$K_{ns} = (0.05156 + 0.07) \\times 100$\n\n$K_{ns}$ = 12.16%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Based on the stem, from which source would it be more profitable for Usha Ltd. to collect capital? Evaluate and give your opinion.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate Cost of New Common Stock\n\n$K_{ns} = 12.16\\%$ (calculated in Part C).\n\nStep 2: Calculate After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$)\n\nFace Value ($FV$) = 1,000\n\nInterest ($I$) = $1,000 \\times 12\\% = 120$\n\nSale Value ($SV$) = $1,000 - (1,000 \\times 5\\%) = 950$\n\nFlotation Cost ($FC$) = 15\n\nNet Sale Value ($NSV$) = $950 - 15 = 935$\n\nMaturity Period ($n$) = 10 years\n\nTax Rate ($T$) = 40% or 0.40\n\nFormula: $K_d = \\frac{I(1-T) + \\frac{FV - NSV}{n}}{\\frac{FV + NSV}{2}} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{120(1-0.40) + \\frac{1,000 - 935}{10}}{\\frac{1,000 + 935}{2}} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{72 + 6.5}{967.5} \\times 100 = \\frac{78.5}{967.5} \\times 100 = 8.11\\%$\n\nEvaluation:\n\nCost of New Common Stock = 12.16%\n\nCost of Debt = 8.11%\n\nOpinion: It is more profitable to collect capital from Bonds (Debt) because the cost of debt (8.11%) is significantly lower than the cost of new common stock (12.16%). This is due to the tax shield on interest and the overall lower risk profile associated with debt compared to equity."
            }
        ]
    },
