                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the average cost of capital for ABC Limited.",
                "answer": "Calculation of Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC):\n\n1. Cost of Equity ($K_e$) = 17%\n\n2. Cost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$) = 10%\n\n3. After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$) = $I(1 - T) = 14\\% \\times (1 - 0.40) = 8.4\\%$\n\nWeights ($W$):\n\nTotal Capital = 80,00,000\n\n$W_e = 40,00,000 / 80,00,000 = 0.50$\n\n$W_p = 10,00,000 / 80,00,000 = 0.125$\n\n$W_d = 30,00,000 / 80,00,000 = 0.375$\n\nWACC Formula:\n\nWACC = $(K_e \\times W_e) + (K_p \\times W_p) + (K_d \\times W_d)$\n\nWACC = $(17\\% \\times 0.50) + (10\\% \\times 0.125) + (8.4\\% \\times 0.375)$\n\nWACC = $8.5\\% + 1.25\\% + 3.15\\% = 12.9\\%$\n\nAnswer: 12.9%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "\"The company will be profitable if the financial manager's proposal is accepted\"—explain the logic of this comment.",
                "answer": "Evaluation of the Proposal:\n\nThe financial manager proposes to raise 20,00,000 Taka via 14% bonds. We must calculate the new WACC to see if the overall cost decreases.\n\nNew Total Capital: 80,00,000 + 20,00,000 = 1,00,00,000 Taka.\n\nNew Weights:\n\n$W_e = 40/100 = 0.40$\n\n$W_p = 10/100 = 0.10$\n\n$W_d = 50/100 = 0.50$ (Original 30L + New 20L)\n\nNew WACC:\n\nWACC = $(17 \\times 0.40) + (10 \\times 0.10) + (8.4 \\times 0.50)$\n\nWACC = $6.8\\% + 1.0\\% + 4.2\\% = 12\\%$\n\nConclusion: Before the proposal, the WACC was 12.9%. After accepting the proposal, the WACC drops to 12%. Since the overall cost of capital is reduced, the firm's value increases, making the proposal profitable and logical."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-012",
        "stem": "The capital structure of Super Power Co. Ltd. is as follows:\n\n*table\n| Source of Capital | Amount (Taka) |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| 13% Common Stock | 3,50,000 |\n| 12% Preferred Stock | 2,00,000 |\n| 10% Debenture | 3,00,000 |\n| **Total** | **8,50,000** |\n\nNext year, the company's expected rate of return on profit is 20%.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Rajshahi Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is the cost of debt capital?",
                "answer": "Cost of debt capital is the effective rate that a company pays on its borrowed funds, such as bonds, debentures, or loans. It is usually calculated on an after-tax basis because interest expenses are tax-deductible."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Is retained earnings cost-free? Explain.",
                "answer": "No, retained earnings is not cost-free. While there are no explicit costs like dividends or interest paid to external parties, it carries an implicit cost known as opportunity cost. This represents the return shareholders could have earned if the earnings were distributed as dividends and invested elsewhere."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) for Super Power Company.",
                "answer": "Calculation of WACC:\n\n1. Cost of Equity ($K_e$) = 13%\n\n2. Cost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$) = 12%\n\n3. Cost of Debt ($K_d$) = 10% (Note: No tax rate is provided in the stem, so pre-tax cost is used).\n\nWeights ($W$):\n\nTotal Capital = 8,50,000\n\n$W_e = 3,50,000 / 8,50,000 \\approx 0.4118$\n\n$W_p = 2,00,000 / 8,50,000 \\approx 0.2353$\n\n$W_d = 3,00,000 / 8,50,000 \\approx 0.3529$\n\nWACC Formula:\n\nWACC = $(K_e \\times W_e) + (K_p \\times W_p) + (K_d \\times W_d)$\n\nWACC = $(13\\% \\times 0.4118) + (12\\% \\times 0.2353) + (10\\% \\times 0.3529)$\n\nWACC = $5.353\\% + 2.824\\% + 3.529\\% = 11.706\\%$\n\nAnswer: 11.71% (approx)"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "If Super Power Company collected 3,50,000 Taka as a loan at 10% interest from 'Uttorbongo' Bank, how justified do you think that would be? Explain in light of the stem.",
                "answer": "Analysis of the Bank Loan Proposal:\n\nThe proposal suggests replacing or adding 3,50,000 Taka of capital with a 10% bank loan.\n\nReasoning:\n\n1. Cost Comparison: The current cost of common stock is 13%. If the company replaces this equity with a 10% bank loan, the specific cost for that portion of capital drops from 13% to 10%.\n\n2. Impact on WACC: Lowering the cost of a major component of the capital structure will result in a lower Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC).\n\n3. Profitability: The stem states the expected return (ROI) is 20%. Since the cost of the loan (10%) is significantly lower than the ROI (20%), the company will generate a positive net spread, increasing the wealth of the shareholders.\n\nConclusion: Collecting the funds from the bank is highly justified as it reduces the overall cost of capital and utilizes financial leverage to maximize returns, provided the company can manage the increased financial risk of debt."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-013",
        "stem": "AT Limited is a leather processing company. The chemicals and waste used in this work are mixed into the Buriganga River. Considering the river water, soil, and environment, the organization decided to set up a water treatment plant. For this, they need 25 lakh Taka. The company is considering a source of capital from which tax benefits can be obtained and the capital providers cannot be the real owners of the company.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is financing?",
                "answer": "Financing is the process of sourcing, collecting, and managing funds for a business or individual to meet specific objectives."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "\"There is a direct relationship between profit and liquidity\"—Do you agree? Explain.",
                "answer": "No, I do not agree. There is an inverse (opposite) relationship between liquidity and profitability. If a company keeps more cash on hand (high liquidity) to meet immediate needs, that cash remains idle and does not earn a return, which reduces profitability. Conversely, investing more cash to increase profit reduces the amount of liquid funds available."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "What type of capital collection is AT Limited considering in the stem?",
                "answer": "In the stem, AT Limited is considering Debt Capital (such as bonds or debentures). This is because the stem mentions two specific characteristics:\n\n1. Tax Benefit: Interest paid on debt is a tax-deductible expense, which reduces the company's tax burden.\n\n2. Ownership: Debt holders (creditors) provide capital but do not receive voting rights or ownership status, meaning they cannot be the \"real owners\" of the company."
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "With which concept of financing is the investment of the project mentioned in the stem related and why? Evaluate.",
                "answer": "The investment in the water treatment plant mentioned in the stem is related to the concept of Social Responsibility (or Social Financing).\n\nReasoning:\n\n1. Environmental Protection: AT Limited is investing 25 lakh Taka not for direct production, but to prevent the pollution of the Buriganga River.\n\n2. Sustainability: By installing a water treatment plant, the company is prioritizing the health of the water, soil, and environment over immediate profit maximization.\n\n3. Social Welfare: In modern finance, an organization is expected to contribute to the well-being of the society in which it operates. This investment reflects the ethical obligation of a business to mitigate its negative externalities (waste) for the greater good of the community."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-014",
        "stem": "The capital structure of SP Ltd. is given in the table below:\n\nThe capital structure of SP Ltd. is as follows:\n\n*table\n| Source of Capital | Amount |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| Common Stock Capital | 4,000 |\n| 10% Preferred Stock | 1,000 |\n| 14% Debenture | 3,000 |\n| **Total** | **8,000** |\n\nThe company's shares are currently selling in the market for 20 Taka. It is expected that the company will pay a dividend of 2 Taka per share next year, which will grow at a rate of 7% constantly. The company's tax rate is 50%.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Dinajpur Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is meant by cost of capital?",
                "answer": "Cost of capital is the minimum rate of return a company must earn on its investments to maintain the market value of its shares and satisfy its investors (debt holders and shareholders)."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Explain why the cost of retained earnings is less than the cost of new common stock capital.",
                "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is lower than the cost of new common stock primarily because the company does not incur flotation costs (like underwriting fees, brokerage, and legal expenses) when using internal funds. Furthermore, the net proceeds from new shares are reduced by these costs, which mathematically increases the required rate of return compared to retained earnings."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) for SP Ltd.",
                "answer": "Calculation of individual costs:\n\n1. Cost of Equity ($K_e$):\n\nMarket Price ($P_0$) = 20; Next Dividend ($D_1$) = 2; Growth ($g$) = 7% or 0.07.\n\n$K_e = (\\frac{D_1}{P_0} + g) \\times 100 = (\\frac{2}{20} + 0.07) \\times 100 = 17\\%$\n\n2. Cost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$): 10%\n\n3. After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$):\n\nInterest ($I$) = 14%; Tax ($T$) = 50% or 0.50.\n\n$K_d = I(1 - T) = 14\\% \\times (1 - 0.50) = 7\\%$\n\nWeights ($W$):\n\nTotal Capital = 8,000.\n\n$W_e = \\frac{4,000}{8,000} = 0.5$; $W_p = \\frac{1,000}{8,000} = 0.125$; $W_d = \\frac{3,000}{8,000} = 0.375$.\n\nWACC Formula:\n\nWACC = $(K_e \\times W_e) + (K_p \\times W_p) + (K_d \\times W_d)$\n\nWACC = $(17\\% \\times 0.5) + (10\\% \\times 0.125) + (7\\% \\times 0.375)$\n\nWACC = $8.5\\% + 1.25\\% + 2.625\\% = 12.375\\%$\n\nAnswer: 12.38%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "If the company collects an additional 2,000 Taka through 14% debentures, analyze the impact it will have on the Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC).",
                "answer": "Calculation of New WACC:\n\nNew Total Capital = 8,000 + 2,000 = 10,000 Taka.\n\nNew Weights:\n\n$W_e = \\frac{4,000}{10,000} = 0.40$\n\n$W_p = \\frac{1,000}{10,000} = 0.10$\n\n$W_d = \\frac{3,000 + 2,000}{10,000} = 0.50$\n\nNew WACC calculation:\n\nWACC = $(17\\% \\times 0.40) + (10\\% \\times 0.10) + (7\\% \\times 0.50)$\n\nWACC = $6.8\\% + 1.0\\% + 3.5\\% = 11.3\\%$\n\nAnalysis:\n\nThe original WACC was 12.375%. After adding more debt (which has the lowest individual cost of 7% due to the tax shield), the overall WACC decreases to 11.3%.\n\nImpact: The inclusion of more low-cost debt capital reduces the company's average cost of funds, which generally increases the value of the firm and the wealth of shareholders, provided the financial risk remains manageable."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-015",
        "stem": "The sources of capital for Beta Limited are as follows:\n\n*table\n| Source of Capital | Weight | Cost |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Common Stock | 50% | - |\n| Preferred Stock | 20% | 10% |\n| Debenture | 25% | 15% |\n| Retained Earnings | 5% | - |\n| **Total** | **100%** | |",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Comilla Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is flotation cost?",
                "answer": "Flotation cost refers to the total cost incurred by a company when issuing new securities (like stocks or bonds) to the public, including underwriting fees, legal fees, and registration charges."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is debt capital considered the cheapest source of fund?",
                "answer": "Debt capital is considered the cheapest source of fund primarily because interest payments on debt are tax-deductible, which reduces the company's net tax liability. Additionally, debt is less risky for investors than equity, so they require a lower rate of return."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of common stock for Beta Limited.",
                "answer": "Calculation for Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$):\n\nWe use the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) since Beta, Risk-free rate, and Market rate are given.\n\nRisk-free rate ($R_f$) = 10%\n\nMarket rate ($R_m$) = 15%\n\nBeta ($\\beta$) = 0.50\n\nFormula:\n\n$K_e = R_f + (R_m - R_f) \\times \\beta$\n\n$K_e = 10\\% + (15\\% - 10\\%) \\times 0.50$\n\n$K_e = 10\\% + (5\\% \\times 0.50)$\n\n$K_e = 10\\% + 2.5\\% = 12.5\\%$\n\nAnswer: 12.5%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Will Beta Limited be able to keep their Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) within 12%? Give your opinion.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate individual costs\n\n1. Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$) = 12.5% (from Part C).\n\n2. Cost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$) = 10%.\n\n3. After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$):\n\n$K_d = I(1 - T) = 15\\% \\times (1 - 0.37) = 9.45\\%$.\n\n4. Cost of Retained Earnings ($K_r$):\n\nFormula: $K_r = K_e(1 - T_p)$\n\n$K_r = 12.5\\% \\times (1 - 0.25) = 9.375\\%$.\n\nStep 2: Calculate WACC\n\nWACC = $(K_e \\times W_e) + (K_p \\times W_p) + (K_d \\times W_d) + (K_r \\times W_r)$\n\nWACC = $(12.5 \\times 0.50) + (10 \\times 0.20) + (9.45 \\times 0.25) + (9.375 \\times 0.05)$\n\nWACC = $6.25\\% + 2.0\\% + 2.3625\\% + 0.46875\\% = 11.08125\\%$\n\nOpinion: Yes, Beta Limited will be able to keep its WACC within 12% because the calculated average cost is approximately 11.08%, which is lower than the target limit."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-016",
        "stem": "Rupsa Company Ltd. has a common stock capital of 50 crore Taka. The market price of common stock is 140 Taka. This year, the company paid a dividend of 14 Taka per share to common stockholders, and historically, dividends paid by the company have increased at a rate of 5%. The tax rate is 40%. The company needs an additional 50 crore Taka for investment in a new project. The company must collect funds from one of the following two options:\n\n**Option-1:** Issuing 10-year bonds at 15% interest rate where the face value of each bond is 1,000 Taka and the market price is 1,100 Taka.\n\n**Option-2:** Funds can be collected by issuing 13% perpetual preferred stock. The market price of preferred stock is 100 Taka. Flotation cost is 2 Taka.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2017",
        "type": "board",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is the cost of capital?",
                "answer": "Cost of capital is the minimum required rate of return that a company must earn on its investment projects to satisfy its investors and maintain the market value of its shares."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is preferred stock called a hybrid security?",
                "answer": "Preferred stock is called a hybrid security because it possesses characteristics of both common stock and debt. Like debt, it usually pays a fixed rate of return (dividend) and has a higher claim on assets than common stock. Like common stock, the dividend is not a legal obligation and does not have a fixed maturity date."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of common stock for Rupsa Company Ltd.",
                "answer": "Calculation for Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$):\n\nCurrent Market Price ($P_0$) = 140 Taka\n\nCurrent Dividend ($D_0$) = 14 Taka\n\nGrowth Rate ($g$) = 5% or 0.05\n\nExpected Dividend ($D_1$) = $D_0(1 + g) = 14(1 + 0.05) = 14.70$ Taka\n\nFormula: $K_e = (\\frac{D_1}{P_0} + g) \\times 100$\n\n$K_e = (\\frac{14.70}{140} + 0.05) \\times 100$\n\n$K_e = (0.105 + 0.05) \\times 100 = 15.5\\%$\n\nAnswer: 15.5%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Which option would be profitable for Rupsa Company Ltd. to adopt for collecting funds? Analyze in light of the stem.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$) for Option-1\n\nFace Value ($FV$) = 1,000; Market Price ($P_0$) = 1,100; Interest ($I$) = $1,000 \\times 15\\% = 150$; Years ($n$) = 10; Tax ($T$) = 40%\n\nFormula: $K_d = \\frac{I(1-T) + \\frac{FV - P_0}{n}}{\\frac{FV + P_0}{2}} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{150(1-0.40) + \\frac{1,000 - 1,100}{10}}{\\frac{1,000 + 1,100}{2}} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{90 - 10}{1,050} \\times 100 = 7.62\\%$\n\nStep 2: Calculate Cost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$) for Option-2\n\nDividend ($D_p$) = $100 \\times 13\\% = 13$; Market Price ($P_0$) = 100; Flotation Cost ($FC$) = 2\n\nNet Sale Value ($NSV$) = $100 - 2 = 98$\n\nFormula: $K_p = \\frac{D_p}{NSV} \\times 100 = \\frac{13}{98} \\times 100 = 13.27\\%$\n\nAnalysis: The cost of Option-1 (7.62%) is significantly lower than the cost of Option-2 (13.27%).\n\nConclusion: Rupsa Company Ltd. should choose Option-1 (Bonds) as it is the more profitable choice due to the lower cost of capital."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-017",
        "stem": "The current market price of Meghna Company's share is 200 Taka. It pays a dividend of 15 Taka per share. The company's dividends grow at an average rate of 5%. In this case, the company's required rate of return is 20%.",
