                "answer": "Calculation with Reduced Market Price:\n\nNew Market Price ($P'_0$) = $200 - 20 = 180$ Taka\n\nExpected Dividend ($D_1$) = 15.75 Taka\n\nGrowth Rate ($g$) = 0.05\n\nNew Cost of Equity ($K'_e$):\n\n$K'_e = (\\frac{15.75}{180} + 0.05) \\times 100$\n\n$K'_e = (0.0875 + 0.05) \\times 100 = 13.75\\%$\n\nImpact Analysis:\n\n1. Initial cost of equity = 12.875%\n\n2. New cost of equity = 13.75%\n\n3. Increase in cost = $13.75\\% - 12.875\\% = 0.875\\%$\n\nEvaluation: There is an inverse relationship between market price and the cost of capital. When the market price decreases while dividends remain constant, investors require a higher percentage return on their investment. Therefore, the cost of common stock capital increases."
