    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-021",
        "stem": "The sources of capital for Sigma Limited are as follows:\n\n*table\n| Source of Capital | Weight | Cost |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Common Stock | 50% | - |\n| Preferred Stock | 20% | 10% |\n| Debenture | 25% | 15% |\n| Retained Earnings | 5% | - |\n| **Total** | **100%** | |\n\nOther Information: The firm's unavoidable risk (Beta) is 0.75. The risk-free rate of return is 10% and the market rate of return is 15%. The company's corporate tax rate is 35% and personal tax rate is 25%.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Notre Dame College · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is flotation cost?",
                "answer": "Flotation cost refers to the total expenses incurred by a company when issuing new securities (such as stocks or bonds) to the public, including underwriting fees, legal fees, brokerage, and registration charges."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is debt capital considered the cheapest source of capital?",
                "answer": "Debt capital is considered the cheapest source because interest payments on debt are tax-deductible expenses. This tax shield reduces the effective cost to the company. Additionally, debt is less risky for investors compared to equity, so they demand a lower rate of return."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of common stock for Sigma Limited.",
                "answer": "Calculation of Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$):\n\nWe use the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) as Beta and Market rates are provided.\n\nRisk-free rate ($R_f$) = 10%\n\nMarket rate ($R_m$) = 15%\n\nBeta ($\\beta$) = 0.75\n\nFormula:\n\n$K_e = R_f + (R_m - R_f) \\times \\beta$\n\n$K_e = 10\\% + (15\\% - 10\\%) \\times 0.75$\n\n$K_e = 10\\% + (5\\% \\times 0.75)$\n\n$K_e = 10\\% + 3.75\\% = 13.75\\%$\n\nAnswer: 13.75%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Will Sigma Limited be able to keep their Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) within 13%? Give your opinion.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate individual costs\n\n1. Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$) = 13.75% (from Part C).\n\n2. Cost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$) = 10%.\n\n3. After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$):\n\n$K_d = I(1 - T) = 15\\% \\times (1 - 0.35) = 9.75\\%$.\n\n4. Cost of Retained Earnings ($K_r$):\n\n$K_r = K_e(1 - T_p) = 13.75\\% \\times (1 - 0.25) = 10.3125\\%$.\n\nStep 2: Calculate WACC\n\nWACC = $(K_e \\times W_e) + (K_p \\times W_p) + (K_d \\times W_d) + (K_r \\times W_r)$\n\nWACC = $(13.75\\% \\times 0.50) + (10\\% \\times 0.20) + (9.75\\% \\times 0.25) + (10.3125\\% \\times 0.05)$\n\nWACC = $6.875\\% + 2.0\\% + 2.4375\\% + 0.515625\\% = 11.828125\\%$\n\nOpinion: Yes, Sigma Limited will be able to keep their WACC within 13%. The calculated WACC is approximately 11.83%, which is well below the 13% limit."
            }
        ]
