                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the after-tax cost of debt capital for Sayma Ltd. as described in the stem.",
                "answer": "Calculation of After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$):\n\nFace Value ($FV$) = 1,000 Taka\n\nCoupon Rate = 15%\n\nInterest ($I$) = $1,000 \\times 15\\% = 150$ Taka\n\nDiscount = 10% of 1,000 = 100 Taka\n\nNet Sale Value ($NSV$) = $1,000 - 100 = 900$ Taka\n\nTax Rate ($T$) = 40% or 0.40\n\nFormula for Irredeemable Debt:\n\n$K_d = \\frac{I(1 - T)}{NSV} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{150(1 - 0.40)}{900} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{150 \\times 0.60}{900} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{90}{900} \\times 100 = 10\\%$\n\nAnswer: 10%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "If Sayma Ltd. sells the debentures at a 10% premium, what will be the impact on the cost of debt? Analyze.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate $K_d$ at 10% Premium\n\nInterest ($I$) = 150 Taka\n\nPremium = 10% of 1,000 = 100 Taka\n\nNew Net Sale Value ($NSV$) = $1,000 + 100 = 1,100$ Taka\n\n$K_d = \\frac{150(1 - 0.40)}{1,100} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{90}{1,100} \\times 100 \\approx 8.18\\%$\n\nStep 2: Analysis\n\n- Cost at 10% Discount = 10%\n\n- Cost at 10% Premium = 8.18%\n\nConclusion: If the debentures are sold at a premium, the cost of debt decreases. This is because the company receives more capital ($NSV$ increases) for the same fixed interest payment, thereby spreading the cost over a larger amount of funds and making the financing more economical."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-028",
        "stem": "The amount of capital is 20,00,000 Taka in Common Stock; 5,00,000 Taka in 14% Preferred Stock; and 15,00,000 Taka in 15% Debenture. Rusha Company's Beta value is 2, the market portfolio rate of return is 15%, and the risk-free rate of return is 7%. The corporate tax rate is 40%. The company's expected rate of return is 25%. The financial manager considers the overall cost of capital for investment.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Cantonment College, Jashore · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is flotation cost?",
                "answer": "Flotation cost refers to the total expenses incurred by a company when issuing new securities to the public, such as underwriting fees, legal fees, and brokerage."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "\"The cost of retained earnings is not always equal to the cost of common stock.\" Explain the statement.",
                "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is generally equal to the cost of common stock, but they differ if there are personal taxes or flotation costs. When a company issues new common stock, it must pay flotation costs, making the cost of new equity higher than the cost of retained earnings. Additionally, if shareholders pay personal income tax on dividends, the opportunity cost (cost of retained earnings) is adjusted downward."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of common stock for the company.",
                "answer": "Calculation of Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$):\n\nWe use the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) as Beta is provided.\n\nRisk-free rate ($R_f$) = 7%\n\nMarket rate ($R_m$) = 15%\n\nBeta ($\\beta$) = 2\n\nFormula:\n\n$K_e = R_f + (R_m - R_f) \\times \\beta$\n\n$K_e = 7\\% + (15\\% - 7\\%) \\times 2$\n\n$K_e = 7\\% + (8\\% \\times 2)$\n\n$K_e = 7\\% + 16\\% = 23\\%$\n\nAnswer: 23%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Will the company be profitable if it invests using the current capital structure? Comment through mathematical analysis.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate individual costs\n\n1. Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$) = 23%\n\n2. Cost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$) = 14%\n\n3. After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$):\n\n$K_d = I(1 - T) = 15\\% \\times (1 - 0.40) = 9\\%$.\n\nStep 2: Calculate Weights\n\nTotal Capital = 20,00,000 + 5,00,000 + 15,00,000 = 40,00,000\n\n$W_e = 20/40 = 0.50$\n\n$W_p = 5/40 = 0.125$\n\n$W_d = 15/40 = 0.375$\n\nStep 3: Calculate WACC\n\nWACC = $(23\\% \\times 0.50) + (14\\% \\times 0.125) + (9\\% \\times 0.375)$\n\nWACC = $11.5\\% + 1.75\\% + 3.375\\% = 16.625\\%$\n\nConclusion: The company's expected rate of return (25%) is higher than its Weighted Average Cost of Capital (16.63%). Therefore, the company will be profitable if it invests using this capital structure."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-029",
        "stem": "The current capital structure of the company is:\n\n*table\n| Source of Capital | Amount (Taka) |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| Common Stock | 7,00,000 |\n| 15% Preferred Stock | 3,00,000 |\n| **Total** | **10,00,000** |",
