            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What is meant by opportunity cost? Explain.",
                "answer": "Opportunity cost is the value or benefit lost by choosing one alternative over another. In finance, if a company invests its funds in a specific project, the return it could have earned by investing that same money in the next best available project is considered the opportunity cost."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of common stock of the company.",
                "answer": "Calculation of Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$):\n\nGiven,\n\nRisk-free rate ($R_f$) = 6%\n\nMarket return rate ($R_m$) = 16%\n\nBeta ($\\beta$) = 1.6\n\nFormula (CAPM):\n\n$K_e = R_f + (R_m - R_f) \\times \\beta$\n\n$K_e = 6\\% + (16\\% - 6\\%) \\times 1.6$\n\n$K_e = 6\\% + (10\\% \\times 1.6)$\n\n$K_e = 6\\% + 16\\% = 22\\%$\n\nAnswer: 22%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Should the company invest in the new project? Give your answer with mathematical logic.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate individual costs\n\n1. Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$) = 22%\n\n2. Cost of Preferred Stock ($K_p$):\n\nDividend ($D_p$) = $100 \\times 15\\% = 15$ Taka\n\nMarket Price ($P_p$) = 130 Taka\n\n$K_p = (15 / 130) \\times 100 = 11.54\\%$\n\n3. After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$):\n\n$K_d = I(1 - T) = 17\\% \\times (1 - 0.40) = 10.2\\%$\n\nStep 2: Calculate New Total Capital\n\nTotal Capital = 7,00,000 + 3,00,000 + 2,00,000 = 12,00,000 Taka.\n\nStep 3: Calculate WACC\n\nWeights: $W_e = 7/12 = 0.5833$; $W_p = 3/12 = 0.25$; $W_d = 2/12 = 0.1667$\n\nWACC = $(22\\% \\times 0.5833) + (11.54\\% \\times 0.25) + (10.2\\% \\times 0.1667)$\n\nWACC = $12.83\\% + 2.89\\% + 1.70\\% = 17.42\\%$\n\nConclusion: The return rate of the new project is 15%, while the overall cost of capital (WACC) is 17.42%. Since the cost is higher than the return, the company should not invest in the new project as it would result in a net loss."
            }
