    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-031",
        "stem": "Satata Limited needs 10,00,000 Taka of additional capital and is considering selling new shares. Currently, each share of the company is selling for 85 Taka. Last year, the company paid a dividend of 4 Taka per share, which is expected to grow at a rate of 7%. The flotation cost for issuing new shares is 2 Taka per share. On the other hand, the company is selling 10-year bonds with a face value of 1,000 Taka at 12% interest. However, the bond is being sold at a 5% discount, and the flotation cost per bond is 15 Taka. The company's tax rate is 40%.",
        "stemImage": "",
        "meta": "Abdul Kadir Mollah City College, Narsingdi · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is optimal capital structure?",
                "answer": "Optimal capital structure is the specific mix of debt and equity that minimizes a company's Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) while maximizing the overall market value of the firm."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "Why is the cost of retained earnings lower than the cost of common stock?",
                "answer": "The cost of retained earnings is lower than the cost of common stock primarily because of flotation costs. When a company issues new common shares, it must pay underwriting fees, legal fees, and other issuance expenses. Retained earnings are internal funds, so no such flotation costs are incurred, making them a cheaper source of equity."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of issuing new shares for Satata Limited.",
                "answer": "Calculation of Cost of New Common Stock ($K_e$):\n\nCurrent Market Price ($P_0$) = 85 Taka\n\nLast year's dividend ($D_0$) = 4 Taka\n\nGrowth rate ($g$) = 7% or 0.07\n\nFlotation cost ($f$) = 2 Taka\n\nNet Sale Value ($NSV$) = $P_0 - f = 85 - 2 = 83$ Taka\n\nNext year's expected dividend ($D_1$) = $D_0(1+g) = 4(1+0.07) = 4.28$ Taka\n\nFormula:\n\n$K_e = (\\frac{D_1}{NSV} + g) \\times 100$\n\n$K_e = (\\frac{4.28}{83} + 0.07) \\times 100$\n\n$K_e = (0.05156 + 0.07) \\times 100 = 12.16\\%$\n\nAnswer: 12.16%"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Based on the stem, from which source would it be more profitable for Satata Limited to collect capital? Give your opinion.",
                "answer": "Step 1: Calculate After-tax Cost of Debt ($K_d$)\n\nFace Value ($FV$) = 1,000 Taka\n\nRedemption Value ($RV$) = 1,000 Taka (assumed at par)\n\nInterest ($I$) = $1,000 \\times 12\\% = 120$ Taka\n\nDiscount = $1,000 \\times 5\\% = 50$ Taka\n\nNet Sale Value ($NSV$) = $1,000 - 50 - 15 = 935$ Taka\n\nMaturity ($n$) = 10 years, Tax ($T$) = 40%\n\nFormula for Redeemable Debt:\n\n$K_d = \\frac{I(1-T) + \\frac{RV-NSV}{n}}{\\frac{RV+NSV}{2}} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{120(1-0.4) + \\frac{1000-935}{10}}{\\frac{1000+935}{2}} \\times 100$\n\n$K_d = \\frac{72 + 6.5}{967.5} \\times 100 = \\frac{78.5}{967.5} \\times 100 = 8.11\\%$\n\nStep 2: Analysis\n\n- Cost of New Equity ($K_e$) = 12.16%\n\n- Cost of Debt ($K_d$) = 8.11%\n\nConclusion: It would be more profitable for Satata Limited to collect capital from Bonds (Debt). This is because the cost of debt (8.11%) is significantly lower than the cost of new common shares (12.16%) due to the tax-deductibility of interest."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "fin1-ch7-cq-032",
        "stem": "The capital structure of Alpha Ltd. is as follows:\n\n*table\n| Source of Capital | Amount (Taka) |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| Common Stock (100 Taka each) | 20,00,000 |\n| 10% Preferred Stock | 12,00,000 |\n| 16% Debt Capital | 8,00,000 |\n| **Total** | **40,00,000** |",
