        "meta": "Government Commerce College, Chattogram · 2026",
        "type": "college",
        "questions": [
            {
                "label": "a",
                "text": "What is cost of capital?",
                "answer": "Cost of capital is the minimum rate of return that a business must earn on its investments to satisfy its investors (stockholders and debt holders) and maintain its market value."
            },
            {
                "label": "b",
                "text": "What impact does flotation cost have on the cost of newly issued shares? Explain.",
                "answer": "Flotation cost increases the cost of newly issued shares. When a company issues new shares, it incurs expenses such as underwriting fees, legal fees, and brokerage. These costs reduce the net proceeds ($NSV$) received from the sale, and since $NSV$ is the denominator in the cost of equity formula, the total percentage cost of that capital increases."
            },
            {
                "label": "c",
                "text": "Calculate the cost of common stock and the cost of debt capital for Alpha Ltd.",
                "answer": "1. Calculation of Cost of Common Stock ($K_e$):\n\nCurrent Dividend ($D_0$) = 10 Taka\n\nGrowth Rate ($g$) = 5% or 0.05\n\nCurrent Market Price ($P_0$) = 120 Taka\n\nExpected Dividend ($D_1$) = $D_0(1 + g) = 10(1 + 0.05) = 10.5$ Taka\n\nFormula: $K_e = (\\frac{D_1}{P_0} + g) \\times 100$\n\n$K_e = (\\frac{10.5}{120} + 0.05) \\times 100 = 13.75\\%$\n\n2. Calculation of Cost of Debt ($K_d$):\n\nInterest Rate ($I$) = 16%\n\nTax Rate ($T$) = 40% or 0.40\n\nFormula: $K_d = I(1 - T)$\n\n$K_d = 16(1 - 0.40) = 9.6\\%$"
            },
            {
                "label": "d",
                "text": "Calculate the average cost of capital according to the manager's advice and give your opinion.",
                "answer": "Step 1: New Capital Mix\n\n50% of Debt (4,00,000 Taka) converted to Common Stock.\n\nNew Common Stock = 20,00,000 + 4,00,000 = 24,00,000 Taka\n\nPreferred Stock = 12,00,000 Taka\n\nRemaining Debt = 4,00,000 Taka\n\nTotal Capital = 40,00,000 Taka\n\nStep 2: Determine Weights ($W$)\n\n$W_e = 24/40 = 0.60$\n\n$W_p = 12/40 = 0.30$\n\n$W_d = 4/40 = 0.10$\n\nStep 3: Calculate New WACC\n\nWACC = $(K_e \\times W_e) + (K_p \\times W_p) + (K_d \\times W_d)$\n\nWACC = $(13.75\\% \\times 0.60) + (10\\% \\times 0.30) + (9.6\\% \\times 0.10)$\n\nWACC = $8.25\\% + 3.0\\% + 0.96\\% = 12.21\\%$\n\nOpinion: The manager's advice is not beneficial. The current WACC is 11.8%, but after following the advice, it increases to 12.21%. This is because debt is a cheaper source of finance due to tax benefits, and replacing it with more expensive equity capital raises the overall cost."
            }
        ]
    }
