    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Limitations of capital budgeting: (i) Change in demand (ii) Change in cost (iii) Change in cost of capital.</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Uncertainty in future demand, costs, and interest rates makes long-term forecasting difficult.</p>",
        "id": 4813
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is obtained by dividing initial investment by annual equal cash inflow?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "ARR",
            "Payback Period (PBP)",
            "NPV",
            "IRR"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$$PBP = \\text{Initial Investment} / \\text{Annual Cash Inflow}$$ (for equal cash flows).</p>",
        "id": 4814
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>At what discount rate does the <code>PV</code> of cash inflows equal the cash outflows?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong Board · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "ARR",
            "IRR",
            "Pre-tax rate",
            "After-tax rate"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Internal Rate of Return (<code>IRR</code>) is the rate where N<code>PV</code> becomes exactly zero.</p>",
        "id": 4815
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which is a traditional technique of capital budgeting?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Payback Period",
            "NPV",
            "IRR",
            "Discounted PBP"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>PBP and ARR are traditional/non-discounted methods.</p>",
        "id": 4816
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Investing in profitable long-term projects is called:</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Capital Budgeting",
            "Cost of Capital",
            "Time Value of Money",
            "Capital Structure"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Capital budgeting is the decision-making process for long-term investments.</p>",
        "id": 4817
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is it called when accepting one project results in rejecting another?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Complementary",
            "Independent",
            "Dependent",
            "Mutually Exclusive"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Mutually exclusive projects compete for the same resource; only one can be chosen.</p>",
        "id": 4818
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Discounted methods in capital budgeting include: (i) N<code>PV</code> (ii) <code>IRR</code> (iii) PBP.</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>N<code>PV</code> and <code>IRR</code> use discounted cash flows; standard PBP does not.</p>",
        "id": 4819
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Subtracting tax from total profit results in:</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Total Profit",
            "Net Profit",
            "Cash Inflow",
            "Depreciation"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Net Profit (<code>EAT</code>) is the residual income after all expenses and taxes are paid.</p>",
        "id": 4820
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the first step in the capital budgeting process?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal Board · 2025",
