    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Limitation of <code>IRR</code>: (i) Complex to solve (ii) Easy decision for multiple <code>IRR</code> (iii) Considers TVM.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Multiple <code>IRR</code> makes decision making harder, not easier (ii is incorrect).</p>",
        "id": 5119
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Raihan divides profit by 5 years and investment by 2. This method is:</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "ARR",
            "PBP",
            "NPV",
            "IRR"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>These are the exact steps for Accounting Rate of Return.</p>",
        "id": 5120
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Based on Mr. Raihan's stimulus, which is correct?</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Method 1 uses TVM",
            "Method 2 ignores rates",
            "Method 1 uses different divisors",
            "Method 2 is equal"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Method 1 (ARR) uses 'n' for profit and '2' for investment.</p>",
        "id": 5121
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Allocating capital based on project priority is called:</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "Budgeting",
            "Cost Control",
            "Capital Rationing",
            "Revenue"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Capital Rationing is prioritizing projects due to limited funds.</p>",
        "id": 5122
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Problems in Capital Budgeting: (i) Uncertainty (ii) No change in demand (iii) Cost change.</p>",
        "meta": "- · -",
        "type": "-",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Constant demand (ii) is not a problem; uncertainty and cost fluctuations are.</p>",
        "id": 5123
    }], shortCQData: [], fullCQData: [] },
        "9": { subjectName: "Finance 1st Paper", chapterName: "Chapter 9 : Risk and Return", mcqData: [{
        "text": "<p>Delta Ltd: Risk-free rate 8%, Market return 12%, Beta 1.5. What is the Market Risk Premium?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "3%",
            "4%",
            "5%",
            "6%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$Market\\ Risk\\ Premium = R_m - R_f = 12\\% - 8\\% = 4\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5124
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Delta Ltd: Risk-free rate 8%, Market return 12%, Beta 1.5. What is the Expected Rate of Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "14%",
            "15%",
            "16%",
            "17%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$E(R) = 8\\% + 1.5(12\\% - 8\\%) = 8\\% + 6\\% = 14\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5125
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Assumptions of CAPM: (i) No inflation (ii) Efficient capital market (iii) No income tax.</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three are standard theoretical assumptions of the CAPM model.</p>",
        "id": 5126
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which risk arises when the value of domestic currency falls against foreign currency?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Liquidity Risk",
            "Interest Rate Risk",
            "Exchange Rate Risk",
            "Company Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Fluctuations in currency values create Exchange Rate Risk.</p>",
        "id": 5127
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the possibility of financial loss in an event called?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Risk",
            "Uncertainty",
            "Rate of Profit",
            "Rate of Loss"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Risk is the measurable possibility of financial loss or deviation.</p>",
        "id": 5128
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Beta 0.75, Rf 6%, Rm 11%. What is the Expected Rate of Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "5%",
            "6%",
            "9.75%",
            "11%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$E(R) = 6\\% + 0.75(11\\% - 6\\%) = 6\\% + 3.75\\% = 9.75\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5129
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which risk arises from the inability to pay interest on debt?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Market Risk",
            "Financial Risk",
            "Liquidity Risk",
            "Business Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Financial risk is specifically linked to the use of debt and interest obligations.</p>",
        "id": 5130
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the standard value of Market Beta?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "-1",
            "0",
            "0.5",
            "1"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>The beta of the overall market portfolio is always defined as 1.0.</p>",
        "id": 5131
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which security is free from bankruptcy/default risk?</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Income Bond",
            "Treasury Bond",
            "Corporate Bond",
            "Municipal Bond"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Government-issued Treasury bonds are considered default-risk free.</p>",
        "id": 5132
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Assumptions of CAPM: (i) No inflation (ii) Efficient market (iii) No tax.</p>",
        "meta": "Chittagong · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Repeated board question confirming CAPM theoretical conditions.</p>",
        "id": 5133
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Profit made from an increase in the price of a share is called:</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Net Profit",
            "Capital Gain",
            "Revenue Profit",
            "Total Profit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$Capital\\ Gain = Selling\\ Price - Buying\\ Price$.</p>",
        "id": 5134
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which type of risk arises from economic uncertainty?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Business Risk",
            "Financial Risk",
            "Liquidity Risk",
            "Market Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Market risk (Systematic risk) stems from broad economic factors.</p>",
        "id": 5135
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Jawad invests in Co A (60k) and Co B (40k). This achieves:</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Expense Increase",
            "Risk Reduction",
            "Liquidity Deficit",
            "Profit Increase"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>This is diversification, which reduces unsystematic risk.</p>",
        "id": 5136
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>A: 60k (10%), B: 40k (12%). What is the Portfolio Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "10.80%",
            "11.20%",
            "12%",
            "12.40%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$(0.6 \\times 10\\%) + (0.4 \\times 12\\%) = 6\\% + 4.8\\% = 10.8\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5137
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Full form of CAPM:</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Capital Asset Product Model",
            "Capital Asset Pricing Model",
            "Capital Asset Pricing Method",
            "Capital Asset Product Method"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Capital Asset Pricing Model.</p>",
        "id": 5138
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The difference between market return and risk-free return is:</p>",
        "meta": "Barisal · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Company Risk",
            "Risk Premium",
            "Market Risk",
            "Expected Return"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$Risk\\ Premium = R_m - R_f$.</p>",
        "id": 5139
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the source of Financial Risk?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Debt Capital",
            "Share Capital",
            "Economic Capital",
            "Inflation"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Financial risk exists only when a firm uses debt (fixed financial charges).</p>",
        "id": 5140
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Buy 200, Sell 250, Dividend 10. What is the Rate of Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "30%",
            "40%",
            "50%",
            "60%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>$[(250-200)+10]/200 = 60/200 = 30\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5141
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Buy 200, Sell 230 (20 less), Div 10: (i) Return 20% (ii) Total profit 40 (iii) Return 25%.</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i & ii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Profit = $30+10=40$. Rate = $40/200 = 20\\%$. So, i & ii are correct.</p>",
        "id": 5142
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which type of risk is within the investor's control?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Financial Risk",
            "Market Risk",
            "Speculative Risk",
            "Political Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Unsystematic risks (like financial/business risk) can be controlled via diversification.</p>",
        "id": 5143
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Q Ltd: Rf 5%, Rm 15%, Beta 1.5. What is the Market Risk Premium?</p>",
        "meta": "Dinajpur · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "5%",
            "10%",
            "15%",
            "20%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$Market\\ Risk\\ Premium = R_m - R_f = 15\\% - 5\\% = 10\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5144
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is measured by Beta ($\\beta$)?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Market Risk",
            "Unique Risk",
            "Financial Risk",
            "Total Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Beta measures systematic risk or Market Risk.</p>",
        "id": 5145
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If the average returns of two securities are equal, which is the best method to measure risk?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Standard Deviation",
            "Beta",
            "Coefficient of Variation",
            "Range"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Standard Deviation is the primary tool for absolute risk measurement.</p>",
        "id": 5146
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the relative expression of risk called?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Coefficient of Variation",
            "Probability",
            "Standard Deviation",
            "Average Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Coefficient of Variation (CV) measures risk relative to return.</p>",
        "id": 5147
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Beta 1.90, Market Return 11%, Risk-free Rate 8%. Expected Rate of Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "10.70%",
            "11.70%",
            "12.70%",
            "13.70%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$E(R) = 8\\% + 1.90(11\\% - 8\\%) = 8\\% + 5.7\\% = 13.70\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5148
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If market return increases from 11% to 13%, what is the change in Expected Return (Beta 1.90)?</p>",
        "meta": "Mymensingh · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "6.10% Increase",
            "7.10% Decrease",
            "8.30% Decrease",
            "3.80% Increase"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Change = $\\beta \\times \\Delta R_m = 1.90 \\times (13\\%-11\\%) = 3.80\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5149
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>In which year did Markowitz propose the Portfolio Theory?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "1913",
            "1920",
            "1950",
            "1952"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Harry Markowitz published \"Portfolio Selection\" in 1952.</p>",
        "id": 5150
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the possibility of loss called?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Uncertainty",
            "Risk",
            "Net Loss",
            "Total Loss"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Risk is the measurable possibility of a loss.</p>",
        "id": 5151
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which risk cannot be avoided (non-diversifiable)?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Market Risk",
            "Unique Risk",
            "Independent Risk",
            "Company Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Market Risk (Systematic risk) affects everyone and cannot be diversified.</p>",
        "id": 5152
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>ABC Co: Buy 700, Div 35, Sell 840. Expected Rate of Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "20%",
            "15%",
            "10%",
            "5%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Note: This usually implies the Holding Period Return. See Q32 for details.</p>",
        "id": 5153
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Kafi: Buy 700, Sell 840. What is the Capital Gain Percentage?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "15%",
            "20%",
            "25%",
            "30%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$[(840 - 700) / 700] \\times 100 = 20\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5154
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Kafi: Buy 700, Div 35, Sell 840. Total Rate of Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "10%",
            "15%",
            "20%",
            "25%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$[(840 - 700) + 35] / 700 = 175 / 700 = 25\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5155
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which one is an insurable risk?</p>",
        "meta": "Rajshahi · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Human Risk",
            "Business Risk",
            "Financial Risk",
            "Speculative Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Pure risks/Human risks are generally insurable; speculative risks are not.</p>",
        "id": 5156
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Inability to cover operating expenses from operating income is:</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Business Risk",
            "Financial Risk",
            "Interest Rate Risk",
            "Liquidity Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Business risk is the variability in EBIT.</p>",
        "id": 5157
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which type of risk cannot be avoided?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Business Risk",
            "Market Risk",
            "Financial Risk",
            "Portfolio Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Market risk is also known as non-diversifiable risk.</p>",
        "id": 5158
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Mr. Sabuj took a bank loan due to insufficient funds. What risk was created?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Business Risk",
            "Financial Risk",
            "Unique Risk",
            "Market Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Using debt (leverage) creates Financial Risk.</p>",
        "id": 5159
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Rf 6%, Rm 12%, Beta 0.5. Expected Rate of Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "18%",
            "9%",
            "6%",
            "3%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$E(R) = 6\\% + 0.5(12\\% - 6\\%) = 6\\% + 3\\% = 9\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5160
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Risk is: (i) Avoidable (ii) Measurable (iii) Originates from uncertainty.</p>",
        "meta": "Comilla · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>All three are fundamental characteristics of financial risk.</p>",
        "id": 5161
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Elements of Total Risk: (i) Avoidable (ii) Unavoidable (iii) Interest rate risk.</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>Total Risk = Systematic (Unavoidable) + Unsystematic (Avoidable).</p>",
        "id": 5162
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Beta 1.50, Rf 6%, Rm 14%. What is the Expected Rate of Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "17%",
            "18%",
            "19%",
            "20%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>$E(R) = 6\\% + 1.5(14\\% - 6\\%) = 6\\% + 12\\% = 18\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5163
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Returns for Security A & B are 15% and 12%. Investment in A is 60%. What is the Portfolio Expected Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "10.60%",
            "11.90%",
            "13.80%",
            "12.40%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 3,
        "explanation": "<p>$(0.6 \\times 15\\%) + (0.4 \\times 12\\%) = 9\\% + 4.8\\% = 13.80\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5164
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>FXD' Co has a return of 16% and standard deviation of 6%. What is the Coefficient of Variation (CV)?</p>",
        "meta": "Jessore · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "40.80%",
            "39.30%",
            "37.50%",
            "32.40%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$CV = (\\sigma / \\bar{R}) \\times 100 = (6 / 16) \\times 100 = 37.5\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5165
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Which risk arises due to changes in a country's economic and political conditions?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Financial Risk",
            "Liquidity Risk",
            "Market Risk",
            "Company Risk"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Systematic/Market risk stems from macroeconomic and political factors.</p>",
        "id": 5166
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Who developed the CAPM model?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Harry Markowitz",
            "Stephen Green",
            "William Sharpe",
            "Miller & Modigliani"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>William Sharpe developed CAPM based on Markowitz's theory.</p>",
        "id": 5167
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>If the market return is less than the risk-free rate, what will the Risk Premium be?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Zero",
            "Positive",
            "Negative",
            "Equal"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>$Risk\\ Premium = R_m - R_f$. If $R_m < R_f$, the result is negative.</p>",
        "id": 5168
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>XYZ Co: Beta 1.5, Avg Return 15%, Treasury Bill rate 5%. What is the Required Rate of Return?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "20%",
            "22.50%",
            "25%",
            "27.50%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 0,
        "explanation": "<p>Note: Using CAPM formula: $5 + 1.5(15-5) = 20\\%$.</p>",
        "id": 5169
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Siam Ltd. is considering two projects with an investment of TK 5,00,000 each. The cost of capital is 10%. Information for the projects is as follows:\n\nSecurity X:\n\nAnnual Cash Inflow (Years 1-5): TK 1,40,000\n\nN<code>PV</code>: TK 30,712\n\nSecurity Y:\n\nAnnual Cash Inflow (Years 1-5): TK 1,50,000\n\nN<code>PV</code>: TK 68,620\n\nQuestion        What is the Payback Period (PBP) of Project X?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "2.50%",
            "2.28%",
            "12.28%",
            "22.80%"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Derived by calculating the variance from the given probabilities/returns.</p>",
        "id": 5170
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>Regarding Security X & Y: (i) Y is less risky (ii) X is acceptable (iii) Y is high earning.</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "i & ii",
            "i & iii",
            "ii & iii",
            "i, ii & iii"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 1,
        "explanation": "<p>Based on comparing $\\sigma$ (risk) and Expected Return of both securities.</p>",
        "id": 5171
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>What is the gain resulting from an increase in share price called?</p>",
        "meta": "Sylhet · 2025",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Total Profit",
            "Net Profit",
            "Capital Gain",
            "Distributed Profit"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": 2,
        "explanation": "<p>Capital Gain is the appreciation in the asset's market value.</p>",
        "id": 5172
    },
    {
        "text": "<p>The difference between market return ($R_m$) and risk-free return ($R_f$) is:</p>",
        "meta": "Dhaka · 2023",
        "type": "board",
        "options": [
            "Company Risk",
            "Risk Premium",
            "Expected Return",
